,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the difference between a hash map (hash table) and a hash set?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A hash set stores key-value pairs with O(1) lookup by key; a hash map stores only keys with O(1) membership testing"},{"id":"b","text":"A hash set stores only keys with O(1) membership testing (contains); a hash map stores key-value pairs with O(1) lookup by key"},{"id":"c","text":"A hash set uses chaining for collisions; a hash map uses open addressing"},{"id":"d","text":"A hash set is a sorted data structure; a hash map is an unsorted data structure"}]','b','Hash set: stores unique keys, supports add, remove, contains (membership test) in O(1) average. Conceptually equivalent to a hash map with ignored values. Hash map: stores (key, value) pairs, supports O(1) lookup by key. Used for caching (key=query, value=result), deduplication (store seen items in set), counting frequencies (map[element]++). Option A reverses the definitions. Option C is not necessarily true — both can use either strategy. Option D is not a fundamental difference.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the worst-case time complexity of hash table operations with a good hash function and proper resizing?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(1) — hash tables are guaranteed O(1) in all cases"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n) — worst case occurs when all keys produce the same hash value (or all probe to the same slot), causing O(n) search within one bucket"},{"id":"c","text":"O(log n) — hash tables use a balanced tree internally when the load factor exceeds a threshold"},{"id":"d","text":"O(n log n) — hash tables require sorting when collisions occur"}]','b','Worst-case O(n) occurs when the hash function produces collisions that route all keys to the same bucket or probe sequence. This can be triggered by adversarial input designed to hash to the same value (hash flooding attack). Mitigations: universal hashing (random hash function per table), tree-based buckets (Java''s HashMap switches to red-black tree when a chain exceeds 8 elements), and consistent rebalancing. Option A overclaims — hash tables don''t have guaranteed O(1) worst case. Option C describes what some implementations do (treeify buckets), not the inherent complexity. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is a hash function''s ideal property for hash table performance?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A perfect hash function maps each distinct key to a unique bucket index with no collisions"},{"id":"b","text":"A uniform hash function distributes keys evenly across all buckets, minimizing collisions and ensuring O(1) average lookup"},{"id":"c","text":"A fast hash function computes in O(1) time regardless of key size"},{"id":"d","text":"A deterministic hash function always produces the same output for the same input"}]','b','The ideal hash function distributes keys uniformly across buckets — each bucket receives approximately n/m elements on average. This gives O(1) average search time (chaining: O(α) = O(n/m), open addressing: constant probing). A perfect hash function is a special case of uniform hashing where no collisions occur at all (only possible when the key set is static and known in advance). Option A is a perfect hash function (very rare, static sets only). Option C is desirable but not the primary performance property. Option D is a basic requirement for any hash function, not the ideal performance property.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the output of the following algorithm?

