,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is linear probing in open addressing?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Linear probing uses a second hash function to find an alternative bucket when a collision occurs"},{"id":"b","text":"Linear probing searches sequentially through adjacent buckets (h+1, h+2, ...) until an empty slot is found; simple but causes primary clustering"},{"id":"c","text":"Linear probing only works with hash sets, not hash maps"},{"id":"d","text":"Linear probing stores the original hash value along with each key to enable fast retrieval"}]','b','Open addressing: all elements stored directly in the table array. On collision at bucket h, linear probing checks h+1, h+2, ... (mod table size) until empty slot found. Search follows same probing sequence. Deletion is tricky — can''t just remove the element (would break search for elements probing through it) — requires tombstone markers. Primary clustering: long runs of consecutive occupied slots form clusters, causing increasingly long probe sequences. Quadratic probing (h+1², h+2², ...) reduces clustering but can miss empty slots. Double hashing (h + i*hash2(key)) eliminates clustering.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between separate chaining and open addressing for hash collision resolution?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Separate chaining stores all colliding keys in a linked list at each bucket (or tree for many collisions); open addressing stores all elements in a single array and finds alternative slots via probing"},{"id":"b","text":"Separate chaining uses O(1) additional memory per element; open addressing uses O(n) memory for the table"},{"id":"c","text":"Open addressing is faster for low load factors; separate chaining is faster for high load factors"},{"id":"d","text":"Separate chaining requires the hash function output range to match the number of buckets; open addressing requires the range to exceed the number of buckets"}]','a','Chaining: each bucket is a container (linked list, tree). Collisions are stored in-bucket. Search: O(α) average where α=n/m. Deletion: easy (remove from list). Memory: proportional to n+m. Open addressing: fixed array of m slots, collisions resolved by probing to next available slot. Search: must probe sequence until key found or empty slot. Deletion: complex (tombstones). Memory: m slots, α ≤ 1 typically. Chaining handles high load factors better; open addressing has better cache locality (contiguous memory). Option B reverses the space trade-offs. Option C is wrong (chaining is better at high load factors). Option D is nonsensical.')
