,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is double hashing and why is it preferred over linear probing?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Double hashing applies two hash functions sequentially and uses the second output to replace the first; faster than a single hash function"},{"id":"b","text":"Double hashing uses a second hash function to compute the probe interval (h(key) + i×h2(key)) on collision, eliminating primary and secondary clustering that plague linear probing"},{"id":"c","text":"Double hashing uses two buckets per key for redundancy, improving fault tolerance"},{"id":"d","text":"Double hashing requires two separate hash tables and alternates between them for each operation"}]','b','Double hashing: on collision at bucket h, probe sequence is h(key), h(key)+h2(key), h(key)+2×h2(key), ... mod table size, where h2(key) is a secondary hash function that must never be 0. This gives probe sequences that depend on both the primary hash and the key value, preventing clustering (keys with same primary hash still probe differently due to h2). Linear probing causes primary clustering (long chains of consecutive occupied slots). Secondary clustering (keys that collide on first hash also collide on subsequent probes) is avoided by double hashing. Option A misdescribes the mechanism. Option C is unrelated. Option D is not what double hashing means.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','When the hash table load factor approaches 1.0, the average search time degrades toward O(n). True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','As load factor α = n/m approaches 1, buckets get fuller. In chaining, average chain length = α. In open addressing, probe sequences get longer (average probes ≈ 1/(1-α)). When α ≈ 1, a single search may probe nearly all slots. Standard practice: resize when α exceeds ~0.75 (Java HashMap) or ~0.66 (Python dict), doubling bucket count, rehashing all elements (O(n) total), resetting α to a safe range. This keeps amortized O(1) per operation.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A hash set and a hash map both use hash functions and handle collisions identically. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','The collision resolution strategy (chaining vs open addressing) is a property of the hash table implementation, not the data structure type. Both hash maps and hash sets can use chaining or open addressing, depending on the implementation. Java''s HashMap and HashSet both use separate chaining with red-black tree fallback (buckets become trees when chain length > 8). Python''s dict uses open addressing with a custom probing strategy. The choice of collision resolution is independent of whether the table stores keys only or key-value pairs.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Java 8''s HashMap switches from linked-list chaining to red-black tree chaining when a bucket''s chain exceeds 8 elements. Why?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Red-black trees provide O(1) lookup in buckets with long chains, improving the overall hash map performance from O(n) to O(log n)"},{"id":"b","text":"Red-black trees provide O(log n) worst-case lookup for buckets with many collisions instead of O(n) linked-list traversal, ensuring no bucket ever degrades to O(n) under hash flooding attacks"},{"id":"c","text":"Red-black trees use less memory than linked lists when chain length exceeds 8"},{"id":"d","text":"Red-black trees are faster for short chains because treeify overhead is proportional to chain size"}]','b','In Java 8+, when a chain exceeds 8 elements (with table size ≥ 64), the bucket is converted to a red-black tree (TreeMap). The reason: O(n) worst-case for a long chain (e.g., from hash collision attacks) is unacceptable in security-sensitive contexts. Red-black tree gives O(log n) worst-case per bucket, bounding the damage of adversarial input. Below 8 elements, linked list is faster (lower constant factors, simpler structure). Above 8, tree overhead is worth it. This is the ''timsort for buckets'' idea applied to collision resolution. Option A is wrong (O(log n) is not O(1)). Option C is false (tree nodes use more memory). Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is consistent hashing, and what problem does it solve?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Consistent hashing maps keys to buckets using a fixed hash function that never changes; it solves the rehashing problem when the table grows"},{"id":"b","text":"Consistent hashing arranges bucket identifiers on a ring (mod 2³²), mapping each key to the next bucket clockwise; when a bucket is added or removed, only keys near that bucket''s position remap, minimizing cache invalidation in distributed systems"},{"id":"c","text":"Consistent hashing requires all servers to hash to the same bucket range using a shared seed, ensuring identical routing across all nodes"},{"id":"d","text":"Consistent hashing is a hash function that produces the same output across different programming languages for cross-platform compatibility"}]','b','Consistent hashing (Karger et al., 1997) arranges bucket identifiers on a circular hash space. Each key is mapped to the nearest bucket clockwise on the ring. When a bucket is added or removed, only keys between the affected bucket and its neighbors remap — O(k/n) keys remap where k is keys and n is buckets. This is crucial for distributed caches (CDN, DynamoDB, Cassandra) where adding/removing nodes should only affect a fraction of keys. Virtual nodes (replicas) improve load distribution by assigning multiple positions per physical node. Option A describes traditional hashing (which requires rehashing all keys on resize). Option C is wrong. Option D is about cross-platform hash compatibility, not consistent hashing.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def group_anagrams(strs):
    from collections import defaultdict
    groups = defaultdict(list)
    for s in strs:
        key = tuple(sorted(collections.Counter(s).items()))
        groups[key].append(s)
    return list(groups.values())

