,(NULL,'SENIOR','A good hash function for strings should process each character of the string for uniform distribution. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','String hash functions like polynomial rolling hash compute H(s) = s[0]×B^(n-1) + s[1]×B^(n-2) + ... + s[n-1]×B^0 (mod M). Processing each character ensures the hash depends on all characters and their positions (so ''abc'' and ''cab'' produce different hashes). Using only the first few characters (or summing without positional weighting) causes collisions: ''ab'' and ''ba'' would both hash to the same value. The base B (e.g., 31, 33, 37) should be a prime > alphabet size to spread bits. This is why string hashing for substrings (rolling hash) and bloom filters requires per-character computation.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the time complexity of accessing an element by index in a singly linked list?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(1) — linked list nodes store direct memory addresses for random access"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n) — the list must be traversed from the head to reach the index"},{"id":"c","text":"O(log n) — binary search can navigate linked list nodes"},{"id":"d","text":"O(n²) — each access requires a full list traversal"}]','b','Singly linked lists have no index-based random access. To reach index i, you must start at head and follow next pointers i times — a sequential walk. This is the fundamental trade-off: linked lists sacrifice O(1) indexed access for O(1) insertion/deletion at known positions (no shifting required). Arrays have the opposite trade-off: O(1) access but O(n) arbitrary insertion. Option A is wrong (arrays provide O(1) random access; linked lists don''t store indices). Option C is wrong (binary search requires random access). Option D overcounts.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the time complexity of inserting a node at the head of a singly linked list?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(n) — all existing nodes must be renumbered and relinked"},{"id":"b","text":"O(1) — create a new node, point its next to the current head, then update head pointer"},{"id":"c","text":"O(log n) — the tree of nodes must be rebalanced"},{"id":"d","text":"O(1) — the new node is automatically placed at the front without any pointer manipulation"}]','b','Head insertion is the linked list''s most efficient operation: (1) allocate new node, (2) newNode.next = head, (3) head = newNode. No traversal needed — the head pointer is directly accessible. This O(1) property makes linked lists ideal for stack implementations. Option A describes array insertion cost, not linked list. Option C is wrong (linked lists are not trees, no rebalancing needed). Option D is incorrect — pointer manipulation is required.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the time complexity of inserting a node at the tail of a singly linked list when a tail pointer is maintained?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(1) — the tail pointer is updated directly without any traversal"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n) — the list must be traversed from head to find the insertion point"},{"id":"c","text":"O(log n) — a binary search tree traversal locates the tail"},{"id":"d","text":"O(1) — tail insertion works identically to head insertion"}]','a','With a tail pointer maintained (tail.next = null, head is separately tracked), appending is: (1) tail.next = newNode, (2) tail = newNode. This is O(1) with no traversal. Without a tail pointer, appending would be O(n) because you''d need to traverse from head to find the last node. This is why linked list implementations often maintain both head and tail pointers. Option B is the cost without a tail pointer. Option C is wrong. Option D is misleading — tail insertion is different from head insertion logic.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the output of the following algorithm?

class ListNode:
    def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):
        self.val = val
        self.next = next

def build(values):
    dummy = ListNode(0)
    cur = dummy
    for v in values:
        cur.next = ListNode(v)
        cur = cur.next
    return dummy.next

def print_list(head):
    result = []
    while head:
        result.append(head.val)
        head = head.next
    return result

head = build([1, 2, 3])
