,(NULL,'JUNIOR','How does Floyd''s cycle detection algorithm (tortoise and hare) detect a cycle in a linked list?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"It uses a hash set to mark visited nodes; if a node is visited twice, a cycle exists"},{"id":"b","text":"The tortoise moves one step at a time (slow pointer) and the hare moves two steps; if they ever meet, a cycle exists"},{"id":"c","text":"It reverses the linked list and checks if the original head is reachable from the tail"},{"id":"d","text":"It compares the length of the list to the position of the last node to detect wrapping"}]','b','Floyd''s algorithm places two pointers at head: slow (tortoise) advances 1 node per step, fast (hare) advances 2 nodes. In a cycle of length c, the hare laps the tortoise. They are guaranteed to meet after O(n) steps because the relative speed of 1 node/step ensures the hare catches up within the cycle. Space: O(1). Option A describes hash-set cycle detection (also valid but O(n) space). Option C is a different approach (reversal detection requires modifying the list). Option D is not a detection mechanism.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What does reversing a singly linked list NOT change?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"The data values stored in each node remain in their original order within each node"},{"id":"b","text":"The node objects themselves — only the next pointers are rewired"},{"id":"c","text":"The total memory usage — no nodes are allocated or deallocated during reversal"},{"id":"d","text":"The time complexity — in-place reversal is still O(n)"}]','d','In-place reversal of a singly linked list uses three pointers (prev, curr, next) and rewires each node''s next pointer from ''next'' to ''prev''. The nodes themselves are not copied, moved, or recreated — only pointer references change. The algorithm traverses each node once → O(n) time, O(1) space. The key insight is that nodes are never recreated; only the linked structure (edges) changes. Option A is always true (node data is untouched). Option B is true (nodes stay in memory). Option C is true (no allocation). Option D is the trick — reversal is O(n) so this is NOT unchanged; it IS O(n).')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the key advantage of a doubly linked list over a singly linked list?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(1) random access by index since both next and prev pointers enable binary search"},{"id":"b","text":"O(1) deletion of a node when given the node reference, because you can update both prev.next and next.prev pointers"},{"id":"c","text":"Faster traversal because two pointers can traverse the list simultaneously in parallel"},{"id":"d","text":"Lower memory usage since each node only needs to store one pointer instead of two"}]','b','In a singly linked list, deleting node X requires access to X''s previous node — you must traverse from head to find it. In a doubly linked list, node X has both .prev and .next; to delete X: X.prev.next = X.next; X.next.prev = X.prev. Both pointer updates are O(1) given the node reference. This makes doubly linked lists ideal for LRU caches, browser history (back/forward), and text editors (undo/redo). Option A is false (no O(1) indexed access). Option C is false (both pointers traverse the same direction for one traversal). Option D is false (doubly linked uses more memory, not less).')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','When merging two sorted singly linked lists, what is the optimal algorithm?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Recursively merge: compare heads, attach the smaller one, recurse on its next — O(n+m) time, O(1) space"},{"id":"b","text":"Convert both to arrays, sort, and convert back — O((n+m) log(n+m)) time"},{"id":"c","text":"Append the second list to the first, then run merge sort on the combined list — O((n+m) log(n+m)) time"},{"id":"d","text":"Use a hash map to map values to their source list, then rebuild — O(n+m) time but O(n+m) space"}]','a','Merging sorted linked lists is a classic O(n+m) merge operation: compare l1.val and l2.val, attach the smaller to the result, advance that pointer, repeat. This mirrors the merge step of merge sort. A dummy head node simplifies handling edge cases (empty lists). Iterative version uses O(1) extra space; recursive version uses O(n+m) call stack. Option B and C are correct but suboptimal (O(n log n) vs O(n+m)). Option D is wasteful.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def reverse_linked_list(head):
    prev, curr = None, head
    while curr:
        nxt = curr.next
        curr.next = prev
        prev = curr
        curr = nxt
    return prev

def to_list(head):
    result = []
    while head:
        result.append(head.val)
        head = head.next
    return result

head = build_list([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
to_list(reverse_linked_list(head))','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','b','The classic in-place linked list reversal: prev starts None (new tail), curr starts at head. At each step: curr.next = prev rewires the link direction, then prev and curr advance. After n steps, curr is None and prev is the new head. This is O(n) time, O(1) space. Option A is wrong (the algorithm clearly rewires). Option C is a different pattern (e.g., reverse pairs). Option D is wrong — the last node becomes the new head, not None.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the time complexity of finding the middle node of a singly linked list using the fast/slow pointer technique?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(1) — a hash map indexed by position gives direct O(1) access to the middle"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n) — the list is traversed once with fast pointer moving 2x speed, meeting the slow pointer at the middle"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n/2) — two passes are required to determine the middle position"},{"id":"d","text":"O(log n) — the fast pointer halves the search space logarithmically"}]','b','Initialize slow = head, fast = head. At each step: slow = slow.next, fast = fast.next.next. When fast reaches the end (None), slow is at the midpoint. For odd-length lists, fast.next is None at termination; for even-length lists, fast is None at termination — slow points to the second of the two ''middle'' nodes. This is a single O(n) pass. Option A describes a hash-based approach (O(n) build, O(1) access, but O(n) space). Option C misrepresents the single pass (two pointers moving at different speeds is one pass). Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the time complexity of detecting a cycle using Floyd''s algorithm?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(1) — only two pointer comparisons are needed regardless of list length"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n) — at most one full traversal of the list is required before the pointers meet"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n²) — cycle detection requires checking all possible cycle entry points"},{"id":"d","text":"O(log n) — the fast pointer halves the effective list length each step"}]','b','In Floyd''s algorithm, the hare traverses 2 steps per step of the tortoise. If a cycle exists, the hare catches up within the cycle length. At most, the hare needs to do one full cycle traversal before meeting the tortoise, which occurs in O(n) total steps (where n is the list length including cycle). Space is O(1). Option A is wrong. Option C is wrong. Option D misapplies the halving concept — the fast pointer doesn''t halve anything, it moves faster.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is a sentinel/dummy node in linked list operations, and what problem does it solve?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A dummy node stores a default value to prevent null pointer exceptions when the list is empty"},{"id":"b","text":"A dummy node acts as a temporary placeholder at the start of the list, eliminating edge cases for head/tail insertion and deletion with a unified pointer update logic"},{"id":"c","text":"A sentinel node marks the end of the list and allows early termination of traversal loops"},{"id":"d","text":"A sentinel node caches the length of the list for O(1) size queries"}]','b','A dummy/sentinel node is a placeholder placed before the real head (or after the tail). It simplifies edge cases: instead of separate handling for head insertion (updating head pointer) and middle insertion (updating prev.next), you create a dummy and always have a ''previous node'' to update. The dummy is stripped off at the end. Common in merge operations, insertion sort on linked lists, and partition operations. Option A is partially correct but misses the key motivation. Option C is wrong (None marks the end). Option D is not the purpose of sentinel nodes.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A singly linked list can be reversed in O(1) auxiliary space. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','The iterative three-pointer approach (prev, curr, next) reverses in-place using only three pointer variables, regardless of list size. This gives O(1) auxiliary space. The recursive approach requires O(n) call stack space, so it is NOT O(1).')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Finding the k-th node from the end of a singly linked list always requires a full O(n) traversal. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','The two-pointer technique solves it in O(n) time and O(1) space in a single pass: advance the first pointer k steps, then advance both pointers until the first reaches the end — the second pointer is now k steps behind, at the k-th-from-end node. This is not O(n²) or multi-pass.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','After detecting a cycle with Floyd''s algorithm, how do you find the cycle''s starting node (entry point)?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Reset the slow pointer to head and move both pointers one step at a time; they meet at the cycle entry node after μ steps"},{"id":"b","text":"Measure the cycle length c, then traverse c steps from head to find the entry point"},{"id":"c","text":"Use the fast pointer to skip nodes at 3x speed until it catches the slow pointer, which marks the entry"},{"id":"d","text":"The slow and fast pointers always meet at the entry point, so no additional steps are needed"}]','a','After Floyd''s detection (slow and fast meet inside the cycle), the entry point is found by resetting one pointer to head and moving both at 1 step per iteration: they will meet exactly at the cycle entry node. The proof: distance from head to entry = μ, distance from entry to meeting point = λ; tortoise traveled μ + λ, hare traveled μ + λ + c (one extra cycle). Since hare = 2 × tortoise: μ + λ + c = 2(μ + λ) → μ = c - λ. After resetting slow to head, moving both μ steps brings them to the entry. Option B is also valid (find cycle length c, then find node at position n-c from head) but requires two passes. Option C is not the Floyd method. Option D is false — they meet somewhere inside the cycle, not necessarily at entry.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def odd_even_linked_list(head):
    if not head: return None
    odd, even, even_head = head, head.next, head.next
    while even and even.next:
        odd.next = even.next
        odd = odd.next
        even.next = odd.next
        even = even.next
    odd.next = even_head
    return head

def to_list(head):
    return [head.val] + to_list(head.next) if head else []

to_list(odd_even_linked_list(build_list([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])))','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','b','The algorithm separates nodes by index parity: all odd-position nodes (1-based: 1,3,5) are collected in order, followed by all even-position nodes (2,4). The odd pointer skips one node and links to the next odd node; the even pointer follows the same pattern for evens. After processing, odd.next = even_head reconnects the two partitions. Result: [1→3→5→2→4]. This is a LeetCode-style problem requiring in-place O(1) space. Option A is wrong. Option C describes reversal. Option D describes pair swapping.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What recurrence relation describes the time complexity of recursive linked list reversal, and what is its space complexity?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"T(n) = T(n-1) + O(1), resolving to O(n) time; space is O(1) since reversal is in-place"},{"id":"b","text":"T(n) = 2T(n/2) + O(n), resolving to O(n log n) time; space is O(log n) for recursion depth"},{"id":"c","text":"T(n) = T(n-1) + O(n), resolving to O(n²) time; space is O(n)"},{"id":"d","text":"T(n) = T(n-1) + O(1), resolving to O(n) time; space is O(n) due to call stack"}]','d','Recursive reversal: reverse(head.next) returns the new head of the reversed sublist; then append current head to its tail. Each call does O(1) work (link rewiring), so T(n) = T(n-1) + O(1) → O(n) time. The recursion depth is n (each call waits for its subcall to return), requiring O(n) call stack space. This is the key trade-off vs. the iterative O(1)-space version: recursive is cleaner but uses O(n) stack space. Option A incorrectly says O(1) space. Option B is merge sort''s recurrence. Option C overcounts work per call.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Both singly and doubly linked lists have O(n) worst-case time complexity for search operations. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','Both singly and doubly linked lists require sequential traversal from head to find a target value — there is no index-based jump or tree structure. The only difference is that doubly linked lists allow O(1) deletion given a node reference (since you have the prev pointer), while singly linked lists require O(n) traversal to find the previous node. Neither structure has O(log n) or O(1) search. Hash tables offer O(1) average search; balanced BSTs offer O(log n) search.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the average time complexity of quick sort?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(n²) — quick sort degrades to quadratic behavior in typical datasets"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n log n) — partition divides array roughly in half each recursive level with O(n) partition cost per level"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n) — a single partition pass sorts the entire array"},{"id":"d","text":"O(log n) — quick sort eliminates half the elements with each comparison"}]','b','Quick sort''s average case: T(n) = T(k) + T(n-k) + O(n), where the partition pivot lands near the middle on average. Solving this recurrence gives O(n log n). This assumes a good pivot strategy (random, median-of-three, etc.). The worst case (pivot always minimum or maximum) gives O(n²). Option A is the worst case. Option C underestimates work (partition is done at every level of recursion, not just once). Option D is binary search complexity, not quick sort.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the space complexity of merge sort?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(1) — merge sort can be implemented in-place with only pointer swaps"},{"id":"b","text":"O(log n) — recursion depth is logarithmic, and no extra arrays are needed"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n) — the merge step requires a temporary array proportional to the subarray being merged"},{"id":"d","text":"O(n log n) — every level of recursion requires O(n) auxiliary space"}]','c','Merge sort''s divide step is free (index arithmetic). The merge/combine step requires copying elements into a temporary array of size proportional to the subarray — O(n) space per merge. With careful implementation (allocating one auxiliary array and reusing slices), this is O(n) total auxiliary space. Recursion depth is O(log n). Standard analysis: O(n) auxiliary space + O(log n) stack = O(n). Option A is false. Option B ignores the merge buffer. Option D overcounts — O(n log n) would require new arrays at every level.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the key property that makes binary search applicable to finding a target in a sorted array?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"The array must be stored in a balanced binary tree structure with O(1) index access"},{"id":"b","text":"The sorted order allows eliminating half the remaining search space with each comparison based on whether the target is less than or greater than the middle element"},{"id":"c","text":"Binary search requires the array to be completely full with no empty slots"},{"id":"d","text":"Binary search only works on integer arrays; it cannot handle floating-point values"}]','b','Binary search exploits sorted order: after comparing target with arr[mid], you know whether the answer lies in the left half or right half (since all left elements < arr[mid] < all right elements). This eliminates half the search space per step. After log₂ n steps, the search space is size 1. The requirement is random access (indexable array), not a specific data structure. Option A describes an actual BST, not binary search. Option C and D are false restrictions.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def bubble_sort(arr):
    n = len(arr)
    for i in range(n):
        swapped = False
        for j in range(0, n - i - 1):
            if arr[j] > arr[j + 1]:
                arr[j], arr[j + 1] = arr[j + 1], arr[j]
                swapped = True
        if not swapped:
            break
    return arr

bubble_sort([5, 2, 9, 1, 5, 6])','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','a','Bubble sort repeatedly swaps adjacent elements if out of order. The outer loop runs n passes; inner loop shrinks from n-i-1 (rightmost i elements are already bubbled into place). After each pass, the largest unsorted element reaches its final position. The `if not swapped: break` optimization detects when the array is already sorted (no swaps in a pass) and exits early. Result: [1, 2, 5, 5, 6, 9]. Option B is wrong (swaps occur). Option C is descending sort. Option D is a partial result mid-algorithm.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What does it mean for a sorting algorithm to be stable?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"The algorithm''s running time does not vary with input order — it always takes the same number of steps"},{"id":"b","text":"Equal elements maintain their relative order from the input in the sorted output"},{"id":"c","text":"The algorithm uses only O(1) auxiliary memory regardless of input size"},{"id":"d","text":"The algorithm guarantees O(n log n) performance even in the worst case"}]','b','Stability means that when two elements have equal keys, their relative order in the output matches their relative order in the input. Example: sorting [(Alice, 2), (Bob, 1), (Carol, 2)] by score: a stable sort guarantees Alice appears before Carol (both score 2, Alice was first). An unstable sort may reverse them. Stability matters when sorting by multiple keys: sort by city, then by name — stable sort preserves city grouping while sorting within it. Merge sort is stable; quick sort is not (partition swaps can change relative order of equals).')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the time complexity of binary search on a sorted array of n elements?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(log n) — the search space halves with each comparison, requiring at most log₂ n iterations"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n) — the algorithm may need to scan the entire array in the worst case"},{"id":"c","text":"O(1) — binary search jumps directly to the target using index arithmetic"},{"id":"d","text":"O(n log n) — log n passes are needed over n elements"}]','a','Binary search computes mid = (lo+hi)//2, compares arr[mid] with target, and recurses into the half that could contain the target. Each step reduces the search space by half. After k steps, remaining space is n/2^k. It reaches size 1 when 2^k ≥ n → k ≥ log₂ n. This is the fundamental O(log n) search algorithm — logarithmic time means halving the work each step. Option B describes linear search. Option C is wrong. Option D miscounts — there is only one element examined per iteration.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','Which sorting algorithm works by repeatedly selecting the minimum element from the unsorted portion and placing it at the beginning?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Selection sort — find the minimum in the unsorted portion, swap it with the first unsorted position"},{"id":"b","text":"Insertion sort — shift elements right to insert the current element into the sorted portion"},{"id":"c","text":"Bubble sort — repeatedly swap adjacent elements until the minimum reaches the front"},{"id":"d","text":"Merge sort — divide the array in half and recursively sort each half before merging"}]','a','Selection sort: for each position i from 0 to n-1, find the minimum element in arr[i..n-1] and swap it with arr[i]. This puts one element in its final position per outer iteration. Key properties: O(n²) time regardless of input order (no best/average case improvement), O(1) space (in-place), and it is NOT stable (swapping can change relative order of equal elements). For example, swapping arr[i] with the minimum may move an equal element past others. Option B describes insertion sort. Option C describes bubble sort''s bubbling mechanism but bubble sort doesn''t find a global minimum.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','Which sorting algorithm is stable by default? (Select all that apply)','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"Merge sort"},{"id":"b","text":"Bubble sort"},{"id":"c","text":"Quick sort (standard partition)"},{"id":"d","text":"Insertion sort"}]','a,b,d','Merge sort (stable when merging with ≤ comparison), bubble sort (adjacent swaps never change relative order of equal elements), and insertion sort (shifting only, no swaps that cross equal elements) are all stable by default. Quick sort''s partitioning swaps elements across the pivot boundary, which can change the relative order of equal elements — making it unstable by default. To make quick sort stable, additional effort is required (index tracking or extra space).')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the worst-case time complexity of quick sort and what causes it?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(n log n) — worst case occurs when the input is already sorted and the pivot is the first element"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n²) — worst case occurs when the pivot consistently selects the smallest or largest element, creating maximally unbalanced partitions"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n²) — worst case occurs when all elements are equal, causing excessive duplicate handling"},{"id":"d","text":"O(n log n) — quick sort always performs in O(n log n) regardless of pivot selection"}]','b','Quick sort''s worst case: T(n) = T(n-1) + T(0) + O(n) = O(n²). This occurs when the pivot is consistently the minimum or maximum element (e.g., already sorted array with first-element pivot, or reverse sorted with last-element pivot). The partition becomes maximally unbalanced: sizes 0 and n-1. Mitigation: randomized pivot selection (expected O(n log n)), median-of-three, or introsort (switch to heap sort after depth limit). Option A misidentifies the time complexity. Option C''s all-equal case depends on partition strategy — naive partition degrades, 3-way partition handles it well. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def binary_search(arr, target):
    lo, hi = 0, len(arr) - 1
    while lo <= hi:
        mid = (lo + hi) // 2
        if arr[mid] == target:
            return mid
        elif arr[mid] < target:
            lo = mid + 1
        else:
            hi = mid - 1
    return -1

