,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between in-place and out-of-place sorting algorithms?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"In-place uses O(1) auxiliary space; out-of-place uses O(n) or more additional space"},{"id":"b","text":"In-place algorithms can only sort arrays; out-of-place algorithms can sort any data structure"},{"id":"c","text":"Out-of-place algorithms are always faster than in-place algorithms"},{"id":"d","text":"In-place means the algorithm never swaps elements; out-of-place swaps elements during sorting"}]','a','In-place sorting algorithms use O(1) or O(log n) auxiliary space (constant or logarithmic, relative to input size). Quick sort is in-place (O(log n) stack space worst-case). Out-of-place algorithms allocate additional memory proportional to input size. Merge sort is typically out-of-place (O(n) auxiliary array). The distinction matters for memory-constrained environments. Option B is false (in-place algorithms work on linked lists too). Option C is false (space vs time trade-off). Option D misdefines in-place.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Which sorting algorithm has the best worst-case time complexity?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Quick sort — O(n log n) worst case with randomized pivot"},{"id":"b","text":"Merge sort — O(n log n) worst case guaranteed due to balanced divide-and-conquer"},{"id":"c","text":"Heap sort — O(n log n) worst case with guaranteed O(1) auxiliary space"},{"id":"d","text":"Insertion sort — O(n) best case and O(n²) worst case, averaging O(n) on small data"}]','b','Merge sort guarantees O(n log n) in all cases (best, average, worst) because it always divides perfectly balanced (T(n) = 2T(n/2) + O(n) → O(n log n)). Heap sort also has O(n log n) worst case but is in-place. Quick sort has O(n²) worst case (unbalanced partitions). The answer is merge sort because it provides guaranteed O(n log n) with consistent performance. However, in practice, introsort (quick sort + heap sort fallback) is often preferred for general sorting. Option C is also valid (heap sort O(n log n) guaranteed, O(1) space), but merge sort is the textbook answer for ''best guaranteed worst case.''')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the recurrence relation for merge sort and what does it resolve to?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"T(n) = T(n-1) + O(1), resolving to O(n) — linear scan"},{"id":"b","text":"T(n) = 2T(n/2) + O(n), resolving to O(n log n) via Master theorem (case 2: a=2, b=2, f(n)=Θ(n), so n^log_b(a)=n, f(n)=Θ(n) → Θ(n log n))"},{"id":"c","text":"T(n) = T(n/2) + O(1), resolving to O(log n) — binary search style"},{"id":"d","text":"T(n) = T(n-1) + O(n), resolving to O(n²) — insertion sort style"}]','b','Merge sort divides the array into two halves (2T(n/2)), recursively sorts each half, then merges them (O(n) merge cost). Master theorem: a=2, b=2, d=1 → n^(log_b a) = n^1 = n, f(n) = Θ(n) → case 2 → Θ(n log n). This is the textbook example for Master theorem case 2. Option A is linear search. Option C is binary search. Option D is O(n²).')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Quick sort is a stable sorting algorithm. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','Quick sort is NOT stable by default. During partitioning, elements are swapped across the pivot boundary. If two equal elements are on opposite sides of the partition, swapping them changes their relative order. This breaks stability. Merge sort is the stable O(n log n) alternative, though it requires O(n) auxiliary space. For applications requiring stability (multi-key sorting, preserving insertion order), use merge sort or implement quick sort with stable partition strategies.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Heap sort has O(n log n) worst-case time complexity and O(1) auxiliary space. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','Heap sort builds a max-heap from the array (O(n)), then repeatedly extracts the maximum (O(log n) per extract) and places it at the end. This gives O(n log n) worst case with no recursion and only O(1) auxiliary space (the input array is sorted in-place). The main drawback is that heap sort is not cache-friendly (non-contiguous memory accesses) and is not stable. It is the only comparison sort with O(n log n) guarantee and O(1) space.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Which sorting algorithms are in-place? (Select all that apply)','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"Quick sort"},{"id":"b","text":"Merge sort (standard implementation)"},{"id":"c","text":"Heap sort"},{"id":"d","text":"Insertion sort"}]','a,c,d','Quick sort (O(log n) stack space, in-place partitioning), heap sort (O(1) auxiliary space, fully in-place), and insertion sort (O(1) auxiliary space, in-place shifting) are all in-place. Merge sort requires O(n) auxiliary array for the merge step — standard implementations are out-of-place. Some complex in-place merge sort variants exist but are not commonly used.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def merge_sort(arr):
    if len(arr) <= 1: return arr
    mid = len(arr) // 2
    left = merge_sort(arr[:mid])
    right = merge_sort(arr[mid:])
    return merge(left, right)

def merge(a, b):
    result, i, j = [], 0, 0
    while i < len(a) and j < len(b):
        if a[i] <= b[j]: result.append(a[i]); i += 1
        else: result.append(b[j]); j += 1
    result.extend(a[i:]); result.extend(b[j:])
    return result

