,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the time complexity of finding the floor (largest element ≤ target) in a sorted array using binary search?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(n) — linear scan is required to find the floor element"},{"id":"b","text":"O(log n) — binary search can be adapted to find floor by tracking the best candidate found so far"},{"id":"c","text":"O(1) — floor can be found by computing target minus one from the last element"},{"id":"d","text":"O(log n) — binary search can directly jump to the floor using the target value as an index offset"}]','b','Binary search for floor: when arr[mid] ≤ target, mid is a candidate for floor — record it and search the right half for a potentially larger floor. When arr[mid] > target, search the left half. After log n steps, the best candidate found is the floor. This is a common binary search variant (along with ceiling, lower bound, upper bound). Option A is linear search. Option C is nonsense. Option D misrepresents how binary search works — it doesn''t use arithmetic on the target as an index.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the lower bound on comparison-based sorting, and why can''t it be beaten by comparison sorts?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(n) — sorting requires examining every element at least once"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n log n) — there are n! possible permutations and each comparison eliminates at most half, requiring log₂(n!) ≈ n log n comparisons in the worst case"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n²) — sorting requires comparing every pair of elements in the worst case"},{"id":"d","text":"O(log n) — a balanced binary decision tree can sort in logarithmic time"}]','b','Comparison sorts can be modeled as binary decision trees: each comparison (a[i] < a[j]?) has two outcomes, creating a binary tree. Sorting must distinguish all n! possible input orderings, so the decision tree must have at least n! leaves. A binary tree with L leaves has height ≥ log₂ L. So minimum height ≥ log₂(n!) ≈ n log₂ n - n log₂ e + O(log n) (Stirling''s approximation). Therefore no comparison sort can beat Ω(n log n) in the worst case. This lower bound can be beaten by non-comparison sorts (counting sort, radix sort, bucket sort) when extra conditions exist (bounded integer range, fixed-length keys).')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Counting sort has O(n + k) time and O(k) space where k is the range of input values, making it linear-time for bounded integers. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','Counting sort works in three phases: (1) count occurrences of each value in O(n), (2) compute prefix sums to determine positions in O(k), (3) place elements in output array using counts in O(n). Total: O(n + k) time, O(k) auxiliary space. It is stable and non-comparison-based, so it can achieve better than Ω(n log n) when the range k is O(n). The trade-off: if k >> n², counting sort becomes impractical (too much memory). Radix sort extends this by applying counting sort digit-by-digit.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def insertion_sort(arr):
    for i in range(1, len(arr)):
        key = arr[i]
        j = i - 1
        while j >= 0 and arr[j] > key:
            arr[j + 1] = arr[j]
            j -= 1
        arr[j + 1] = key
    return arr

print(insertion_sort([5, 2, 9, 1, 5, 6]))','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','a','Insertion sort processes each element from index 1: it shifts all larger elements right to make room for the key. Trace: [2,5,9,1,5,6] after key=2; [2,5,9,1,5,6] after key=9 (no shifts); [1,2,5,9,5,6] after key=1 (shifts 5,9 right); [1,2,5,5,9,6] after key=5 (shifts 9 right); [1,2,5,5,6,9] after key=6 (shifts 9 right). Result: [1, 2, 5, 5, 6, 9]. Option B is wrong. Option C is descending. Option D is mid-state.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is external sorting, and why is it needed?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"External sorting sorts data that does not fit in main memory (RAM); it uses disk I/O in passes (e.g., merge sort-based external merge sort), minimizing the number of expensive disk reads/writes"},{"id":"b","text":"External sorting sorts arrays that are stored outside the CPU cache; it minimizes cache misses by sorting in cache-sized chunks"},{"id":"c","text":"External sorting is a synonym for radix sort applied to large integers; it processes each digit as an external pass"},{"id":"d","text":"External sorting sorts data in external (non-volatile) memory like SSDs; it is no different from internal sorting in terms of algorithm"}]','a','External sorting handles data too large to fit in RAM — used in databases and file systems. The classic approach: (1) sort chunks that fit in RAM, write to disk, (2) merge sorted runs using a k-way merge (heap-based). The goal is minimizing disk I/O (random disk access is orders of magnitude slower than sequential read). External merge sort: sort M-page runs, then merge k runs at a time where k = RAM pages / run pages. Key insight: disk I/O is the bottleneck, not CPU comparisons.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Which sorting algorithms are stable? (Select all that apply)','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"Bubble sort"},{"id":"b","text":"Merge sort"},{"id":"c","text":"Radix sort (LSD)"},{"id":"d","text":"Quick sort (standard partition scheme)"}]','a,b,c','Bubble sort (stable — adjacent swaps preserve relative order of equals), merge sort (stable — merge preserves order when elements are equal), and radix sort LSD (stable counting sort per digit preserves order across digits). Quick sort is NOT stable (partition swaps can cross equal elements). Radix sort MSD can be made stable with careful implementation, but LSD is inherently stable due to its per-digit counting sort foundation.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the key property that makes counting sort run in linear time?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Counting sort uses binary search to locate each element''s position in O(log n)"},{"id":"b","text":"Counting sort uses the element values as array indices (no comparisons needed), and its runtime O(n + k) is linear when the range k is O(n)"},{"id":"c","text":"Counting sort divides the array in half recursively and merges in O(n), achieving O(n log n)"},{"id":"d","text":"Counting sort is a comparison-based sort that beats the Ω(n log n) lower bound by using a special comparison strategy"}]','b','Counting sort is non-comparison-based: it uses a count array where count[key] directly indexes by element value. For each element with value v, the output position is determined by counting occurrences — no pairwise comparisons. Time: O(n + k) where k = max - min + 1. When k = O(n), this is O(n). When k >> n (e.g., sorting 32-bit integers where k = 2³²), it becomes impractical. This is why radix sort applies counting sort digit-by-digit: each digit has range k = base (e.g., 10 for decimal), keeping k small and linear-time.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def radix_sort(arr):
    max_val = max(arr)
    exp = 1
    while max_val // exp > 0:
        counting_sort_by_digit(arr, exp)
        exp *= 10
    return arr

def counting_sort_by_digit(arr, exp):
    n = len(arr)
    output = [0] * n
    count = [0] * 10
    for x in arr:
        count[(x // exp) % 10] += 1
    for i in range(1, 10):
        count[i] += count[i-1]
    for i in range(n-1, -1, -1):
        digit = (arr[i] // exp) % 10
        count[digit] -= 1
        output[count[digit]] = arr[i]
    for i in range(n):
        arr[i] = output[i]

print(radix_sort([170, 45, 75, 90, 802, 24, 2, 66]))','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','c','LSD (Least Significant Digit) radix sort processes digits from least to most significant. Pass 1 (ones digit): [170, 90, 802, 2, 24, 45, 75, 66]. Pass 2 (tens digit): [802, 2, 24, 45, 66, 170, 75, 90]. Pass 3 (hundreds digit): [2, 24, 45, 66, 75, 90, 170, 802]. Radix sort is stable (backward pass ensures stability) and runs in O(d × (n + k)) where d = digits and k = base. Option A is wrong sorting. Option B is an intermediate state. Option D is the result of LSD sort with wrong final order.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Heap sort builds a max-heap and then repeatedly extracts the maximum element. What is the time complexity of the heapify (build-heap) operation?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(n log n) — heapify calls bubble-down for each of the n elements, each taking O(log n)"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n) — the bottom-up buildheap (Floyd''s algorithm) runs in linear time because most nodes are at the bottom (small height) and higher nodes don''t sink far"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n²) — each node requires comparison with both children until the correct position is found"},{"id":"d","text":"O(log n) — heapify needs only to check the root node''s children to maintain the heap property"}]','b','Floyd''s bottom-up heap construction runs in O(n) — not O(n log n). The key insight: nodes at height h have at most ⌊log n⌋ - h children to sink past. Most nodes are at the bottom of the tree (large h → small height), so they sink very little. Summing the work across all levels gives the geometric series result O(n). If you insert n elements one by one (each O(log n)), it''s O(n log n). The bottom-up construction saves a log factor. Option A describes n individual inserts. Option C overestimates. Option D underestimates.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Which sort runs fastest on a nearly-sorted array: insertion sort, quick sort, or merge sort? (Select all that apply)','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"Insertion sort — O(n) best case on nearly sorted data"},{"id":"b","text":"Quick sort — O(n log n) regardless of input order"},{"id":"c","text":"Timsort (used in Python/Java) — O(n) best case for runs that already exist"},{"id":"d","text":"Merge sort — O(n log n) but faster constant factors than quick sort on nearly sorted data"}]','a,c','Insertion sort has O(n) best case (already sorted or nearly sorted — inner loop rarely executes). Timsort (Python''s sorted(), Java Arrays.sort()) exploits existing runs and runs in O(n) on nearly sorted data. Quick sort''s performance is independent of input order (except for pivot quality — sorted input causes O(n²) worst case for naive pivot). Merge sort is O(n log n) regardless, with consistent performance but higher constant factors. The answer is insertion sort and Timsort.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','The comparison-based sorting lower bound Ω(n log n) applies to all sorting algorithms. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','The Ω(n log n) lower bound applies only to comparison-based sorts (those that determine order by comparing pairs of elements). Non-comparison sorts can beat this bound under specific conditions: counting sort O(n + k) where k is the range, radix sort O(d × (n + k)) where d is digit count and k is base, bucket sort O(n) average when inputs are uniformly distributed. These algorithms use the structure of the data (integer bounds, string length) rather than pairwise comparisons.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def selection_sort(arr):
    n = len(arr)
    for i in range(n):
        min_idx = i
        for j in range(i+1, n):
            if arr[j] < arr[min_idx]:
                min_idx = j
        arr[i], arr[min_idx] = arr[min_idx], arr[i]
    return arr

print(selection_sort([64, 25, 12, 22, 11]))','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','a','Selection sort: pass 1 → min=11 at index 3 → swap arr[0] and arr[3] → [11,25,12,22,64]; pass 2 → min=12 at index 2 → swap arr[1] and arr[2] → [11,12,25,22,64]; pass 3 → min=22 at index 3 → swap arr[2] and arr[3] → [11,12,22,25,64]; pass 4 → min=25 at index 3 → already in place. Result: [11, 12, 22, 25, 64]. Selection sort makes exactly one swap per outer iteration and always performs O(n²) comparisons regardless of input order. Option B is wrong. Option C is ascending but wrong algorithm. Option D is mid-state.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the time complexity of radix sort, and what factors determine how many passes it requires?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(n log n) — the number of passes depends on the logarithm of the number of elements"},{"id":"b","text":"O(d × (n + k)) where d = number of digits (digits of max value), k = base (radix); fewer passes than d when using larger base with more complex counters"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n + k) — one counting sort pass is always sufficient regardless of key size"},{"id":"d","text":"O(n × k) — each of the n elements must be processed through all k buckets"}]','b','Radix sort (LSD or MSD) applies a stable sort per digit. Each digit sort (typically counting sort) runs in O(n + k) where k = base (radix). With d digits (e.g., for an integer with max value M, d = ⌈log_k M⌉), total time: O(d × (n + k)). Larger base k means fewer digits but more memory (k counters). Smaller base means more passes but less memory. For decimal numbers with base 10 and max value 802: d=3. For 32-bit integers with base 256: d=4. The choice of base balances memory vs. passes.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the time complexity of push and pop operations on a stack implemented with a linked list?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(n) for push and O(1) for pop — linked list insertion at head is O(n) for arrays"},{"id":"b","text":"O(1) for both push and pop — push adds to the head, pop removes from the head"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n) for both — each operation requires a full traversal of the list"},{"id":"d","text":"O(log n) for both — binary search is used to locate the stack top"}]','b','Stack (LIFO) implemented as a linked list with head as top: push = insert at head (newNode.next = head, head = newNode) → O(1). Pop = remove from head (temp = head, head = head.next, free temp) → O(1). No traversal needed — head is always accessible. This makes linked-list stacks very efficient. Array-backed stacks are also O(1) amortized for push (resize is O(n) occasionally) and O(1) for pop. Option A reverses the costs. Option C and D are incorrect.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is a queue''s FIFO property?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"First-In-First-Out — the first element enqueued is the first element dequeued; like a line at a store"},{"id":"b","text":"First-In-First-Out — the last element enqueued is the first to be dequeued"},{"id":"c","text":"Last-In-First-Out — the most recent element is dequeued first"},{"id":"d","text":"FIFO means elements are processed in sorted order by value"}]','a','FIFO (First-In-First-Out) means the oldest element (first to be inserted) is removed first. Real-world analogy: a queue/line at a coffee shop. Operations: enqueue (add to back/rear) and dequeue (remove from front). Used for BFS, task scheduling, print job queues, message queues. Option B reverses it. Option C describes a stack (LIFO). Option D is not a property of queues.')
