,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the time complexity of enqueue and dequeue operations on a queue implemented with a circular buffer?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(n) — elements must be shifted when enqueuing at the front"},{"id":"b","text":"O(1) for both — head and tail indices are maintained; operations just advance pointers with wrap-around"},{"id":"c","text":"O(log n) — binary search is used to locate the queue head"},{"id":"d","text":"O(1) for enqueue and O(n) for dequeue — dequeue requires finding the front element"}]','b','Circular queue (ring buffer): fixed-size array with two pointers (front and rear). Enqueue: add at rear, advance rear pointer (modulo capacity). Dequeue: remove at front, advance front pointer (modulo capacity). Both are O(1) — no element shifting. When rear == front, the queue is either empty (initial) or full (when using a full-slot convention). A common convention uses (rear+1) % capacity == front for full detection, leaving one slot unused. This is the standard queue implementation in operating systems (circular buffers for print queues, network buffers).')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the primary application of a stack in algorithm design?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Breadth-first search — queues are used for level-order traversal"},{"id":"b","text":"Depth-first search — the call stack or explicit stack tracks the next node to explore"},{"id":"c","text":"Finding the shortest path — stacks maintain the minimum distance between nodes"},{"id":"d","text":"Sorting elements — stacks can sort arrays faster than comparison-based sorts"}]','b','DFS naturally uses a stack (LIFO): push neighbors onto the stack, pop and explore. Recursive DFS uses the call stack implicitly; iterative DFS uses an explicit stack. Stack''s LIFO order produces depth-first exploration (going as deep as possible before backtracking). BFS uses a queue (FIFO) to explore level by level. Option A is correct about BFS but the question asks about stack applications. Option C is wrong (shortest path uses priority queue or BFS). Option D is wrong (stacks don''t sort; they''re used for expression evaluation).')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is a monotonic stack?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A stack that maintains elements in sorted ascending or descending order; used to find the next greater/smaller element in O(n)"},{"id":"b","text":"A stack that uses a single monotonic function (f(x) = ax + b) to determine push/pop eligibility"},{"id":"c","text":"A stack that grows by doubling its size when full, achieving amortized O(1) push"},{"id":"d","text":"A stack with only one element allowed at each level, used for DFS on binary trees"}]','a','Monotonic stack maintains a stack where elements are monotonically increasing or decreasing. While iterating, pop elements that are smaller (or larger) than the current element and record the current element as their ''next greater'' (or ''next smaller''). This turns O(n²) brute force (checking all previous elements) into O(n) by ensuring each element is pushed and popped at most once. Classic problems: Next Greater Element, Daily Temperatures (next warmer day), Largest Rectangle in Histogram. Option B, C, D are incorrect.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is a valid use of a queue in graph traversal?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Queue is used for depth-first search to track the deepest unexplored node"},{"id":"b","text":"Queue is used for breadth-first search (BFS) — enqueue neighbors, process in FIFO order, guaranteeing level-by-level traversal"},{"id":"c","text":"Queue can detect cycles by checking if a node is already in the queue"},{"id":"d","text":"Queue replaces recursion to implement binary search on sorted arrays"}]','b','BFS uses a queue: start with source vertex, dequeue vertex, enqueue all unvisited neighbors. The FIFO property ensures vertices discovered earlier are explored earlier — this gives level-order (breadth-first) traversal. BFS finds shortest paths in unweighted graphs (number of edges from source). The visited set prevents revisiting. Option A is DFS (stack). Option C is not BFS''s primary purpose — cycle detection uses visited set + recursion stack (DFS) or in-degree tracking (Kahn''s algorithm). Option D is nonsense.')
