,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is a stack overflow, and when does it typically occur?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Stack overflow occurs when the heap runs out of memory during dynamic allocation"},{"id":"b","text":"Stack overflow occurs when the call stack exceeds its allocated memory limit, typically from unbounded recursion without a base case"},{"id":"c","text":"Stack overflow occurs when a queue''s circular buffer wraps around more than N times"},{"id":"d","text":"Stack overflow only occurs in languages without garbage collection"}]','b','The call stack has a fixed size (e.g., 1-8 MB). Each recursive call pushes a stack frame (return address, local variables, parameters). Unbounded recursion (e.g., infinite recursion without a base case) pushes frames until the stack overflows, causing a stack overflow error. In languages like Python, this manifests as RecursionError. Tail call optimization (TCO) can mitigate this in some languages (Scheme, Scala), converting tail recursion into iteration. Option A describes heap overflow. Option C is nonsensical. Option D is false (stack overflow occurs in all languages with call stacks).')
