,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is a deque (double-ended queue) and what operations does it support efficiently?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A deque is a priority queue where elements are ordered by priority; supports O(log n) insert and extract-max"},{"id":"b","text":"A deque is a double-ended queue supporting O(1) insert and delete at both front and back ends, enabling both stack and queue behavior"},{"id":"c","text":"A deque is a stack with exactly two elements, used for swapping pairs during sorting"},{"id":"d","text":"A deque is equivalent to two stacks joined head-to-tail, supporting O(log n) operations due to synchronization overhead"}]','b','Deque (double-ended queue): O(1) insert/delete at both ends (appendleft, popleft, append, pop). This unifies stack (push/pop one end) and queue (enqueue/dequeue opposite ends). Real-world uses: sliding window maximum (monotonic deque), implementing BFS with priority, undo/redo buffers (max-length deque), palindrome checking. Python''s collections.deque is implemented as a doubly-linked list of blocks (array blocks internally for cache locality), giving O(1) amortized operations. Option A describes a heap/priority queue. Option C is wrong. Option D mischaracterizes the complexity.')
