    return len(stack) == 0

print(is_balanced("({[]})"), is_balanced("([)]"), is_balanced("{}"))','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','a','(''{[]}'')'' checks: ''{''→push, ''(''→push, ''[''→push, '']''→pop ''['' matches, '')''→pop ''('' matches, ''}''→pop ''{'' matches. Stack empty at end → True. ''([)]'': ''(''→push, ''[''→push, '')''→pop ''(''? Stack top is ''['' ≠ '')'' → return False. ''{}'': ''{''→push, ''}''→pop ''{'' matches, stack empty → True. Output: True, False, True. This is the classic bracket balancing problem using a stack — push openers, pop and verify on closers. Option B is wrong. Option C is wrong (first is balanced). Option D is wrong (first is balanced).')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the maximum number of elements that can be stored in a circular queue of size N implemented with the (rear + 1) % N == front convention?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"N — all N slots are usable for storing elements"},{"id":"b","text":"N - 1 — one slot is left unused to distinguish the empty queue from the full queue"},{"id":"c","text":"N + 1 — the circular nature allows one extra element beyond the physical size"},{"id":"d","text":"2N — the circular queue doubles its capacity when full"}]','b','Circular queue with N slots: using the convention (rear+1) % N == front to detect ''full'', the queue can hold at most N-1 elements. When front == rear, the queue is empty. To distinguish empty from full without extra metadata, one slot must be unused. Alternative: store a ''size'' counter or a ''full'' flag to use all N slots. Option A (N) would make it impossible to distinguish empty (front==rear, 0 elements) from full (front==rear, N elements). This is a classic space-time trade-off in circular buffer design. Option C and D are wrong.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the sliding window maximum problem, and how does a monotonic deque solve it in O(n)?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Sliding window maximum finds the maximum element in each window of size k; a monotonic deque maintains indices in decreasing order, popping smaller elements from the back when the current element arrives, giving O(n) total"},{"id":"b","text":"Sliding window maximum uses a regular queue and dequeues the front element when the window slides, taking O(n×k) time"},{"id":"c","text":"Sliding window maximum sorts each window and returns the median, using a heap for O(n log n)"},{"id":"d","text":"Sliding window maximum can only be solved by checking all pairs of elements in O(n²)"}]','a','Sliding window maximum: given array and window size k, find max in each consecutive window of size k. Monotonic deque approach: maintain a deque of indices in decreasing value order. For each new element: (1) remove indices from front if they''re outside the current window, (2) remove indices from back whose values are ≤ current (they''ll never be the max while current is in the window), (3) append current index. The front of the deque is always the maximum of the current window. Each element is pushed and popped at most once → O(n) total. Naive O(n×k) approach checks all k elements per window. Option B is the naive approach. Option C is different (median, not max). Option D is wrong.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Using two stacks, it is possible to implement a queue that supports enqueue and dequeue both in O(1) amortized time. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','Two-stack queue: stack_in (for enqueue) and stack_out (for dequeue). Enqueue: push onto stack_in (O(1)). Dequeue: if stack_out is empty, transfer all elements from stack_in to stack_out (pop from in, push onto out) — this reverses order, giving FIFO. Each element is pushed and popped at most twice (once to in, once to out). Amortized O(1) per operation. This is how some language runtimes implement queue-like behavior with two stacks. Real-world use: task scheduling with priority reversal, undo mechanisms.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the maximum number of nodes at level k of a binary tree?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"k — each level can have at most k nodes"},{"id":"b","text":"2^k — each node at level k-1 can have 2 children, giving 2 × 2^(k-1) = 2^k nodes"},{"id":"c","text":"k² — nodes grow quadratically with level depth"},{"id":"d","text":"2^(k-1) — only the root counts as level 1, so level k has 2^(k-1) nodes"}]','b','Level 0 (root): 2⁰ = 1 node. Level 1: 2¹ = 2 nodes. Level 2: 2² = 4 nodes. This follows directly from binary branching: each level doubles the potential node count of the previous level. The total nodes in a complete binary tree of height h is 2^(h+1) - 1 (geometric series). Option D is the formula for maximum nodes up to and including level k-1, not level k specifically.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the maximum number of nodes in a binary tree of height h (where height = number of edges on the longest path from root to leaf)?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"h + 1 — one more node than the number of edges"},{"id":"b","text":"h² + 1 — quadratic growth with height"},{"id":"c","text":"2^(h+1) - 1 — all levels are completely filled (full binary tree)"},{"id":"d","text":"2^h — only 2^h leaf nodes at depth h"}]','c','A complete binary tree of height h has all levels fully filled except possibly the last, which fills left to right. Maximum nodes: sum from i=0 to h of 2^i = 2^(h+1) - 1 (geometric series formula). Minimum nodes in a tree of height h: h + 1 (degenerate chain). This range from h+1 to 2^(h+1)-1 is why tree shape matters enormously for BST/tree-based algorithm performance. Option D (2^h) is the maximum number of leaf nodes, not total nodes.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','In a Binary Search Tree (BST), what property must hold for every node?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"All nodes in the left subtree have values greater than the node, and all nodes in the right subtree have values less than the node"},{"id":"b","text":"All nodes in the left subtree have values less than the node, and all nodes in the right subtree have values greater than the node"},{"id":"c","text":"Nodes are stored in a max-heap property: parent ≥ left child and parent ≥ right child"},{"id":"d","text":"The tree must be perfectly balanced: left and right subtrees differ in height by at most 1"}]','b','BST invariant: left subtree contains values less than the node''s value; right subtree contains values greater. This enables O(log n) search on average: each comparison eliminates half the remaining tree. Note that ''strictly greater'' on the right (no duplicates, or handle duplicates consistently on one side) is a common convention. Option A reverses the inequality — it would make searching incorrect. Option C describes a max-heap, not a BST. Option D describes an AVL tree property, not a general BST.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the time complexity of searching in a balanced BST with n nodes?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(1) — BST uses a hash-based lookup internally"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n) — BST requires a full traversal in the worst case"},{"id":"c","text":"O(log n) — the search space is halved with each comparison, following the tree height"},{"id":"d","text":"O(n log n) — each comparison requires O(log n) node address calculation"}]','c','In a balanced BST (height ≈ log₂ n), search traverses a single path from root to a leaf, performing at most h = O(log n) comparisons. Each step compares the target with the current node value and recurses left or right. This is the fundamental advantage of search trees over unsorted arrays: O(log n) search instead of O(n) linear scan. The ''balanced'' qualifier is critical — an unbalanced/skewed BST degenerates to O(n) search. Self-balancing trees (AVL, Red-Black) maintain this O(log n) guarantee.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the output of an inorder traversal of the BST below?

        5
       / \
      3    8
     / \   / \
    1   4 6   9','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','b','Inorder traversal (left → root → right) on a BST visits nodes in ascending sorted order. This is a fundamental property: all left-subtree values are smaller, root is between left and right, all right-subtree values are larger. The recursive call stack: leftmost first (1), then 3, then 4, then root 5, then right subtree (6, 8, 9). Option A is preorder (root-first). Option C is reverse inorder (right-root-left, giving descending order). Option D is BFS/level-order traversal.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the time complexity of performing a level-order (BFS) traversal of a binary tree with n nodes?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(log n) — BFS uses a queue and visits nodes in logarithmic layers"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n) — each node is enqueued and dequeued exactly once"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n²) — BFS requires comparing each node with every other node"},{"id":"d","text":"O(1) — BFS uses pointer arithmetic to jump between levels"}]','b','BFS uses a queue: initialize with root, then loop while queue non-empty: pop node, process it, enqueue its children. Each of n nodes is enqueued and dequeued exactly once — O(1) work per node → O(n) total. The queue holds at most the width of the widest level (O(n) worst-case for a complete tree). BFS is ideal for finding shortest paths in unweighted graphs/trees. DFS (recursive or stack-based) also visits every node once → O(n), but differs in space usage (stack depth vs queue width).')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def level_order(root):
    if not root: return []
    result, queue = [], [root]
    while queue:
        node = queue.pop(0)
        result.append(node.val)
        if node.left:  queue.append(node.left)
        if node.right: queue.append(node.right)
    return result

level_order(build_tree([3, 9, 20, None, None, 15, 7]))','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','a','Level-order (BFS) processes nodes by depth: root (3), then level 1 (9, 20), then level 2 (15, 7). The queue ensures FIFO order: left child appended before right, so left-to-right within each level. The tree [3,9,20,None,None,15,7] represents a BinaryTree LeetCode-style array where index i''s children are at 2i+1 and 2i+2, yielding left=9, right=20, left''s children=None, right''s children=15 and 7. Option B has wrong order (20 before 9). Option C is reverse order. Option D has right before left within a level.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','Which traversals produce the output [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] for a left-skewed BST with root 1, right child 2, right child 3...? (Select all that apply)','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"Preorder (root, left, right)"},{"id":"b","text":"Inorder (left, root, right)"},{"id":"c","text":"Postorder (left, right, root)"},{"id":"d","text":"Level-order (BFS)"}]','a,b,d','A left-skewed BST (chain) stores values in strictly ascending order along the left pointers. For such a tree, preorder (root-left-right) visits nodes in insertion order: [1,2,3,4,5]. Inorder of a BST is always sorted ascending: [1,2,3,4,5]. Level-order also visits in ascending order since it''s essentially a linear chain: [1,2,3,4,5]. Postorder visits root last: [2,3,4,5,1] — the root is always processed last in postorder.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','BFS (Breadth-First Search) and DFS (Depth-First Search) both visit every node exactly once. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','BFS and DFS both mark nodes as visited and explore every reachable vertex. BFS uses a queue (FIFO) and processes level by level; DFS uses a stack (LIFO) or recursion and goes deep before backtracking. Both have O(V+E) time complexity (on adjacency list) since each vertex and edge is examined at most once. The difference is the order in which nodes are processed, not the set of nodes visited.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between an adjacency list and an adjacency matrix representation of a graph?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Adjacency list stores edges in a list; adjacency matrix stores vertices in a 2D array"},{"id":"b","text":"Adjacency list is O(V+E) space and O(deg(v)) neighbor lookup; adjacency matrix is O(V²) space and O(1) edge existence check"},{"id":"c","text":"Adjacency matrix is more space-efficient for sparse graphs; adjacency list is better for dense graphs"},{"id":"d","text":"Adjacency list supports only directed graphs; adjacency matrix supports only undirected graphs"}]','b','Adjacency list: array of V lists, where list[i] stores neighbors of vertex i. Space: O(V+E) since only actual edges are stored. Neighbor lookup: O(deg(v)) by scanning the list. Adding an edge: O(1). Edge existence check: O(deg(v)). Adjacency matrix: V×V boolean matrix. Space: O(V²) regardless of edge count. Edge existence check: O(1) via matrix lookup. For sparse graphs (E << V²), adjacency list is vastly more space-efficient. For dense graphs or when edge existence checks are frequent, matrix may win. Option A reverses the definitions. Option C is false (sparse → list, dense → matrix). Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','In a graph with V vertices and E edges, what is the time complexity of performing DFS starting from a single source vertex?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(V) — DFS visits each vertex exactly once"},{"id":"b","text":"O(E) — DFS traverses each edge exactly once"},{"id":"c","text":"O(V+E) — DFS visits each vertex once and traverses each edge once"},{"id":"d","text":"O(V²) — DFS requires examining all possible vertex pairs"}]','c','DFS marks vertices as visited and explores all outgoing edges. Each vertex is visited at most once → O(V). Each edge is examined at most twice (once from each endpoint) → O(E). Combined: O(V+E). This holds for both adjacency list (explore all edges of each visited vertex) and adjacency matrix (scan entire row of V entries for each of V vertices → O(V²)). The O(V+E) bound is tight for adjacency list representation, which is why list representation is preferred for sparse graphs.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the output of a preorder traversal of the BST below?

        5
       / \
      3    8
     / \   / \
    1   4 6   9','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','b','Preorder traversal: root → left → right. Visit order: 5 (root), then left subtree preorder: 3 (root of left) → 1 (leaf) → 4 (leaf), then right subtree: 8 → 6 → 9. Result: [5, 3, 1, 4, 8, 6, 9]. This traversal order is useful for cloning/copying trees (root processed before subtrees, so you know the parent before children) and prefix expression of expression trees. Option A is inorder (BST sorted). Option C is right-root-left traversal. Option D is reverse preorder.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is a topological sort of a directed acyclic graph (DAG), and what algorithm computes it?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A topological sort is an ordering where all edges point from higher to lower indices; it is computed using binary search on the adjacency matrix"},{"id":"b","text":"A topological sort is a linear ordering where for every directed edge u→v, u appears before v; Kahn''s algorithm (BFS with in-degree) or DFS postorder produces it"},{"id":"c","text":"A topological sort is equivalent to sorting vertices by their degree; it is computed using merge sort on the degree sequence"},{"id":"d","text":"A topological sort exists for all directed graphs; if a cycle exists, the algorithm ignores cycle edges"}]','b','Topological sort applies only to DAGs (directed acyclic graphs). Kahn''s algorithm: compute in-degrees of all vertices, initialize queue with zero in-degree vertices, repeatedly remove a vertex (output it), decrement in-degrees of its neighbors, enqueue any that reach zero. DFS approach: perform DFS, add vertex to output list when backtracking (postorder), then reverse the list. Both produce valid topological orderings (which may not be unique). Option A is nonsense. Option C is wrong. Option D is false — topological sort is undefined if a cycle exists.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the space complexity of recursive DFS on a graph with n nodes and maximum recursion depth d?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(1) — DFS uses an explicit stack that is discarded after each call"},{"id":"b","text":"O(V) — the visited set stores all vertices"},{"id":"c","text":"O(d) — the call stack depth is proportional to the maximum recursion depth, which in the worst case equals the number of nodes"},{"id":"d","text":"O(E) — DFS must store all edges in the recursion stack during traversal"}]','c','Recursive DFS uses the call stack implicitly. The maximum stack depth equals the longest path from the start vertex without revisiting a node. In the worst case (tree, or graph with no cycles), this equals the number of nodes O(V). For a balanced tree of height h, the depth is O(log V). The visited set is O(V) space but is separate from recursion depth. Option A is wrong (stack is call stack, not discarded). Option B describes the visited set, not recursion stack. Option D is wrong (edges are not stored in the stack).')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A postorder traversal visits the root of a subtree after all its descendants have been visited. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','Postorder traversal: left → right → root. This means the root is processed after both subtrees are fully explored. This order is essential for deleting/deleting trees (must free children before parent), computing tree height recursively (children computed before parent), and evaluating expression trees (operands before operators).')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A Binary Search Tree (BST) always maintains O(log n) search time regardless of insertion order. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','A plain BST (without self-balancing) has no balance guarantee. Inserting sorted data [1,2,3,4,5] produces a degenerate chain (height = n) → O(n) search, losing the log-height advantage. Self-balancing trees (AVL, Red-Black, B-tree, Treap) maintain height ≈ log n through rotations/rebalancing, preserving O(log n) operations.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def height(root):
    if not root: return 0
    left = height(root.left)
    right = height(root.right)
    return max(left, right) + 1

