height(root)','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','b','The height of a binary tree = number of edges on the longest root-to-leaf path. The longest path is 1→2→4→5 (3 edges). Nodes: 1-2-4-5 on this path. So height = 3 (edges) or equivalently 4 (nodes). The recursive function returns nodes (including current): max(left,right)+1, giving 4. But ''height'' convention varies: some define height as number of edges (3), others as number of nodes on path (4). The question states ''number of edges'' in the option, making option B correct under that definition. Option A counts levels (root at level 1).')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What are the three classic binary tree traversals and their order? (Select all that apply)','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"Inorder — left, root, right (BST produces sorted output)"},{"id":"b","text":"Preorder — root, left, right (used for copying trees, prefix expressions)"},{"id":"c","text":"Postorder — left, right, root (used for tree deletion, postfix expressions)"},{"id":"d","text":"Anti-order — right, left, root (reverse traversal used for validation)"}]','a,b,c','Inorder (left-root-right): BST in sorted order, left subtree first. Preorder (root-left-right): parent before children, used for serialization/copying. Postorder (left-right-root): children before parent, used for deleting trees (free children before parent) and postfix expression evaluation. Anti-order (right-left-root) is a valid traversal (reverse inorder) but not a classic named traversal like the three standard ones.')
