,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the time complexity of inserting a node into a Red-Black tree with n nodes?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(1) — Red-Black trees use hash-based node insertion"},{"id":"b","text":"O(log n) — insertion finds the position in O(log n) and rebalancing takes O(log n) rotations at most"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n) — the tree may require restructuring all n nodes during insertion"},{"id":"d","text":"O(n log n) — each comparison in the search phase costs O(log n)"}]','b','Red-Black trees are self-balancing BSTs. Insertion: (1) BST insert in O(log n) — find the leaf position by traversing from root. (2) Fix violations via rotations and recoloring — at most 2 rotations (amortized) and O(log n) recoloring up the tree. Total: O(log n). The key guarantee: height is always ≤ 2*log₂(n+1), so operations are guaranteed logarithmic. Used in C++ STL (map, set), Java TreeMap, and Linux kernel scheduling.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the output of the following algorithm?

def bst_from_preorder(preorder, bound=float(''inf'')):
    if not preorder or preorder[0] > bound: return None
    val = preorder.pop(0)
    node = TreeNode(val)
    node.left = bst_from_preorder(preorder, val)
    node.right = bst_from_preorder(preorder, bound)
    return node

# preorder = [8, 5, 1, 7, 10, 9, 12]
tree = bst_from_preorder(preorder.copy())
# Print inorder of resulting tree:
print(inorder_traversal(tree))','CODE_OUTPUT','[]','b','This algorithm reconstructs a BST from its preorder traversal using the BST property: all left-subtree values < node, all right-subtree values > node. The bound parameter tracks the valid range. For [8,5,1,7,10,9,12]: 8 is root, 5<8→left subtree, 1<5→left subtree, 7>1,7<5→right child of 1, 10>8→right subtree of 8, 9<10→left child of 10, 12>10→right child of 10. Inorder of any BST (including reconstructed ones) yields sorted ascending order: [1,5,7,8,9,10,12]. Option A is preorder, not inorder. Options C and D have wrong inorder results.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the time complexity of building a BST from a sorted array in optimal fashion?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(n log n) — each insertion into the BST costs O(log n), done n times"},{"id":"b","text":"O(n) — recursively build the BST from the middle element as root (balanced), visiting each element once"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n²) — the sorted order requires O(n) search for each insertion point"},{"id":"d","text":"O(log n) — only the middle element needs to be processed"}]','b','Optimal BST construction from sorted array: pick the middle element as root (ensures balance), recursively build left subtree from left half, right subtree from right half. Each element is visited exactly once during the recursive construction → O(n) time. Space: O(log n) recursion depth for a balanced tree, or O(n) if counting the output tree''s node array. This is much better than inserting n elements one by one (O(n log n)) or inserting sorted elements into a plain BST (O(n²) worst case).')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Both BFS and DFS have O(V+E) time complexity on adjacency list graphs, but differ in space complexity due to the data structure used. True or false?','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','Both BFS and DFS visit each vertex once and examine each edge once → O(V+E) time. The difference is auxiliary space: BFS uses a queue storing at most the widest frontier (O(V) worst-case), while DFS uses a call stack with depth equal to the longest path (O(V) worst-case, but often O(log V) for balanced graphs). The visited set is O(V) for both. For very wide graphs, BFS queue can dominate; for very deep graphs, DFS recursion dominates.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is an AVL tree and how does it differ from a Red-Black tree in terms of balance factor?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"AVL trees and Red-Black trees are identical — the names are synonyms for self-balancing BSTs"},{"id":"b","text":"AVL trees require |height(left) - height(right)| ≤ 1 for every node (stricter balance); Red-Black trees only require root is black and red nodes have black children (more relaxed balance, faster insert/delete)"},{"id":"c","text":"AVL trees use a max-heap ordering; Red-Black trees use a BST ordering"},{"id":"d","text":"Red-Black trees are balanced with O(log n) per operation but AVL trees are not self-balancing"}]','b','AVL trees (named after inventors Adelson-Velsky and Landis) enforce |balance factor| ≤ 1 for every node: the left and right subtree heights differ by at most 1. This is a stricter balance condition than Red-Black trees, meaning AVL trees are more balanced → faster search, but slower insert/delete (more rotations). Red-Black trees have a more relaxed property (coloring rules ensure height ≤ 2*log(n+1)) → faster insert/delete, slightly slower search. AVL is used in databases where search-heavy workloads dominate; Red-Black in language runtimes (C++ STL, Java Collections).')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','How do AVL rotations (single and double) restore balance after an insertion?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"AVL trees use only single rotations (zig/zag) for all imbalance cases; double rotations are unnecessary"},{"id":"b","text":"Single rotation (zig/zag) fixes imbalances at the child level; double rotation (zig-zag or zag-zig) fixes imbalances at the grandchild level where a single rotation would be insufficient"},{"id":"c","text":"AVL rotations rebuild the entire subtree from scratch using the middle element as root, ensuring perfect balance"},{"id":"d","text":"AVL rotations only occur when the tree height exceeds the Red-Black tree maximum of 2*log(n+1)"}]','b','AVL single rotation: used when the imbalance is a direct child of the imbalanced node (e.g., left-left outside case: rotate right). Double rotation: zigzag (left child rotates right, then node rotates left) or zag-zig (right child rotates left, then node rotates right). Double rotation handles cases where the child''s imbalance direction is opposite to the parent''s (grandchild pattern). For example, inserting 1, 2, 3 into an empty AVL tree: after 1,2 are inserted, the tree is imbalanced right-right → single left rotation restores balance.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the minimum number of nodes in an AVL tree of height h, and what recurrence describes it?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"N(h) = N(h-1) + N(h-2) + 1 — the Fibonacci-like recurrence of AVL trees gives near-logarithmic growth"},{"id":"b","text":"N(h) = N(h-1) + N(h-2) + 1 — similar to Fibonacci, giving approximately φ^h nodes where φ ≈ 1.618"},{"id":"c","text":"N(h) = 2N(h-1) + 1 — exponential growth like a full binary tree"},{"id":"d","text":"N(h) = h + 1 — linear, matching the minimum of any binary tree"}]','a','AVL tree minimum node count: N(h) = N(h-1) + N(h-2) + 1 with N(0)=1, N(1)=2. This is nearly Fibonacci (F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2)) but with +1. Solving gives N(h) ≈ φ^(h+1) where φ ≈ 1.618. This means a tree of height h has at least N(h) ≈ 1.618^h nodes, or equivalently height h ≤ log_φ(n) — logarithmic! This is why AVL trees guarantee O(log n) operations. Option B correctly identifies the recurrence and growth but misstates the context. Option C is full tree formula. Option D is degenerate tree.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the minimum number of nodes in an AVL tree of height h?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"N(h) = h + 1 — linear minimum, same as any binary tree"},{"id":"b","text":"N(h) = N(h-1) + N(h-2) + 1 — the AVL recurrence is nearly Fibonacci (F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2)), giving N(h) ≈ 1.618^h nodes and height O(log n)"},{"id":"c","text":"N(h) = 2^(h+1) - 1 — the full binary tree maximum, which is also the minimum"},{"id":"d","text":"N(h) = h² — quadratic minimum for AVL trees"}]','b','AVL minimum node formula: N(0)=1, N(1)=2, N(h)=N(h-1)+N(h-2)+1. This is the Fibonacci recurrence + 1. Solving gives N(h) ≈ φ^(h+2) - 1 where φ≈1.618. Inverting: h ≤ log_φ(n) — logarithmic! This is why AVL trees guarantee O(log n) operations despite being more balanced than plain BSTs. The +1 term in the recurrence makes AVL trees slightly shallower than Fibonacci trees. Option A is the degenerate tree minimum. Option C is the full/perfect tree maximum (not minimum). Option D is wrong.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is a segment tree, and what problems does it solve?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A segment tree is a binary tree where each node stores the minimum of a segment; it supports O(n) range minimum queries but O(n) updates"},{"id":"b","text":"A segment tree is a binary tree built on an array where each node stores an aggregate (min, max, sum) over a range; it supports O(log n) range queries and point updates in O(log n)"},{"id":"c","text":"A segment tree is equivalent to a BST used for searching sorted arrays; it provides O(log n) search and O(n) insert"},{"id":"d","text":"A segment tree is a balanced binary search tree used for range locking in concurrent databases"}]','b','Segment tree (interval tree): built on an array of size n. Leaves store individual elements; internal node stores aggregate (sum, min, max, GCD, etc.) of its children''s range. A node covering range [l,r] has children covering [l,mid] and [mid+1,r]. Range query (range aggregate) traverses O(log n) nodes (the query covers ~2log n nodes in the tree). Point update updates O(log n) nodes (path from leaf to root). Space: 2n-1 nodes. Used for static range queries with point updates. Fenwick tree (BIT) is a more space-efficient alternative for associative operations (sum, product).')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the time complexity of BST deletion when the node has two children?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"O(1) — the node is replaced with its inorder successor in one step"},{"id":"b","text":"O(log n) — find the inorder successor (minimum of right subtree), replace the node''s value, and delete the successor node (which has at most one child)"},{"id":"c","text":"O(n) — the entire right subtree must be traversed to find the replacement"},{"id":"d","text":"O(n log n) — BST deletion requires O(log n) search plus O(n) to restructure the tree"}]','b','BST deletion when node has two children: find the inorder successor (IOS = minimum node of right subtree, or inorder predecessor = maximum of left subtree). Copy the successor''s value into the target node, then delete the successor node (which has at most one child → easy deletion). The search for IOS is O(log n) for balanced BST, O(h) for unbalanced. Total: O(log n) for balanced, O(n) for skewed. This is why BST deletion of two-child nodes is more complex than one-child or leaf nodes. Option A is wrong. Option C overestimates. Option D miscounts.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the key difference between HTTP POST and GET methods?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"GET sends data in the request body; POST appends data to the URL query string"},{"id":"b","text":"GET requests are idempotent (safe, cacheable) and send data in the URL; POST requests are non-idempotent and send data in the request body"},{"id":"c","text":"POST is faster than GET because it bypasses URL parsing"},{"id":"d","text":"GET can handle binary file uploads; POST cannot"}]','b','GET is idempotent (no side effect on the server) and sends parameters in the URL query string — making results bookmarkable and cacheable. POST sends data in the request body (not in the URL), is non-idempotent by default, and should be used for submitting forms, creating resources, or triggering actions. Option A reverses the two. Option C is false (performance difference is negligible). Option D is false — both can technically carry binary data, but file uploads conventionally use POST.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is a CDN (Content Delivery Network) and what problem does it solve?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A CDN caches static assets at edge servers close to users, reducing latency and offloading traffic from origin servers"},{"id":"b","text":"A CDN runs application logic at the edge to replace traditional application servers"},{"id":"c","text":"A CDN is a distributed database that stores user session data across multiple regions"},{"id":"d","text":"A CDN is a load balancer that routes traffic between availability zones within a region"}]','a','CDNs cache static content (images, CSS, JS, fonts, video) at geographically distributed edge PoPs (points of presence). Instead of every user hitting the origin server, requests are served from the nearest edge — reducing round-trip latency, lowering bandwidth costs, and providing DDoS protection. CDNs do not run application logic (that''s edge functions, a different concept). Option B describes edge computing, not CDN caching. Option C describes a distributed session store, not CDN. Option D describes a load balancer.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is sticky sessions (session affinity) in load balancing?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A technique that binds a user''s requests to a specific server using a cookie or IP hash; useful when server-side session storage is not available"},{"id":"b","text":"A way to prevent any server from caching user sessions by forcing all sessions to be stored in a shared database"},{"id":"c","text":"A load balancing algorithm that distributes traffic equally using round-robin regardless of server load"},{"id":"d","text":"A method of encrypting session tokens before sending them over HTTPS"}]','a','Sticky sessions route all requests from the same user to the same backend server using a cookie (e.g., JSESSIONID) or source IP hash. This works around the problem of in-memory sessions being lost when a load balancer routes requests to different servers. However, it creates load imbalance and reduces horizontal scalability — the preferred approach is shared session storage (Redis/Memcached) without sticky sessions. Option B describes session storage strategy, not affinity. Option C describes round-robin, not sticky sessions. Option D describes TLS encryption.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What are the HTTP status code ranges and their meanings?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"1xx informational, 2xx success, 3xx redirection, 4xx client error, 5xx server error"},{"id":"b","text":"1xx server errors, 2xx client errors, 3xx success, 4xx redirects, 5xx informational"},{"id":"c","text":"1xx resource moved, 2xx found, 3xx not modified, 4xx auth required, 5xx server overloaded"},{"id":"d","text":"1xx-3xx are client errors, 4xx-5xx are server errors"}]','a','Standard HTTP status ranges: 1xx (Informational: request received, continuing), 2xx (Success: action received and accepted), 3xx (Redirection: further action needed), 4xx (Client Error: bad syntax or impossible request), 5xx (Server Error: server failed to fulfill valid request). Common codes to know: 200 OK, 201 Created, 204 No Content, 301/302 Redirect, 304 Not Modified, 400 Bad Request, 401 Unauthorized, 403 Forbidden, 404 Not Found, 429 Too Many Requests, 500 Internal Server Error, 502 Bad Gateway, 503 Service Unavailable. Option B reverses 1xx/2xx meanings. Option C is inaccurate. Option D miscategorizes 4xx/5xx.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is a reverse proxy, and how does it differ from a forward proxy?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A reverse proxy and forward proxy are identical — both sit between clients and the internet"},{"id":"b","text":"A forward proxy represents clients to the internet (client-side privacy); a reverse proxy represents backend servers to the internet (server-side aggregation, TLS termination, caching, load balancing)"},{"id":"c","text":"A reverse proxy is used only for caching static images; a forward proxy handles all traffic types"},{"id":"d","text":"A forward proxy routes traffic within a data center; a reverse proxy routes traffic between data centers"}]','b','A forward proxy (e.g., corporate proxy, VPN) acts on behalf of clients — hiding their identity from servers, bypassing content filters, enabling cache sharing. A reverse proxy (e.g., Nginx, HAProxy, Cloudflare) acts on behalf of backend servers — terminating TLS, aggregating multiple backend services, providing load balancing, caching, and static file serving. Users interact with the reverse proxy without knowing about the backend architecture. Nginx as a reverse proxy for a microservice cluster is a common example. Option A is false. Option C is too narrow. Option D is incorrect.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the primary difference between a SQL (relational) database and a NoSQL database in terms of schema?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"SQL databases require no schema; NoSQL databases enforce a strict schema on write"},{"id":"b","text":"SQL databases enforce a fixed schema at write time (schema-on-write) — data must conform to table definitions; NoSQL databases typically use schema-on-read — structure is interpreted at read time and can vary per document"},{"id":"c","text":"Both SQL and NoSQL databases use schema-on-write; the difference is only query language"},{"id":"d","text":"NoSQL databases have no concept of schema — they store data without any structural definition"}]','b','Schema-on-write (SQL): the database enforces that data conforms to table definitions when written — invalid data is rejected. Schema-on-read (NoSQL/document): data is stored without enforced structure; the application interprets the structure when reading. Schema-on-read enables flexible data models (e.g., storing different attributes per document), which is useful when the data model evolves rapidly or differs across entities. Schema-on-write provides stronger data integrity guarantees at the cost of flexibility. Option A is incorrect. Option C is false. Option D overstates — NoSQL stores data with structure, just without enforcing it at write time.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the main purpose of a message queue in a distributed system?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"To permanently store all messages forever so they can be replayed at any time"},{"id":"b","text":"To decouple producers from consumers by temporarily holding messages — producers send messages and return immediately; consumers retrieve messages at their own pace, enabling asynchronous processing and fault tolerance"},{"id":"c","text":"To route messages directly from producers to the correct consumer using real-time connection management"},{"id":"d","text":"To provide a backup storage mechanism when a database is temporarily unavailable"}]','b','A message queue decouples producers (senders) from consumers (receivers) in both time and space. Producers publish messages and return immediately — they don''t wait for consumers to process. Consumers pull messages at their own pace. This enables: asynchronous processing, load leveling (absorb traffic spikes), fault tolerance (messages persist if consumers are down), and independent scaling of producers and consumers. Queues are temporary stores (messages are deleted after successful processing). They are not permanent archives (that''s an event store). Option A overstates persistence. Option C describes direct routing, not queuing. Option D is not the primary purpose.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What does API versioning mean, and why is it important in REST API design?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"API versioning means incrementing the API''s major version number every time a bug is fixed"},{"id":"b","text":"API versioning is the practice of maintaining backward compatibility across different versions of an API contract — allowing clients on old versions to continue working while new versions introduce breaking changes; common formats: URL path (/v1/users), header (Accept: application/vnd.api+json; version=1), or query string"},{"id":"c","text":"API versioning is only necessary when switching from REST to GraphQL"},{"id":"d","text":"API versioning is a security mechanism that prevents unauthorized clients from accessing the API"}]','b','API versioning manages breaking changes (renamed fields, changed response structure, removed endpoints) without disrupting existing clients. Clients explicitly opt into a version. Breaking changes are introduced in a new version; old versions remain supported for a deprecation window. URL path versioning (/v1/) is the most explicit and widely used (Stripe, Twilio, GitHub). Header versioning is more REST-idiomatic (Content-Type negotiation). Query string versioning (?version=2) is simple but pollutes URLs. Versioning in the path is the most common and visible approach for public APIs. Option A is false. Option C is false. Option D describes authentication, not versioning.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','Which caching strategy writes data to the cache synchronously at the same time as writing to the database?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Write-back (write-behind) — writes to cache immediately and flushes to database asynchronously"},{"id":"b","text":"Write-through — both the cache and the database are updated synchronously in the same operation; both must succeed before the write is acknowledged"},{"id":"c","text":"Cache-aside (lazy loading) — data is written only to the database; the cache is populated on the next read"},{"id":"d","text":"Read-through — the cache reads from the database and populates itself before returning data"}]','b','Write-through updates both cache and database synchronously and atomically. The write is acknowledged only after both succeed. Cache always holds consistent, up-to-date data. Slower than write-behind (two I/O operations) but eliminates the risk of stale data and crash-loss scenarios. Write-behind (A) is faster but risks losing data if the process crashes between the cache write and the DB write. Cache-aside (C) only writes to the DB, not the cache. Read-through (D) is a read strategy, not a write strategy. The question asks for a write caching strategy that writes to both synchronously.')
,(NULL,'JUNIOR','What is the difference between horizontal scaling and vertical scaling?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Horizontal scaling adds more machines to a pool; vertical scaling adds more CPU, RAM, and storage to a single existing machine"},{"id":"b","text":"Both terms describe the same thing — they are synonyms used interchangeably in cloud documentation"},{"id":"c","text":"Vertical scaling is unlimited; horizontal scaling is limited by the physical capacity of a single machine"},{"id":"d","text":"Horizontal scaling is faster because it doesn''t require copying data between machines"}]','a','Horizontal scaling (scaling out) adds more machines to a pool, distributing load across nodes. Vertical scaling (scaling up) upgrades a single machine with more resources. Horizontal is preferred for fault tolerance and near-unlimited scale but requires stateless design and introduces distributed systems complexity (consistency, network partitions). Vertical scaling is simpler but hits a hardware ceiling and creates a single point of failure. Option B is false. Option C reverses the constraints. Option D is not necessarily true — scaling out involves distributing work, not just copying data.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What does the CAP theorem state, and which two properties can a distributed system guarantee at any given moment?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A distributed system can guarantee all three: Consistency, Availability, and Partition Tolerance simultaneously"},{"id":"b","text":"CAP states that during a network partition, you must choose between Consistency and Availability; without partition, you can have both"},{"id":"c","text":"CAP is only relevant for database systems; microservices are exempt"},{"id":"d","text":"Consistency, Availability, and Partition Tolerance are always guaranteed, but Performance degrades when two are strong"}]','b','The CAP theorem (Brewer''s theorem) states that a distributed data store can provide at most two of three guarantees during a network partition: Consistency (all nodes see the same data at the same time), Availability (every request gets a response), and Partition Tolerance (the system continues operating when network partitions occur). Since partitions are unavoidable in real networks, the real choice is CP (prioritize consistency, sacrifice availability during partition) or AP (prioritize availability, allow stale reads during partition). Option A is false (impossible per CAP). Option C is false. Option D is a misreading of PACELC, not CAP.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is database indexing, and what is the trade-off when creating an index?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"An index creates a sorted copy of a column''s data, enabling O(log n) lookups instead of O(n) full table scans at the cost of extra storage and slower writes"},{"id":"b","text":"An index compresses table data to reduce disk usage; reads are faster but writes are faster too due to better locality"},{"id":"c","text":"An index is a primary key that uniquely identifies each row; it has no trade-offs because databases are optimized for it"},{"id":"d","text":"An index speeds up reads but has no effect on write performance"}]','a','A database index (commonly a B+ tree) maintains a sorted data structure mapped to row locations, enabling logarithmic seek for queries targeting indexed columns. The cost: extra disk/memory storage, and slower writes (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE must update both the table and all relevant indexes). Index selection is a trade-off: columns used in WHERE, JOIN, and ORDER BY benefit; columns with low cardinality (e.g., gender) may not help much. Over-indexing a write-heavy table hurts throughput significantly. Option B is false (writes are slower, not faster). Option C describes a primary key constraint, not a general index. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is sharding (horizontal partitioning) of a database, and what are common sharding keys?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Sharding distributes rows of a table across multiple database servers using a shard key; user_id or tenant_id are common choices that enable even distribution"},{"id":"b","text":"Sharding is a vertical partitioning strategy that splits hot and cold columns into separate tables on the same server"},{"id":"c","text":"Sharding is a replication strategy that creates multiple read-only copies of the database for redundancy"},{"id":"d","text":"Sharding requires that every query include the shard key to route to the correct node; queries without the shard key require scatter-gather across all shards"}]','a','Sharding (horizontal partitioning) splits rows of a logical table across N physical database servers (shards). A shard key (e.g., user_id, date, region) determines which shard owns each row. Good shard keys distribute load evenly — a poor key (e.g., country code) can create hotspots on one shard. Cross-shard queries (joins, aggregations) are expensive and often require scatter-gather or denormalization. Option B describes vertical partitioning (splitting columns). Option C describes read replicas. Option D''s statement about requiring the shard key is generally true but the statement format mixes it with cross-shard query cost — the correct answer highlights the key properties cleanly.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What are the key differences between REST and GraphQL APIs, and in which scenarios is GraphQL superior?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"GraphQL is always faster than REST because it uses a binary protocol; REST uses JSON which is slow"},{"id":"b","text":"REST uses multiple endpoints with fixed response shapes; GraphQL uses a single endpoint with a query language that lets clients specify exactly which fields they need — superior for mobile clients, third-party consumers, and complex UI data requirements where clients need different subsets of the same entity"},{"id":"c","text":"GraphQL replaces REST entirely for all API use cases; REST is legacy technology"},{"id":"d","text":"REST and GraphQL are both SQL-like query languages with minor syntactic differences"}]','b','REST: multiple endpoints (/users, /orders, /products); the server decides the response shape. GraphQL: single endpoint; clients write queries specifying exactly which fields and nested relationships they need. GraphQL advantages: (1) eliminates over-fetching/under-fetching — clients get exactly what they need, (2) single endpoint simplifies consumer integration, (3) strong typing enables developer tooling and introspection. GraphQL disadvantages: complexity, potential N+1 query problems (requires DataLoader pattern), caching is harder. Best for: complex client-driven data requirements, mobile APIs, aggregating multiple services. Not ideal for: simple CRUD APIs, public APIs where you want server-controlled response shapes. Option A is false. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the main benefit of using gRPC over REST for internal microservice communication?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"gRPC uses HTTP/2 with binary Protobuf serialization, providing smaller payloads, multiplexing, and bidirectional streaming — faster and more efficient than REST JSON over HTTP/1.1 for high-volume internal calls"},{"id":"b","text":"gRPC is language-agnostic in the same way REST is; the main difference is the API naming convention"},{"id":"c","text":"gRPC uses UDP for transport which is faster than TCP used by REST"},{"id":"d","text":"gRPC automatically handles service discovery and load balancing without any configuration"}]','a','gRPC (Google Remote Procedure Calls) uses HTTP/2 for transport (multiplexing, header compression) and Protocol Buffers (binary serialization — smaller, faster to parse than JSON). Key advantages: (1) binary serialization is ~5-10x faster than JSON parsing, (2) strongly typed .proto contracts enable code generation for many languages, (3) bidirectional streaming — clients and servers can stream data simultaneously, (4) HTTP/2 multiplexing eliminates head-of-line blocking. Best for: internal service-to-service calls where performance matters, streaming use cases (chat, real-time data). Not ideal for: external public APIs where browser compatibility and simplicity matter more (REST/GraphQL are better). Option B is false. Option C is false (gRPC uses HTTP/2 over TCP). Option D requires separate tooling.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is consistent hashing and what problem does it solve in distributed systems?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Consistent hashing maps keys and servers onto a ring (hash ring); adding or removing nodes only remaps a fraction of keys, minimizing cache/shard redistribution compared to modulo hashing"},{"id":"b","text":"Consistent hashing ensures that all nodes in a distributed system always agree on the same value for a given key, regardless of network latency"},{"id":"c","text":"Consistent hashing uses a deterministic hash function that always produces the same result on any node — it is not affected by network partitions"},{"id":"d","text":"Consistent hashing is a load balancing algorithm that distributes requests evenly using a modulo of current load divided by total capacity"}]','a','In standard modulo hashing (hash(key) % N servers), adding or removing a server remaps almost all keys — causing a cache/shard miss storm. Consistent hashing maps both servers and keys onto a circular hash space (ring); a key is owned by the nearest server clockwise on the ring. When a server is added or removed, only adjacent keys on the ring are remapped (O(1/n) fraction). Virtual nodes (replicas) further distribute load more evenly across physical nodes. Used in DynamoDB, Cassandra, Memcached, Redis Cluster. Option B describes linearizability, not consistent hashing. Option C is misleading. Option D describes weighted round-robin.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is event sourcing and how does it compare to traditional CRUD (state-based) persistence?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Event sourcing stores the full sequence of state-changing events (journal) rather than current state; current state is derived by replaying events — enabling audit trails, temporal queries, and replay-based debugging"},{"id":"b","text":"Event sourcing is equivalent to a traditional database with ACID transactions; the difference is only the API naming (save vs publish)"},{"id":"c","text":"Event sourcing is a messaging pattern used in message queues; it has no relationship to database persistence"},{"id":"d","text":"Event sourcing requires CQRS — you cannot use event sourcing without also implementing command query responsibility segregation"}]','a','Instead of storing current state (UPDATE row SET balance = 100), event sourcing stores every domain event (AccountOpened, Deposit(50), Withdrawal(10)...) in an append-only log. Current state is computed by replaying the event log. Benefits: full history, temporal queries (''what was my balance on Jan 1?''), event replay for debugging, and easy integration with event-driven microservices. Challenges: event schema evolution (upcasting), eventual consistency, and snapshot strategies for long-lived aggregates. Option B is false. Option C is false. Option D is false — CQRS and event sourcing are complementary but independently optional patterns.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation) and the standard layered architecture?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"CQRS separates the data models for read and write operations: a single data model handles both commands (writes) and queries (reads) in standard architecture; CQRS uses dedicated read models optimized for query patterns and write models optimized for command validation"},{"id":"b","text":"CQRS is a message queuing pattern; it has no relationship to how data models are designed"},{"id":"c","text":"CQRS requires two separate databases — one for commands and one for queries — connected via database-level replication"},{"id":"d","text":"CQRS is only applicable to microservices and cannot be used in monolithic applications"}]','a','Standard layered architecture uses the same data model for both reads and writes (e.g., a User entity for both creating users and listing them). CQRS separates these: Command model handles writes (business logic, validation), Query model handles reads (optimized for specific query patterns, possibly a different schema or even a different database). CQRS enables read and write optimization independently, supports event sourcing naturally, and allows different teams to work on read vs. write side. Often combined with event sourcing. Complexity cost is high — only use CQRS when read/write patterns are significantly different. Option B is false. Option C overstates (can be in-memory read models). Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is PACELC, and how does it extend the CAP theorem?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"PACELC states that during a partition, you choose between Consistency and Availability (same as CAP); when there is no partition, you choose between Latency and Consistency — stronger consistency requires synchronous replication with higher write latency"},{"id":"b","text":"PACELC replaces CAP entirely and states that all three properties (Consistency, Availability, Latency) can always be maximized simultaneously"},{"id":"c","text":"PACELC is only relevant for single-node databases with no network topology"},{"id":"d","text":"PACELC describes a trade-off between Partition tolerance and Eventual consistency — latency is not a factor"}]','a','PACELC (Brewer, 2012) adds Latency as a first-class dimension: even without a partition, you face a Latency vs. Consistency trade-off. A system that synchronously replicates writes to all replicas for strong consistency incurs higher write latency. DynamoDB: PB (write latency vs. availability), PC/EC (consistency vs. latency). Cassandra: PA/E (availability vs. consistency) + EL (latency vs. consistency). CAP doesn''t capture latency; PACELC does. This is critical for geo-distributed systems where cross-region write latency is a key design decision. Option B is false. Option C is false. Option D mischaracterizes PACELC.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the primary role of DNS (Domain Name System) in web architecture, and what are the main DNS record types relevant to system design?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"DNS translates human-readable domain names to IP addresses; relevant record types include A (IPv4 address), AAAA (IPv6 address), CNAME (alias to another domain), and MX (mail server) — which are used to route traffic to application servers, CDNs, and email systems"},{"id":"b","text":"DNS is a load balancer that routes HTTP traffic to the least-loaded server based on real-time CPU usage"},{"id":"c","text":"DNS is only used during the initial domain registration process and is not relevant after a site is deployed"},{"id":"d","text":"DNS records are static and never change after they are first set — they cannot be updated without taking the site offline"}]','a','DNS is the global phonebook of the internet — resolving domain names to IP addresses. A record maps a domain to an IPv4 address. AAAA maps to IPv6. CNAME creates an alias (e.g., www.example.com → example.com or cdn.example.com → cdn.cloudflare.com). MX records route email. TTL (Time To Live) determines how long DNS responses are cached before re-resolution. Low TTLs enable rapid failover and blue-green deployments; high TTLs reduce query load. DNS is hierarchical (root → TLD → authoritative nameserver) and uses caching extensively. Option B confuses DNS with Anycast and load balancing. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between TLS 1.2 and TLS 1.3 in terms of handshake speed and security?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"TLS 1.3 reduces the handshake from 2 round trips to 1 by eliminating insecure cipher suites, removing SHA-1, and requiring forward secrecy — making it both faster and more secure than TLS 1.2"},{"id":"b","text":"TLS 1.2 and TLS 1.3 are functionally identical; TLS 1.3 is just a newer version number"},{"id":"c","text":"TLS 1.3 is slower because it uses stronger encryption algorithms that require more computation"},{"id":"d","text":"TLS 1.3 removes all cipher suites and cannot be used with any existing server software"}]','a','TLS 1.3 (RFC 8446) improves over TLS 1.2: (1) 1-RTT handshake (vs 2-RTT in TLS 1.2) — 0-RTT resumption mode for returning clients, (2) removes insecure features: SHA-1, 3DES, CBC ciphers, export ciphers, static RSA/ Diffie-Hellman key exchange, (3) mandates forward secrecy — compromising a long-term key cannot decrypt past sessions, (4) cleaner protocol design. TLS 1.2 is still widely deployed but TLS 1.3 should be preferred where supported — both performance (fewer round trips) and security (fewer attack surfaces) advantages. Option B is false. Option C is false (handshake is faster even though algorithms are strong). Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between a service mesh and an API gateway in microservices architecture?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A service mesh and an API gateway are the same thing with different names — both handle all internal and external traffic"},{"id":"b","text":"An API gateway is the single entry point for external client traffic (North-South traffic); a service mesh handles service-to-service (East-West) traffic within the cluster via sidecar proxies — they address different traffic directions and are complementary, not interchangeable"},{"id":"c","text":"A service mesh replaces the API gateway entirely by routing all external and internal traffic"},{"id":"d","text":"An API gateway uses sidecar proxies; a service mesh does not use proxies"}]','b','North-South (external client → cluster): API gateway (Kong, AWS API Gateway, Envoy as gateway) handles auth, rate limiting, routing, TLS termination at the perimeter. East-West (service-to-service within cluster): service mesh (Istio, Linkerd) uses sidecar proxies (Envoy) to handle mTLS, retries, circuit breaking, traffic splitting between services without application changes. They are complementary layers: the gateway sits at the cluster boundary, the mesh operates inside. Option A is false. Option C overstates — mesh handles internal traffic; gateway handles external. Option D reverses: gateway is a standalone component; mesh uses sidecar proxies.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: DNS uses UDP by default for lookups, which means DNS responses are not reliable and cannot be trusted.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','DNS primarily uses UDP on port 53 for lookups (fast, low overhead). However, DNS responses include a transaction ID for matching queries to responses, and resolvers implement retry logic and caching to handle reliability. For large responses exceeding UDP packet size, TCP is used (truncated flag in UDP response signals this). DNSSEC adds cryptographic verification of DNS responses to prevent spoofing. The lack of built-in reliability in UDP is addressed by resolver retry behavior and the caching layer (recursive resolvers cache TTL-based responses). DNS is designed to be resilient and reliable despite using UDP as its primary protocol.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: A system can be both CP (consistent and partition-tolerant) and AP (available and partition-tolerant) at the same time by using different databases for different operations.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','The CAP theorem applies per-data-record or per-operation, not per-system. A system can support both CP and AP operations for different data types (e.g., Cassandra using quorum for CP operations and ''any'' read for AP operations) — but for a given read, you cannot simultaneously guarantee both strong consistency and availability during a partition. The ''choice'' (CP or AP) is made at the operation level, and the system must commit to one per-operation contract. Some modern databases offer tunable consistency (Cassandra, DynamoDB) but each specific consistency level is still a CP or AP choice. You cannot be simultaneously CP and AP for the same data at the same time.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: REST APIs must always use JSON as their response format.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','REST does not mandate JSON. REST (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style based on resources and HTTP verbs — it does not prescribe a serialization format. While JSON is the most common format for REST APIs (due to its universal browser support and readability), REST can use any format: XML (application/xml), Protocol Buffers (application/x-protobuf), MessagePack (application/msgpack), or even HTML (application/xhtml+xml) for browser-based clients. The Content-Type header declares the format. The key REST constraints are: client-server, stateless, cacheable, layered system, uniform interface. Format is an implementation detail.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: Rate limiting and API throttling are the same concept implemented differently at the network layer vs. application layer.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','Rate limiting enforces a maximum number of requests per time window (e.g., 1000 requests/minute per API key) — typically returning HTTP 429 Too Many Requests when exceeded. Throttling (in the traditional sense) slows down responses to abusive clients without rejecting them — returning deferred responses. In some API gateway contexts, ''throttling'' refers to enforced rate limits, but technically they are different: rate limiting is a hard quota enforcement, throttling is deferred processing. Both can be implemented at network layer (Nginx limit_req), application layer, or API gateway. The distinction matters for UX: rate limiting is an abrupt stop; throttling is a slow-down.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the Raft consensus algorithm and what problem does it solve?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Raft is a leader election and log replication algorithm that achieves consensus in a distributed system; a leader receives writes, replicates to followers, and confirms after a majority acknowledges"},{"id":"b","text":"Raft is a gossip protocol that propagates state changes across nodes using eventual consistency without a leader"},{"id":"c","text":"Raft guarantees linearizability for all reads without a leader, similar to read-your-writes consistency"},{"id":"d","text":"Raft is a two-phase commit protocol variant used for distributed transactions within a single database cluster"}]','a','Raft solves distributed consensus: electing a leader, replicating log entries from the leader to followers, and ensuring safety despite node failures. Writes go through the leader; the leader replicates entries to a majority of followers before committing. Reads can be served by the leader. Raft requires majority (quorum) for committing — 3-node cluster tolerates 1 failure, 5-node tolerates 2. Option B describes gossip protocols (e.g., Cassandra, SWIM), not Raft. Option C describes linearizability without a leader (not Raft). Option D confuses Raft with 2PC.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Which properties of DNS make it vulnerable to DNS spoofing (cache poisoning), and what modern DNS security mechanism mitigates this?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"DNS is vulnerable because it uses UDP without authentication; the mitigation is switching all DNS lookups to TCP"},{"id":"b","text":"DNS spoofing exploits the lack of authentication in DNS responses (no cryptographic verification); DNSSEC (DNS Security Extensions) adds digital signatures to DNS records — resolvers verify the signature using public keys anchored at the root zone — ensuring responses are authentic and not tampered with"},{"id":"c","text":"DNS cache poisoning is caused by large response sizes; the mitigation is to limit DNS response sizes to under 512 bytes"},{"id":"d","text":"DNSSEC is deployed universally and all domain registrars support it by default"}]','b','DNS spoofing (cache poisoning): an attacker floods a recursive resolver with forged DNS responses before the legitimate response arrives, poisoning the cache with incorrect IP mappings (redirecting to malicious sites). Classic defense: random source ports + random transaction IDs made prediction harder but are not cryptographically strong. DNSSEC (RFC 4033) adds: (1) digital signatures (RRSIG) over DNS record sets, (2) chain of trust from root zone down, (3) DS records for delegated zones. Resolvers verify signatures before caching. DNSSEC adoption is incomplete (not universally deployed), and it does not encrypt DNS queries (that''s DoT/DoH). Option A is incomplete. Option C is incorrect. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the difference between the Paxos and Raft consensus algorithms, and why was Raft created?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Paxos and Raft are functionally identical; Raft was created to use a different programming language"},{"id":"b","text":"Paxos is the foundational distributed consensus algorithm (Lamport, 1998) with two phases (prepare, accept) that is proven correct but notoriously difficult to understand and implement; Raft was designed with the explicit goal of understandability — it separates leader election, log replication, and safety into distinct, comprehensible components while providing equivalent safety guarantees"},{"id":"c","text":"Raft is faster than Paxos because it uses fewer network round trips per consensus decision"},{"id":"d","text":"Paxos requires a majority quorum; Raft tolerates more failures by not requiring quorum"}]','b','Paxos (Single-Decree Paxos, Multi-Paxos) is proven correct but has a reputation for being extremely difficult to understand and implement correctly — Lamport''s original paper is famously opaque. Raft (Ongaro & Ousterhout, 2014) was designed with understandability as the primary goal: clear separation of subproblems (leader election, log replication, safety, membership changes), strong leader assumption, and fewer corner cases. Both provide safety (liveness not guaranteed). In practice, Raft is more widely implemented in open-source systems (etcd, CockroachDB, TiKV). Multi-Paxos can be more efficient for high-throughput writes (using a stable leader). Option A is false. Option C is not the primary motivation. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','A social media platform needs to store user timelines for 500 million users. Reads (loading a user''s feed) happen 100x more frequently than writes (new posts appearing in feeds). The system must tolerate data center failures. What caching architecture best addresses this?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Store all timelines in a single Redis cluster with a 24-hour TTL; on new post, push to all followers'' cached timelines"},{"id":"b","text":"Use fan-out-on-read: cache each post individually; when a user loads their timeline, fetch and merge recent posts from the people they follow; this avoids write amplification from pushing to millions of followers for celebrity accounts"},{"id":"c","text":"Store timelines in a distributed SQL database with read replicas; use consistent hashing to distribute reads across replicas"},{"id":"d","text":"Fan-out-on-write (push model) works for all social media use cases because it ensures timelines are always pre-computed"}]','b','Twitter/Facebook-style timelines use fan-out-on-read (pull model) to handle the ''celebrity problem'': pushing a post to a million follower timelines causes massive write amplification. Fan-out-on-read: post is cached individually by post_id; on timeline load, the system fetches recent posts from followed users (from cache) and merges/sorts. Celebrity accounts (high follower count) are handled specially — their posts may be cached at a higher tier. Hybrid: fan-out-on-write for normal users, fan-out-on-read for high-follower accounts. Option A misdescribes a push model. Option C is not the primary solution for social media timelines (joins are expensive). Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the difference between database replication lag and eventual consistency, and how do you monitor and mitigate replication lag in a production MySQL primary-replica setup?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Replication lag and eventual consistency are the same concept measured differently; they are both caused by the same hardware limitation"},{"id":"b","text":"Replication lag is the time delay between a write being committed on the primary and being applied on a replica; eventual consistency means replicas may serve stale reads; monitoring: show slave status (Seconds_Behind_Master), pt-heartbeat; mitigation: use semi-synchronous replication, configure replica with adequate hardware, use read-after-write routing (read from primary for recent writes)"},{"id":"c","text":"Replication lag only affects write performance, not read performance; eventual consistency only affects reads"},{"id":"d","text":"Replication lag cannot be monitored in MySQL — it requires a separate monitoring system"}]','b','Replication lag: delay in applying changes from primary to replica (in MySQL async replication). If lagging, reads from replicas return stale data — an instance of eventual consistency. Monitoring: SHOW SLAVE STATUS shows Seconds_Behind_Master (though it''s approximate), pt-heartbeat provides more accurate lag measurement, Percona Monitoring and Management (PMM) provides graphs. Mitigation strategies: (1) semi-synchronous replication (primary waits for at least one replica to acknowledge before committing), (2) ensure replica has equivalent hardware (disk I/O is often the bottleneck), (3) shard writes across primaries, (4) for critical read-after-write, route reads to primary. Option A conflates the terms incorrectly. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Your system uses Kafka for event streaming. A topic has 12 partitions and 4 consumers in a consumer group. How many consumers can process messages concurrently, and what happens to the remaining consumers?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"All 4 consumers can process messages simultaneously — Kafka distributes messages across all consumers in the group"},{"id":"b","text":"At most 4 consumers process messages concurrently (one per assigned partition); with 12 partitions, each of the 4 consumers is assigned 3 partitions; the remaining consumers (if any) sit idle waiting for a partition to become available when another consumer leaves"},{"id":"c","text":"Kafka uses a round-robin assignment to all 12 consumers — if only 4 exist, Kafka creates 8 virtual consumers to fill the gap"},{"id":"d","text":"The topic must have at least as many partitions as consumers for any messages to be consumed"}]','b','Kafka partitions are the unit of parallelism for a consumer group. Each partition can only be assigned to one consumer at a time. With 12 partitions and 4 consumers: each consumer gets 3 partitions (Kafka distributes evenly). A consumer with no assigned partitions sits idle — it cannot process messages until another consumer in the group leaves or the partition count increases. This is why partition count should be >= expected maximum consumer count. If you want more parallelism, increase partition count (up to the broker limit and throughput capacity). Consumer count > partition count wastes consumers. Option A is false. Option C is false. Option D is backwards (messages still flow, just less parallelism).')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is the ''split-brain'' problem in distributed systems, and what quorum-based strategies prevent it in consensus systems?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Split-brain occurs when two nodes in a cluster both believe they are the primary and accept conflicting writes; quorum-based prevention requires that writes be acknowledged by a majority (>50%) of nodes — if a minority partition loses quorum, it stops accepting writes, preventing conflicting writes"},{"id":"b","text":"Split-brain is caused by network latency and can be eliminated by adding more CPU cores to each node"},{"id":"c","text":"Split-brain only affects MySQL databases; NoSQL databases are immune because they use eventual consistency"},{"id":"d","text":"Quorum requires unanimous agreement from all nodes before any write is accepted"}]','a','Split-brain: a network partition divides a cluster into two groups, each believing the other is dead and both trying to act as primary — accepting conflicting writes. This results in diverged data states (two ''brains'' with different data). Quorum-based prevention: require that any write be acknowledged by a majority (more than half) of nodes. With a majority quorum, at most one partition group can have a quorum — the other group refuses writes, preventing divergence. Example: 5-node cluster tolerates 2-node failure (3-node quorum required). If 3+ nodes can communicate, they form a quorum and continue; 2-node partition cannot accept writes. This is how Raft, Paxos, and Cassandra''s quorum writes prevent split-brain. Option B is unrelated. Option C is false. Option D overstates.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Your company needs to migrate a legacy monolithic application to microservices incrementally. What migration strategy would you use and why?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Rewrite the entire monolith from scratch in microservices — this is faster than incremental migration because you don''t carry legacy debt"},{"id":"b","text":"Use the strangler fig pattern: place an API gateway in front of the monolith; incrementally extract functionality into microservices and route traffic through the gateway; new or migrated features go to microservices, remaining features stay in the monolith — until the monolith is eventually ''strangled'' and decommissioned"},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy the monolith and microservices side by side with no integration — let them evolve independently until the monolith naturally dies"},{"id":"d","text":"Migrate by database: extract the database schema first, then migrate services one by one from the monolith to microservices"}]','b','The strangler fig pattern (Martin Fowler) is the recommended approach for monolith-to-microservices migration. An API gateway (or reverse proxy) intercepts all traffic. Migrated functionality is implemented in a microservice and registered with the gateway; traffic is routed to the microservice instead of the monolith. Over time, more functionality migrates until the monolith is a small stub (or zero). Benefits: low-risk incremental migration, real production traffic testing of new service, ability to rollback, delivering value throughout the migration. A full rewrite (A) is the ''big rewrite'' anti-pattern — famously fails because it takes too long, delivers no value during the process, and may never finish. Option C creates integration chaos. Option D (database-first) is valid but must be coordinated with strangler fig.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Which of the following are true about the OAuth 2.0 Authorization Code flow with PKCE? Select all that apply.','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"PKCE adds a cryptographically random code_verifier and its SHA-256 hash (code_challenge) to the authorization request"},{"id":"b","text":"PKCE prevents authorization code interception attacks where an attacker substitutes their own code during the redirect"},{"id":"c","text":"PKCE allows the authorization server to skip token validation when the code is exchanged"},{"id":"d","text":"PKCE is required for public clients (SPAs, mobile apps) and is now recommended for all OAuth client types"}]','a,b,d','PKCE (RFC 7636) adds a code_verifier (random string, 43-128 chars) and its SHA-256 hash (code_challenge) to the authorization request. When the authorization code is exchanged, the client must present the original code_verifier. Without it, an attacker intercepting the redirect URL can exchange the authorization code for tokens. The code_verifier makes this impossible without access to the client''s secret. PKCE is required for all OAuth clients in OAuth 2.1 (not just public ones). Option C is false — PKCE adds validation, not skips it. The authorization server MUST validate the code_verifier against the stored code_challenge.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Which of the following are valid strategies for preventing cache stampede (thundering herd)? Select all that apply.','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"Cache locks (mutex): only one request fetches from the database on a cache miss, others wait for the lock to release and then read from the cache"},{"id":"b","text":"Probabilistic early expiration: proactively refresh the cache before the TTL expires, based on the probability that the cached value will be needed"},{"id":"c","text":"Increasing the TTL to 24 hours eliminates cache stampede because the cache rarely expires"},{"id":"d","text":"Stale-while-revalidate: serve the stale value while refreshing the cache in the background"}]','a,b,d','Cache stampede (thundering herd) occurs when a popular cache entry expires and many concurrent requests all miss simultaneously, overwhelming the backend. Solutions: (a) Cache locks (Redis SETNX or semaphore) — one request fetches from DB, others wait and read from the populated cache. (b) Probabilistic early expiration — proactively refresh before TTL expires using a probabilistic formula to avoid synchronized expiration. (d) Stale-while-revalidate — HTTP Cache-Control pattern: serve stale data immediately while a background refresh populates the cache. Option C (long TTL) actually worsens the problem — longer TTL means more requests accumulate before expiry, creating a bigger thundering herd when it expires.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Which of the following are characteristics of gRPC that make it suitable for internal microservice communication? Select all that apply.','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"Uses Protocol Buffers (binary serialization) for smaller, faster-encoded messages compared to JSON"},{"id":"b","text":"Supports bidirectional streaming — both client and server can stream data simultaneously over a single TCP connection"},{"id":"c","text":"Has a built-in service discovery mechanism that automatically finds and load balances across service instances"},{"id":"d","text":"Uses HTTP/2 for multiplexing multiple requests over a single connection, eliminating head-of-line blocking"}]','a,b,d','gRPC advantages for internal microservice communication: (a) Protocol Buffers (binary Protobuf) provide compact, fast serialization — much faster than JSON parsing. (b) Bidirectional streaming — clients and servers can stream data simultaneously (useful for chat, real-time data feeds, streaming from sensors). (d) HTTP/2 multiplexing enables multiple concurrent streams over a single TCP connection, eliminating HTTP/1.1''s head-of-line blocking. Option C is false — gRPC does NOT have built-in service discovery; it requires external tooling (Envoy, Consul, Kubernetes DNS). Service discovery is the responsibility of the infrastructure, not the RPC framework.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Your distributed system needs to handle 1 million concurrent WebSocket connections across multiple servers. What architectural considerations are most critical? Select all that apply.','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"Stateless application design — WebSocket servers must not store per-connection state locally; all shared state must live in Redis or a message broker for cross-server fan-out"},{"id":"b","text":"Horizontal scaling with a load balancer that supports WebSocket connection routing and sticky sessions for message delivery"},{"id":"c","text":"A pub/sub message broker (Redis pub/sub, NATS, Kafka) to enable cross-server message fan-out when one server needs to send a message to a client connected to a different server"},{"id":"d","text":"WebSocket connections can be scaled out indefinitely with no upper limit by simply adding more servers"}]','a,c','Scaling WebSocket connections requires: (a) Stateless design — WebSocket servers are stateful (long-lived connections) but must externalize application state; per-connection in-memory state (e.g., user''s active session data) must not exist locally, or cross-server routing fails. (c) Pub/sub broker for fan-out — when Server A needs to send a message to User X connected to Server B, Server A publishes to the broker and Server B delivers. Redis pub/sub, NATS, or Kafka can serve this role. Option B (sticky sessions) is counterproductive for WebSocket scaling — it fights the goal of horizontal scaling. Option D is false — each server has OS-level limits (file descriptors, memory per connection); scaling is bounded by these.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Which statements about distributed tracing with W3C TraceContext are correct? Select all that apply.','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"The traceparent header carries the trace ID (globally unique per request), parent span ID (of the calling service), and trace flags (sampling decision)"},{"id":"b","text":"If any service in the call chain fails to propagate the traceparent header, the entire trace breaks at that point — downstream spans appear as disconnected or are lost"},{"id":"c","text":"W3C TraceContext eliminates the need for any application code changes because it operates at the network layer independently of application code"},{"id":"d","text":"Distributed tracing requires that all services use the same programming language to ensure consistent trace ID generation"}]','a,b','W3C TraceContext (traceparent header): format ''version-traceId-parentId-flags''. (a) The traceparent carries the trace ID (unique request identifier), parent span ID (the span that called this service), and flags (sampling). Correct. (b) If a service strips or fails to propagate headers, the downstream appears as a separate trace or is lost. The trace breaks at the non-propagating service. This is why auto-instrumentation (OpenTelemetry agents) is important. Option C is false — while service mesh sidecars handle propagation transparently for HTTP/gRPC, application-level code (database calls, message queue publishing) requires instrumentation. Option D is false — W3C TraceContext is language-agnostic; OpenTelemetry SDKs exist in all major languages.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Which properties make an API gateway more suitable than a service mesh for external client traffic management? Select all that apply.','MULTIPLE_ANSWER','[{"id":"a","text":"API gateways provide protocol translation (HTTP → gRPC, WebSocket) and API composition (GraphQL Federation, REST aggregation) for external clients"},{"id":"b","text":"API gateways provide client-facing rate limiting, authentication (JWT validation, OAuth token introspection), and billing/throttling based on API keys"},{"id":"c","text":"API gateways are deployed as sidecar proxies alongside each microservice pod inside the cluster"},{"id":"d","text":"Service meshes are equally capable as API gateways for managing external traffic since they also sit at the cluster boundary"}]','a,b','API gateways excel at North-South (external client → cluster) concerns: (a) protocol translation (external clients may use REST/HTTP, internal services may use gRPC), API composition (aggregating multiple backend calls into a single client response), (b) client-facing auth and rate limiting (API key validation, JWT verification, OAuth introspection at the edge), billing, and client-specific throttling. Option C is false — API gateways are typically deployed as standalone services or ingress controllers, not sidecars (service mesh uses sidecars). Option D is false — service meshes are primarily designed for East-West (internal) traffic; a gateway sits at the boundary with features optimized for external clients.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is load shedding, and how does it differ from load balancing in a system under extreme load?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Load shedding and load balancing are the same thing — both distribute traffic across servers equally"},{"id":"b","text":"Load shedding selectively rejects low-priority requests under extreme load to protect critical service functionality — e.g., reject analytics API requests but accept payment requests; load balancing distributes load across available servers without selective rejection"},{"id":"c","text":"Load balancing is the aggressive approach (rejects requests) and load shedding is the conservative approach (distributes load)"},{"id":"d","text":"Load shedding only applies to batch processing systems and has no relevance to real-time APIs"}]','b','Load shedding (also called load shedding or priority-aware rejection): when a system is at or beyond capacity, selectively rejecting non-critical requests to preserve resources for critical ones. Example: under DDoS or flash crowd, reject unauthenticated requests, background jobs, and analytics endpoints while accepting payment and authentication requests. This is graceful degradation at the request level. Load balancing (A) distributes load across servers without selective rejection — it assumes all requests should be served if possible. Load shedding is a last resort when load balancing, auto-scaling, and circuit breaking have been exhausted. Option C reverses the definitions. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','What is graceful degradation, and how does it differ from a circuit breaker?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Graceful degradation and circuit breaker are the same pattern with different names"},{"id":"b","text":"Graceful degradation is the system-level capability to maintain partial functionality when a component fails — e.g., a product catalog service that goes down still serves cached data and disables review ratings; circuit breaker is the per-call pattern that prevents cascading failures by failing fast when a dependency is unhealthy"},{"id":"c","text":"Circuit breaker is the system-level pattern; graceful degradation is the per-call pattern"},{"id":"d","text":"Graceful degradation requires that all components in the system fail simultaneously for it to activate"}]','b','Graceful degradation: when a component (service, database, feature) fails, the system as a whole continues operating at reduced functionality — not failing completely. Examples: serving stale cache when the database is down, disabling non-essential features (recommendations) during high load, falling back to cached search results when the search service is down. Circuit breaker: a per-call pattern that monitors the health of a specific dependency and fails fast (returns fallback) when the failure rate exceeds a threshold — preventing resource exhaustion. Circuit breaker is a mechanism that enables graceful degradation; graceful degradation is the desired property. Option A is false. Option C reverses the mapping. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','True or False: A Kafka topic with a retention period of 7 days and a compaction policy enabled simultaneously will retain messages for at least 7 days before compaction takes effect.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','Log compaction and log retention are different cleanup policies in Kafka: (1) Log retention (log.retention.ms/hours) deletes segments older than the retention window. (2) Log compaction (cleanup.policy=compact) retains only the latest value for each key — it does not delete old messages based on time; it retains at least one message per key indefinitely. You cannot enable both simultaneously as primary cleanup policies — the policies are mutually exclusive per topic. You can configure a topic with both retention and compaction by setting cleanup.policy=compact,delete — but compaction takes effect immediately (not after 7 days), and retention applies to segments, not individual messages. For event sourcing, log compaction alone is typically used.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','True or False: The Raft consensus algorithm guarantees liveness (the system will always make progress) in addition to safety (no conflicting leaders can be elected).','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','Raft guarantees safety (no two nodes can both believe they are the legitimate leader in the same term) but does NOT guarantee liveness. In network partition scenarios, if a minority of nodes cannot reach a quorum, they will not make progress — the cluster is temporarily unavailable for writes. This is a fundamental trade-off in consensus algorithms (FLP impossibility): in an asynchronous system with possible network failures, no consensus algorithm can guarantee both safety AND liveness simultaneously. Raft chooses safety — if the network ispartitioned, it stops accepting writes rather than risking split-brain. This is correct behavior for a CP system. Liveness is only guaranteed when a majority partition exists and the leader is reachable.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the fundamental purpose of a cache in a system architecture, and what is the most important trade-off it introduces?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A cache permanently stores frequently accessed data to replace the database as the primary data store"},{"id":"b","text":"A cache stores copies of frequently accessed data closer to the consumer to reduce latency and load on the origin; the main trade-off is data staleness — cached data can become outdated relative to the source of truth"},{"id":"c","text":"A cache is a software layer that speeds up reads but cannot be used for writes — it is purely a read optimization"},{"id":"d","text":"A cache eliminates the need for a database entirely by storing all application state in memory"}]','b','A cache (from French ''cacher'' — to hide) is a temporary, high-speed storage layer that keeps copies of data likely to be re-requested. The core benefit is reduced latency and offloaded database/backend load. The fundamental trade-off is staleness: the cache is a copy, not the source of truth, so cached data can diverge from the origin over time. Cache invalidation strategies (TTL, event-driven eviction, write-through) are critical design decisions. Option A mischaracterizes cache as a permanent store. Option C is false (write-through, write-behind caches exist). Option D is dangerous.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is cache-aside (lazy loading), and what are its main advantages over cache-aside''s alternatives?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Cache-aside eagerly loads all database data into cache on application startup to warm the cache proactively"},{"id":"b","text":"Cache-aside is a pattern where the application first checks the cache; on a cache miss, it reads from the database and populates the cache — the advantage is simplicity and only caching what is actually requested"},{"id":"c","text":"Cache-aside writes go directly to the cache and the cache propagates writes to the database asynchronously in the background"},{"id":"d","text":"Cache-aside guarantees that the cache is always 100% synchronized with the database at all times"}]','b','Cache-aside (lazy loading): application code checks cache → if miss, reads from DB → populates cache → returns data. Advantages: simple to implement, only caches what is actually used (no wasted cache space on unused data), naturally adapts to access patterns, and doesn''t require special infrastructure. Disadvantages: cache stampede (thundering herd on popular cache misses), cold-start latency for first requests, no write-through to update the cache. Alternatives: read-through (cache itself fetches on miss), write-through (cache updated synchronously on writes), write-behind (cache updated, DB updated asynchronously). Option A describes cache warming. Option C describes write-behind. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A popular blog post goes viral and your cache receives 10,000 requests per second for the same post content. On the first request, a cache miss causes a single database query — but on subsequent requests, all 9,999 other requests also hit the database simultaneously before the cache is populated. What is this problem called and how do you prevent it?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Cache poisoning — malicious requests flood the cache with incorrect data; prevent by using signed cache entries"},{"id":"b","text":"Cache stampede (thundering herd) — multiple concurrent requests all miss the cache simultaneously and hit the database; prevent using probabilistic early expiration, a cache lock (only one request fetches from DB while others wait), or a background refresh with stale-while-revalidate"},{"id":"c","text":"Cache avalanche — all cache entries expire at once due to a shared TTL; prevent by adding random jitter to TTL values"},{"id":"d","text":"Cache fragmentation — memory is allocated and deallocated too frequently, causing memory pressure; prevent by pre-allocating a large heap"}]','b','Cache stampede (thundering herd) occurs when popular cache entries expire (or are evicted) and many concurrent requests all miss simultaneously, overwhelming the backend. Solutions: (1) probabilistic early expiration (probabilistically refresh cache before actual expiry), (2) cache locks (mutex/semaphore — one request fetches from DB, others wait on the lock), (3) stale-while-revalidate (serve stale data while refreshing in background). Cache avalanche (C) is a related but different problem: mass expiry of entries sharing a TTL. Cache poisoning (A) and fragmentation (D) are unrelated.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is TTL (Time To Live) in the context of caching, and what are the consequences of setting a TTL too short vs. too long?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"TTL is the maximum size of a cache entry in bytes; a short TTL prevents cache bloat but causes frequent evictions of large objects"},{"id":"b","text":"TTL is the duration a cached entry remains valid before it should be refreshed or discarded; too short increases database load (frequent cache misses), too long increases staleness risk and wastes cache space on outdated data"},{"id":"c","text":"TTL is only relevant for CDN caches; application-level caches like Redis do not use TTL"},{"id":"d","text":"A longer TTL always improves cache hit rate and reduces backend load — there is no downside to very long TTLs"}]','b','TTL defines how long a cache entry is considered valid. Short TTLs (e.g., 60 seconds): lower staleness risk but more cache misses and backend load — good for rapidly changing data (stock prices, inventory counts). Long TTLs (hours/days): higher cache hit rate, less backend load, but stale data risk — appropriate for relatively static data (user profile metadata, configuration). The optimal TTL is data-dependent and often tuned empirically. Option A misdefines TTL. Option C is false (TTL is a core Redis feature). Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between write-through and write-behind (write-back) caching strategies?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Write-through and write-behind are identical — both update the cache and database simultaneously in the same synchronous operation"},{"id":"b","text":"Write-through updates the cache and database synchronously in the same operation — both must succeed before acknowledging the write; write-behind updates the cache immediately and asynchronously flushes to the database — acknowledging the write before the database is updated"},{"id":"c","text":"Write-behind always writes to the database first before updating the cache; write-through updates the cache first"},{"id":"d","text":"Write-through is an asynchronous strategy used for high-throughput write scenarios; write-behind is synchronous and used when data durability is critical"}]','b','Write-through: synchronous dual-write to cache + DB. Acknowledgment sent only after both succeed. Cache always has consistent, up-to-date data. Slower writes (two I/O ops). Good for: data that will be immediately re-read, cache-aside misses that should be populated. Write-behind (write-back): write to cache immediately (fast), acknowledge instantly, flush to DB asynchronously in background. High write throughput, but a crash between cache write and DB flush loses data (durability risk). Good for: high-write-throughput scenarios (logging, analytics, rate limiting) where occasional data loss is acceptable. Option A is false. Option C is backwards. Option D is backwards.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Which cache eviction policy evicts the least recently used entry when the cache reaches its maximum capacity?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"LRU (Least Recently Used) — discards the least recently accessed entry when capacity is reached"},{"id":"b","text":"LFU (Least Frequently Used) — discards the entry with the lowest access frequency count"},{"id":"c","text":"FIFO (First In, First Out) — discards the oldest entry regardless of access history"},{"id":"d","text":"Random Eviction — selects a random entry to discard; provides no statistical guarantee of keeping hot data"}]','a','LRU (Least Recently Used) tracks access timestamps for each entry and evicts the entry that hasn''t been accessed for the longest time when capacity is full. It works well when recently accessed items are likely to be accessed again (temporal locality). LRU is the most commonly used eviction policy in Redis and Memcached (both use variants of LRU). LFU (B) is better for workloads where frequency matters more than recency (e.g., persistently popular items). FIFO (C) ignores usage patterns. Random (D) is simple but doesn''t prioritize hot data. Option A is correct.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between LRU and LFU eviction policies, and when would LFU be more appropriate than LRU?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"LRU and LFU are the same algorithm with different names — both track access frequency in the same way"},{"id":"b","text":"LRU evicts least recently accessed items; LFU evicts least frequently accessed items; LFU is better when you want to keep persistently popular items even if they weren''t accessed recently, and avoid keeping a single large spike that happened to be recent"},{"id":"c","text":"LFU always outperforms LRU for all cache workloads because frequency is a better predictor of future access than recency"},{"id":"d","text":"LRU is only used for CPU caches (L1/L2); LFU is used for disk and memory caches"}]','b','LRU uses recency as a proxy for future access (temporal locality assumption). LFU uses frequency as a proxy (items accessed many times are likely accessed again). LFU is better for workloads with ''bursty'' access patterns: an item accessed once a million times recently gets evicted by an item accessed once right now in LRU, which is wrong for that workload. LFU''s challenge: frequency counters accumulate (''cache pollution'' from old hot items that are no longer accessed). Redis supports LFU via the maxmemory-policy ''allkeys-lfu'' and ''volatile-lfu''. Option A is false. Option C is false (workload-dependent). Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Your Redis cache is consuming 100% of its allocated memory. What happens to new write operations, and what Redis configuration or strategy should you implement to handle this?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Redis automatically evicts old entries to make room for new writes — no configuration needed"},{"id":"b","text":"Redis by default returns an OUTOFMEMORY error when maxmemory is reached and no eviction policy can free space (unless the policy is ''noeviction'' which also returns an error); you must configure an appropriate eviction policy (e.g., allkeys-lru, volatile-ttl) or scale the cluster"},{"id":"c","text":"Redis automatically switches to a disk-backed storage mode when memory is full — writes are redirected to the filesystem"},{"id":"d","text":"When Redis hits maxmemory, it starts returning null for all read operations until memory is freed"}]','b','Redis blocks write commands when maxmemory is reached (unless a suitable eviction policy is set). The default eviction policy is ''noeviction'' (return error on write). Configuring ''allkeys-lru'' or ''volatile-lru'' enables automatic eviction of least-recently-used keys to free space. ''volatile-ttl'' evicts keys with the shortest TTL. ''volatile-random'' and ''volatile-lfu'' also exist. Choosing the right policy depends on whether all keys are candidates for eviction or only keys with a TTL set. Redis Cluster mode distributes keys across nodes for horizontal memory scaling. Option A is wrong. Option C is wrong. Option D is wrong.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A CDN serves your static assets (images, CSS, JavaScript) globally. An updated CSS file was deployed to the origin server, but users worldwide are still seeing the old CSS for up to 24 hours. What is the root cause and how do you fix it?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"The CDN is serving stale content because the origin server is down — fix by restarting the origin server"},{"id":"b","text":"The CDN is honoring the Cache-Control TTL set by the origin; the old CSS is cached at edge PoPs for up to 24 hours; fix by setting a short TTL on static assets, using cache-busting (filename versioning like app.a1b2c3.css), or issuing a cache invalidation (purge) request to the CDN after deployment"},{"id":"c","text":"The CDN automatically purges all cached content on every origin server deployment — the issue is a browser cache problem, not CDN"},{"id":"d","text":"The CSS file is too large (> 1 MB) and the CDN rejects caching for files above its size limit"}]','b','CDN edge nodes honor the origin''s Cache-Control max-age header. If the origin serves Cache-Control: max-age=86400 (24 hours), the CDN caches the file for 24 hours before checking the origin again. When deploying updates, old cached versions persist until TTL expires. Solutions: (1) set short TTLs for mutable assets, (2) implement cache-busting (fingerprint/ versioning in filenames: main.abc123.js vs main.js — changing content changes the URL so the CDN treats it as a new asset), (3) issue a cache purge/invalidation API call to the CDN immediately after deployment. Option A is unrelated. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is cache-busting (or cache-busting fingerprinting), and why is it the preferred way to handle caching for static assets that change frequently?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Cache-busting forces the browser to clear its entire browser cache whenever a new deployment occurs"},{"id":"b","text":"Cache-busting embeds a content hash or build timestamp into the filename or query string of a static asset; when the asset changes, the URL changes, causing the CDN and browser to treat it as a new resource — eliminating stale cache issues without requiring cache invalidation"},{"id":"c","text":"Cache-busting is a technique used exclusively by Redis to prevent cache stampede problems during key eviction"},{"id":"d","text":"Cache-busting requires users to manually clear their browser cache after every deployment"}]','b','Cache-busting (fingerprinting) makes each version of a file have a unique URL: e.g., main.a3f8c1d2.js (hash-based) or main.20240407.js (timestamp-based). When the file content changes (new build), the hash changes → new URL → new cache entry → browsers and CDNs fetch the new file. Old cached versions naturally expire by TTL or are simply never requested again. This decouples cache TTL from deployment cadence — long TTLs (1 year) can be used safely for immutable build artifacts. Option A is false. Option C confuses stampede prevention with cache-busting. Option D is the old manual workaround.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the stale-while-revalidate caching pattern, and when is it most useful?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Stale-while-revalidate immediately expires all cache entries when the TTL is reached — the next request always triggers a fresh fetch"},{"id":"b","text":"Stale-while-revalidate serves a cached entry even after it has expired (stale) while asynchronously fetching a fresh copy in the background — providing fast responses without staleness forever"},{"id":"c","text":"Stale-while-revalidate is a write strategy that updates the cache and database in alternating order to balance write throughput"},{"id":"d","text":"Stale-while-revalidate is a cache eviction strategy that removes expired entries first before evicting non-expired entries"}]','b','Stale-while-revalidate (HTTP Cache-Control extension): return the cached (potentially stale) entry immediately to the user, then asynchronously refresh the cache in the background. Users get fast responses (no wait for revalidation), and the cache stays relatively fresh. The ''stale-while-revalidate'' directive in Cache-Control: s-maxage=3600, stale-while-revalidate=60 means: serve from cache for 3600s, then for 60s more serve stale while refreshing. This is the HTTP equivalent of a cache lock + background refresh, and is natively supported by CDNs, Nginx, and many HTTP clients. Option A describes simple expiry. Option C and D are unrelated.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: Adding a cache layer in front of a database always reduces the average latency of read operations.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','A cache adds a network hop and potential serialization overhead. For requests that are cache misses, the path cache → miss → database is longer than database alone. If the cache hit rate is low (less than ~70-80%), the overhead of the added cache layer outweighs the benefit. Cache only helps when hit rate is high enough that the average latency (hit_rate × cache_latency + miss_rate × (cache_latency + db_latency)) is lower than raw database latency. Cache also helps reduce database load and improve throughput at the cost of staleness risk — the benefit is not just latency reduction.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: Setting a TTL of 0 on a cache entry effectively makes the entry never expire.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','In Redis, TTL=0 means the key is already expired and will be deleted on the next access (or immediately if lazy expiration is triggered). TTL=0 is a special value that means ''expired immediately'' — the opposite of ''never expire.'' To make an entry never expire in Redis, simply do not call EXPIRE on the key, or set TTL to -1. A null TTL in HTTP Cache-Control also has specific meaning (don''t cache at all). This is a common misconception.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: A cache miss always requires a full round-trip to the database before the cached data can be restored.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','A cache miss can be handled in multiple ways. In cache-aside, yes, the application fetches from the DB. But in cache-aside with a mutex lock, concurrent requests wait for the first to populate the cache. In stale-while-revalidate, the stale cached value is returned while the cache is refreshed in the background — no waiting for the miss. In probabilistic early expiration, the cache may serve a fresh value even as it revalidates. The miss rate and database load are not the same thing — the cache miss latency can be hidden entirely by serving stale data while revalidating asynchronously.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Your team is evaluating Redis vs. Memcached as an application-level cache. Redis is single-threaded. How does this affect throughput and latency characteristics compared to Memcached''s multi-threaded architecture?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Redis''s single-threaded design is always slower than Memcached''s multi-threaded design for all workloads because it can only use one CPU core"},{"id":"b","text":"Redis''s single-threaded event loop eliminates lock contention entirely and provides predictable, consistent latency for all operations; Memcached''s multi-threaded design can achieve higher raw throughput on multi-core machines but suffers from lock contention and inconsistent latency under high concurrency — Redis 6+ adds I/O threads to parallelize network processing while keeping command execution single-threaded"},{"id":"c","text":"Memcached''s multi-threaded design is superior because it can process multiple commands simultaneously on different CPU cores; Redis cannot use more than one core without manual sharding"},{"id":"d","text":"Both Redis and Memcached are single-threaded and provide identical throughput characteristics; any performance difference is due to network configuration"}]','b','Redis''s single-threaded event loop (using epoll/kqueue) provides latency consistency: no lock contention, no context switching overhead between threads, and predictable O(log N) complexity for most operations. It is not limited to one core for network I/O in Redis 6+ (I/O threads parallelize network processing) and scales well beyond Memcached for most workloads. Memcached''s multi-threaded design (libevent-based) can saturate multiple cores for high-throughput scenarios but suffers from global metadata locks that limit scalability under contention. For typical application cache workloads (sub-millisecond target), Redis''s single-threaded model is advantageous. For maximum throughput with many concurrent small operations, Memcached may edge out Redis.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','A user profile service reads user data 100 times more frequently than it is updated. The cache stores user profiles with a 1-hour TTL. On update, the service invalidates the cache. Under high write concurrency, a scenario arises where a cache miss occurs just as an update is in-flight — one request reads old data, another updates DB, the first request re-populates the cache with stale data. How do you fix this?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Increase the TTL to 24 hours to reduce the probability of cache misses occurring near update time"},{"id":"b","text":"Use write-through caching: on update, write to the database AND the cache simultaneously in the same transaction so the cache always has fresh data"},{"id":"c","text":"Implement a cache update mutex or use a compare-and-swap (CAS) token: on update, store a version number in both the DB and cache; on read, verify the version matches before populating the cache — stale reads with old version are discarded"},{"id":"d","text":"Remove TTL entirely — without expiration, the cache will never miss and the stale data problem disappears"}]','c','This is a classic race condition between cache invalidation and concurrent reads (the ''delete-then-read'' race). The standard fix is a version or timestamp check: store a version number with each entity in both the DB and cache. On a cache miss, the reader fetches from DB (getting version N), checks the version in the cache — if cache version != DB version, discard the stale value and refetch. More robust: use a distributed lock (Redis SETNX) around the read-and-cache operation to serialize reads during an in-flight update. Write-through (B) is also correct but requires the cache to be write-capable and still has race windows. Option A doesn''t fix the race. Option D creates permanent staleness risk.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','You are designing a caching strategy for a social media application where users can have millions of followers. Caching a user''s timeline (posts from people they follow) needs to support high read throughput. What caching architecture is most appropriate?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Cache the full timeline for each user with a 5-minute TTL; when a user posts, immediately update all followers'' timeline caches by pushing to each follower''s cached timeline"},{"id":"b","text":"Use fan-out-on-read: timeline is assembled at read time from cached post objects; each post is cached individually by ID; this avoids massive write amplification but adds latency on reads for users with many followers"},{"id":"c","text":"Fan-out-on-write (push model) works for all social media use cases; it ensures timelines are always pre-computed and read instantly"},{"id":"d","text":"Social media timelines do not benefit from caching because they are unique to each user and change too frequently"}]','b','Twitter/Facebook-style timelines use fan-out-on-read (pull model): when User A loads their timeline, the system fetches the list of people A follows, then fetches recent cached posts from each followed user, merges and sorts them. Each post is cached individually (post ID → post content). Fan-out-on-write (push model) — pushing to all follower timelines on every post — causes massive write amplification for users with millions of followers (celebrity problem). Hybrid approaches are used in practice: fan-out-on-write for normal users, fan-out-on-read for high-follower-count accounts. Option A misdescribes a push model with a short TTL that doesn''t solve celebrity followers. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','A CDN is used for a video streaming application. Videos range from 30-second clips to 2-hour movies. The CDN serves millions of users. What CDN caching strategy would you recommend for optimizing both storage costs and playback start time (TTFB)?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Cache all video content at the CDN edge with a TTL of 7 days; this maximizes cache hit rates and minimizes origin requests regardless of video length"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a tiered caching strategy: cache the first 5-10 minutes (intro segment) of each video at edge PoPs for fast playback start (low TTFB), and use a origin-pull (lazy loading) strategy for the remainder of the video streamed from the nearest regional cache mid-tier; short clips are fully cached, long videos are streamed with partial caching"},{"id":"c","text":"Disable CDN caching entirely and stream all video content directly from the origin server — CDN caching is not suitable for video streaming"},{"id":"d","text":"Store only the video thumbnail images in the CDN; the actual video files should always be streamed directly from object storage without CDN involvement"}]','b','Video streaming has unique caching requirements: (1) playback start time (TTFB/Time to First Byte) is critical for user experience; (2) long videos (2-hour movies) are too large to fully cache at every edge PoP; (3) only the first few minutes are watched on average (retention curve). Best strategy: segment-based caching — cache the first segment at edge (fast start), cache popular full videos at mid-tier regional caches, and stream remainder from origin or deep storage. Use HLS/DASH chunked delivery so each segment is independently cacheable. Option A wastes CDN storage on videos users rarely finish. Option C eliminates CDN benefits. Option D ignores that CDN works well for byte-range requests on video segments.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','True or False: In a Redis Cluster with multiple shards, cache-aside pattern works identically to a single-node Redis cache — if the key exists on one of the nodes, it will always be found regardless of which node handles the request.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','In Redis Cluster, keys are distributed across shards using hash slots (16384 slots, mapped to nodes by slot = CRC16(key) mod 16384). Each request must be routed to the correct node for the key''s slot. If a client connects to the wrong node for a given key, it receives a MOVED redirect (the cluster tells the client which node to retry). Clients must implement smart routing (using cluster-aware drivers that cache slot mappings) or use a proxy (Redis Cluster Proxy, Twemproxy). Cache-aside pattern works fine in cluster mode but requires cluster-aware clients or proxies to route requests correctly. Single-node behavior assumptions break in cluster mode.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','You need to implement a distributed session store for a globally distributed web application with 50 million active sessions. Sessions must be accessible within 10ms latency from any region. What is the most appropriate architecture?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Store sessions in a single Redis cluster in one region and accept the latency penalty for cross-region access — this is the most reliable approach"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a geo-distributed Redis cache (e.g., Redis Enterprise Global, CockroachDB, or DynamoDB Global Tables with DAX) with local read replicas in each region and a single write primary — route session reads to the nearest replica with session-level consistency (read-your-writes go to primary region), and writes to the primary"},{"id":"c","text":"Store sessions in an in-memory hash map on each application server — this eliminates network latency entirely for local session access"},{"id":"d","text":"Store sessions in browser cookies signed with HMAC — no server-side session storage is needed, and this scales infinitely without infrastructure"}]','b','Global session storage requires: (1) local read replicas in each region for sub-10ms reads, (2) a single write primary to avoid split-brain scenarios, (3) session-level consistency for read-after-write (same user''s writes must be visible to them). Redis Enterprise (CRDT-based geo-replication), DynamoDB DAX + Global Tables, or CockroachDB can provide this. Redis Cluster is intra-region, not geo-distributed. Option A''s single-region approach fails the 10ms global requirement. Option C (server-local memory) creates a session-loss problem on server restarts and doesn''t work with horizontal scaling. Option D (HMAC cookies) has size limits (4KB), exposes session data to the client, and provides no server-side invalidation capability.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the primary purpose of database normalization, and what problem does it prevent?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Normalization speeds up queries by storing computed aggregates in separate tables"},{"id":"b","text":"Normalization organizes data into tables to eliminate redundant storage and prevent update anomalies (insert, update, delete) that corrupt data integrity when the same data is stored in multiple places"},{"id":"c","text":"Normalization is required for any database that uses foreign key constraints"},{"id":"d","text":"Normalization reduces the number of indexes needed to speed up joins between related tables"}]','b','Normalization (1NF through BCNF/3NF) eliminates data redundancy by splitting data into related tables so each fact is stored exactly once. The primary goal is preventing update anomalies: if ''customer address'' is stored in both Orders and Invoices tables and the customer moves, an update must happen in multiple places — one might be missed, creating inconsistent data. Normalization also ensures referential integrity. Denormalization (adding redundant data) is done intentionally for read performance. Option A describes a materialized view, not normalization. Option C is incidental, not the primary purpose. Option D is backwards.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','You have a user table with a ''country'' column used frequently in WHERE clauses. Most users are from one country (skewed data distribution). What problem can this cause with a simple B-tree index?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"The index will use too much disk space because country has low cardinality"},{"id":"b","text":"The query optimizer may ignore the index for the majority country value and do a full table scan instead, because a B-tree index provides little selectivity for highly skewed distributions"},{"id":"c","text":"B-tree indexes cannot be created on columns with fewer than 100 distinct values"},{"id":"d","text":"The index will cause deadlock conflicts on concurrent inserts into the user table"}]','b','For highly skewed cardinality (e.g., 90% of rows are country=''US''), the query planner may determine that a B-tree index is not selective enough — scanning 90% of the index is no better than a table scan, so the planner skips the index. This is called a ''leading column problem'' in composite indexes and is why covering indexes, partial indexes, or histogram statistics exist. Low-cardinality columns (gender, country, boolean flags) are poor B-tree index candidates unless used in composite indexes with high-cardinality leading columns. Option A is wrong (index size relates to row count, not cardinality). Option C is false. Option D is unrelated to index selectivity.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between a covering index and a standard B-tree index?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A covering index includes all columns in the table; a standard index includes only the primary key column"},{"id":"b","text":"A covering index (composite index with all query columns) allows the query to be satisfied entirely from the index without touching the actual table rows — eliminating the need for a separate row lookup"},{"id":"c","text":"Covering indexes are only used for write-heavy workloads to batch multiple updates into one I/O operation"},{"id":"d","text":"There is no functional difference; a covering index is just a B-tree index with a different name"}]','b','A covering index (also called a composite covering index or index with included columns) includes all columns a query needs as index entries — not just the WHERE clause columns. When the query is fully covered, the database can return results from the index alone without fetching the actual rows (a ''table or heap fetch''). This dramatically speeds up queries for wide tables where reading the row is expensive. The tradeoff: larger index size, slower writes. The index columns must appear in the right order (most selective first for B-tree lookups). Option A is incorrect. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is database sharding (horizontal partitioning), and what is the main operational challenge when resharding an existing sharded database?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Sharding splits columns of a table into separate tables (vertical partitioning); the challenge is maintaining foreign key consistency across column splits"},{"id":"b","text":"Sharding splits rows of a table across multiple database servers using a shard key; the main challenge is that resharding (changing the shard key or adding shards) requires remapping and migrating a large portion of existing data with minimal downtime"},{"id":"c","text":"Sharding creates read-only copies of the database for reporting; the challenge is keeping replicas in sync with the primary"},{"id":"d","text":"Sharding automatically rebalances data across nodes when load changes; there is no manual resharding step"}]','b','Sharding (horizontal partitioning) distributes rows across N shards based on a shard key. The hardest operational problem is resharding — changing the number of shards or the shard key — which requires remapping existing rows and migrating data while the application continues serving traffic. Techniques to minimize this: consistent hashing (minimizes remapping), allocate-on-warn (pre-allocate shards), and online schema tools (Vitess, CockroachDB, TiDB handle this natively). Option A describes vertical partitioning. Option C describes replication. Option D is false for manual sharding strategies.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','ACID properties guarantee strong consistency for database transactions. What does the ''I'' (Isolation) in ACID specifically govern?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Isolation guarantees that all nodes in a distributed database see the same committed data at the same time"},{"id":"b","text":"Isolation controls how concurrent transaction operations interact — determining which phenomena (dirty reads, non-repeatable reads, phantom reads) are permitted and invisible to each other"},{"id":"c","text":"Isolation ensures that a transaction either completes fully or rolls back entirely with no partial effects on the database"},{"id":"d","text":"Isolation is irrelevant for single-threaded in-memory databases and only matters for disk-based systems"}]','b','Isolation governs the visibility of concurrent operations within a transaction. Different isolation levels (Read Uncommitted, Read Committed, Repeatable Read, Serializable) permit or prevent phenomena: dirty reads (uncommitted data), non-repeatable reads (same row changes between reads), and phantom reads (new rows appear in a range scan). The Durability (D) in ACID handles crash recovery. Atomicity (A) handles all-or-nothing execution. Consistency (C) handles database rules. Option A describes linearizability, not isolation. Option C describes atomicity. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','BASE semantics (Basically Available, Soft state, Eventual consistency) are used by many NoSQL databases. What does ''Soft state'' mean?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"The database does not enforce schema constraints; schema is enforced at the application layer"},{"id":"b","text":"The state of the system may change over time even without new input, because replicas are converging asynchronously and replica states may differ temporarily"},{"id":"c","text":"BASE systems guarantee that reads will eventually become consistent after a fixed timeout period (e.g., 30 seconds)"},{"id":"d","text":"Soft state means the database can lose data silently during normal operation without informing the application"}]','b','Soft state captures the idea that replica state is ''in flux'' — replicas may hold different values for the same entity at the same moment because updates are propagated asynchronously. The system''s state evolves over time as replicas converge. Hard state (the opposite) would mean the stored value is the definitive committed state. Option A describes schema-on-read, not soft state. Option C misrepresents eventual consistency as having a guaranteed bounded convergence time — true convergence bounds are not guaranteed in BASE. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A system requires financial transaction integrity where a balance cannot go negative. Should you rely on database constraints or application-level checks — and why?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Application-level checks are faster because the database constraint check adds unnecessary overhead to every transaction"},{"id":"b","text":"Database constraints (CHECK constraints, triggers) are the last line of defense — the database enforces them regardless of race conditions, application bugs, or malicious input; always enforce critical invariants at the database level in addition to application checks"},{"id":"c","text":"Database constraints are deprecated in modern systems; microservices should handle all business logic in the application layer"},{"id":"d","text":"For financial integrity, use eventual consistency — the system will reconcile discrepancies asynchronously"}]','b','Critical business invariants (balance >= 0, inventory >= 0, unique email) must be enforced at the database level because: (1) concurrent transactions can race past application checks; (2) bugs, compromised credentials, or direct DB access can bypass application logic; (3) constraints are enforced atomically as part of the transaction. Application checks and database constraints together form defense-in-depth. Relying solely on application code is a common source of data integrity bugs. Option A ignores race conditions. Option C is wrong. Option D is dangerous for financial data.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is denormalization, and when is it appropriate to deliberately denormalize a normalized database design?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Denormalization means dropping all tables and storing everything in a single wide table for maximum simplicity"},{"id":"b","text":"Denormalization is the intentional addition of redundant data to normalized tables to speed up read queries, and is appropriate when read performance outweighs the cost of keeping redundant data in sync across multiple write paths"},{"id":"c","text":"Denormalization should never be done — normalized databases are always faster due to smaller table sizes and efficient use of indexes"},{"id":"d","text":"Denormalization is only used in NoSQL databases; SQL databases must always remain fully normalized"}]','b','Denormalization adds redundant data (e.g., storing product_name in the Orders table alongside a foreign key to Products) to eliminate expensive joins for read-heavy workloads. The cost: write operations must update redundant copies — if not done atomically, data can diverge. It is appropriate when reads vastly outnumber writes, join costs are prohibitive (e.g., real-time dashboards), or the data rarely changes. Pre-join materialized views, duplicate columns for query convenience, and summary tables are all denormalization patterns. Option A is an extreme. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the primary difference between SQL (relational) and NoSQL databases in terms of data model flexibility and query capability?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"SQL databases are slower than NoSQL databases for all workloads due to the overhead of join processing"},{"id":"b","text":"NoSQL databases offer flexible schemas (schema-on-read) and simpler query models (key-value, document, wide-column) at the cost of limited cross-document query capability; SQL databases enforce a fixed schema and provide powerful relational queries and joins"},{"id":"c","text":"SQL databases cannot handle JSON or semi-structured data; NoSQL databases are the only option for document storage"},{"id":"d","text":"NoSQL databases guarantee ACID transactions across multiple collections or tables; SQL databases do not support transactions"}]','b','NoSQL databases trade relational query power for schema flexibility and horizontal scalability. Key-value (Redis), document (MongoDB), and wide-column (Cassandra) stores let you store data without predefining structure. Cross-document joins and complex aggregations are limited or require application-side processing. SQL databases provide rich declarative queries (JOIN, GROUP BY, window functions), ACID transactions, and mature query optimizers — making them strong for transactional (OLTP) and analytical (OLAP) workloads with structured data. Option A is workload-dependent. Option C is false (PostgreSQL has JSONB). Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Your application needs to support 1 million writes per second globally with low latency. A single primary database cannot handle this. What data architecture best solves this write-scaling problem?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Add more read replicas to the primary database and route all writes to the primary — read replicas improve read throughput but not write throughput"},{"id":"b","text":"Shard the database across multiple write-capable nodes using a distributed SQL database (e.g., CockroachDB, TiDB, YugabyteDB) or a sharding middleware (Vitess) that provides transparent horizontal write scaling with ACID guarantees"},{"id":"c","text":"Upgrade the primary database server with more CPU, RAM, and NVMe SSDs — vertical scaling can handle any write throughput requirement"},{"id":"d","text":"Use an in-memory cache in front of the database to absorb write traffic and flush to disk asynchronously"}]','b','Write scaling requires partitioning (sharding) writes across multiple write-capable nodes. Traditional primary-replica setups only scale reads — the primary is the bottleneck. Distributed SQL databases (CockroachDB, TiDB, YugabyteDB) provide horizontal write scaling with SQL semantics, automatic resharding, and ACID transactions. Vitess (MySQL sharding middleware) and manual application-level sharding are also valid. Option A only scales reads. Option C has a hardware ceiling. Option D delays writes but doesn''t scale the database itself — cache still must eventually write to DB.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between synchronous and asynchronous database replication, and when would you choose each?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Synchronous replication copies data to replicas before acknowledging writes; chosen for durability guarantees. Asynchronous replication acknowledges writes immediately and copies in the background; chosen for lower latency and higher availability"},{"id":"b","text":"Asynchronous replication is faster because it copies data to all replicas simultaneously using parallel threads; synchronous replication is sequential and therefore slower"},{"id":"c","text":"Synchronous replication is only used for read replicas; asynchronous replication is used for disaster recovery replicas"},{"id":"d","text":"There is no practical difference; both offer identical durability and performance characteristics"}]','a','Synchronous replication waits for replica confirmations before committing — if a replica is slow or down, the write blocks or fails. This guarantees that a committed write exists on multiple nodes. Asynchronous replication acknowledges immediately after the primary commits, propagating changes in the background — lower latency but a window of data loss if the primary fails before propagation completes. Synchronous is used for financial systems, DR in multi-DC setups. Asynchronous is used for geo-distributed read replicas where latency matters more than zero-RPO. Option B overstates the difference. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: In a multi-master database replication setup, each node can accept writes and replicate to others — this eliminates all single points of failure and provides both high availability and strong consistency.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','Multi-master replication eliminates a single write-primary but introduces serious new problems: write conflicts (concurrent writes to the same row at different nodes), consistency trade-offs (must use last-writer-wins or conflict resolution), and coordination complexity. Nodes that are network-partitioned can accept conflicting writes that must be reconciled later. Multi-master provides high availability but sacrifices strong consistency — it falls under the AP side of CAP. Conflict-free Replicated Data Types (CRDTs) can help but have limited applicability. It is not a free lunch.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: SQL databases always use ACID transaction semantics, while NoSQL databases always use BASE semantics.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','This is a common misconception. The SQL/NoSQL distinction is about data model (relational vs. non-relational), not transaction guarantees. Many SQL databases support BASE (e.g., PostgreSQL''s asynchronous standbys), and many NoSQL databases support ACID-like transactions (e.g., MongoDB 4.0+ supports multi-document ACID transactions, Cassandra supports tunable consistency, Cosmos DB offers strong consistency mode). ACID vs BASE describes consistency trade-offs that can exist in both SQL and NoSQL systems.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Your team is designing a multi-tenant SaaS application where each tenant''s data must be completely isolated. A tenant''s data must never be accessible to other tenants even during database failures or maintenance. Which multi-tenancy architecture provides the strongest isolation?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Shared database, shared schema — tenant_id column in all tables with application-level access control"},{"id":"b","text":"Shared database, separate schemas — each tenant has their own schema (namespace) within a single database instance, providing schema-level isolation and separate namespace"},{"id":"c","text":"Separate database per tenant — each tenant gets their own database instance (database-per-tenant), providing complete physical isolation including separate connection pools, backup domains, and failure domains"},{"id":"d","text":"Separate database per tenant provides the strongest isolation, but separate schemas within a shared database is equally strong for most compliance requirements"}]','c','Database-per-tenant (separate database instance per tenant) provides the strongest isolation: each tenant has a separate connection pool, separate backup domain, separate resource allocation, and failures are fully contained. Shared-schema (tenant_id column) has the weakest isolation — a SQL injection or misconfigured query could cross tenant boundaries. Shared-schema-with-schema isolation is better but still shares the database server (resource contention, shared failure domain). For compliance-heavy workloads (healthcare, finance), database-per-tenant or even separate database servers per tenant are required. Option D''s second clause is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','A Cassandra cluster uses a partition key to distribute data across nodes. You discover that one partition is receiving 10x more traffic than others (a ''hot partition''). What are the consequences and what mitigation strategies exist?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Hot partitions are handled automatically by Cassandra''s gossip protocol; no manual intervention is required"},{"id":"b","text":"Hot partitions cause one node to become a bottleneck, saturating its resources while others sit idle; mitigations include adding a ''write path'' that buffers hot data in an in-memory store (e.g., Redis), splitting the hot partition key into sub-partitions, or using request rate limiting at the coordinator node"},{"id":"c","text":"Hot partitions can be eliminated by increasing the replication factor — more replicas spread the load across more nodes"},{"id":"d","text":"Cassandra''s consistent hashing automatically balances partitions evenly regardless of access patterns — hot partitions indicate a bug in the application"}]','b','Cassandra distributes data by partition key — if a key maps to a frequently accessed entity (e.g., a celebrity''s user profile), all reads/writes for that entity hit a single node (or replica group), creating a bottleneck. Cassandra''s repair and read mechanisms can amplify this (anti-caching, read-repair). Mitigations: (1) write-behind cache (Redis in front of Cassandra) to absorb hot reads, (2) token-range splitting to add more vnodes for the hot range, (3) bucketing the partition key (userId_timestamp_bucket) to spread load across more partitions, (4) local-patch: keep the hot entity in a separate store. Option A is false. Option C only applies to replication factor for durability, not load distribution. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Your application requires serializable isolation (the strongest isolation level) to prevent all concurrency anomalies, but PostgreSQL''s serializable isolation is causing significant performance degradation. What alternative approaches can provide serializability without full serializable locking?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Use READ COMMITTED isolation and add explicit row-level locks (SELECT FOR UPDATE) around all transactions — this provides serializability equivalent behavior without serializable snapshot isolation overhead"},{"id":"b","text":"Move to an optimistic concurrency control pattern: use version numbers or optimistic locks, detect conflicts at commit time, and retry conflicting transactions — this provides serializability without blocking locks at the cost of transaction retry overhead"},{"id":"c","text":"Serialized operations cannot be achieved without serializable isolation — any alternative will permit anomalies"},{"id":"d","text":"Use READ UNCOMMITTED and rely on application-level checks to prevent dirty reads — this is functionally equivalent to serializable with better performance"}]','b','Serializable snapshot isolation (SSI) in PostgreSQL uses a serialized execution plan but can cause significant lock contention for write-heavy workloads. Optimistic concurrency control (OCC) is an alternative: transactions read data without locking, record a version/timestamp or checksum of what they read, and at commit time verify no concurrent modification occurred. If a conflict is detected, the transaction retries. This works well for read-heavy workloads with occasional conflicts, but can cause livelock (starvation) under high write contention. Option A''s explicit locking approach is serializable but uses pessimistic locking (blocking). Option C is false. Option D is dangerous and false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','You need to implement a globally distributed database that can serve low-latency reads from multiple regions while tolerating region failures. Read-your-writes consistency for the same user is required. Which combination of strategies best addresses these requirements?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Use a single primary region with asynchronous read replicas in other regions — serve all reads from the primary to guarantee read-your-writes consistency"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a multi-region database with read replicas in each region, and after a write, route the same user''s subsequent reads to the writer region for a time window (session-level consistency), falling back to replica reads elsewhere"},{"id":"c","text":"Disable eventual consistency entirely by configuring synchronous multi-region replication with quorum consensus — all regions confirm every write before acknowledgment"},{"id":"d","text":"Store all user-specific data in a client-side local database (IndexedDB) that syncs asynchronously — read-your-writes is guaranteed locally without any server-side consistency guarantees"}]','b','Global multi-region databases (DynamoDB Global Tables, Cosmos DB, CockroachDB, Spanner) provide eventual consistency by default. Read-your-writes (session consistency) is achieved by routing reads to the writer region briefly after a write — known as ''sticky sessions to the writer.'' This is the standard pragmatic approach: it keeps writes latency bounded by the nearest region''s round-trip to the primary, while giving users consistent reads for their own data. Option A sacrifices the benefit of geo-distribution for reads. Option C (synchronous multi-region quorum) has extremely high write latency (satellite link round-trip time). Option D is a client-side pattern, not a database architecture.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','True or False: A composite index on (last_name, first_name) can be used efficiently for a query that filters only on first_name.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','In a B-tree composite index, the leading column(s) must be present in the query filter for the index to be used efficiently. An index on (last_name, first_name) supports efficient queries on (last_name) and (last_name, first_name), but a query filtering only on first_name cannot use the index — the database must scan the entire index or table because first_name appears after last_name in the index structure. This is the ''leading column rule'' for composite B-tree indexes. Queries on first_name alone require a separate index on first_name. This is a common source of performance bugs in large applications.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','You are designing a time-series IoT database where millions of sensor readings arrive per second. Each reading has a device_id, timestamp, and value. What indexing and partitioning strategy best supports both high ingestion throughput and efficient time-range queries per device?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Store all readings in a single table with a primary key on (timestamp) only — this enables fast time-range scans; device_id is stored as a regular column for filtering"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a composite partition key of (device_id, timestamp) — partitioning by device_id colocates each device''s data on the same nodes, enabling efficient per-device time-range queries, while timestamp ordering within each partition enables efficient range scans; use bucketing within partitions for very high volume devices"},{"id":"c","text":"Create a separate database for each device to ensure complete isolation — this is the only way to handle millions of writes per second"},{"id":"d","text":"Store raw readings in a key-value store (Redis) for write throughput, and move all historical data to a SQL database for analytical queries — separate stores eliminate the need for complex indexing"}]','b','Time-series databases (TimescaleDB, InfluxDB, Cassandra with bucketing) use a (device_id, timestamp) composite partition key to colocate each device''s data on the same nodes. This enables efficient per-device range queries (partition pruning eliminates unrelated devices) and high write throughput (each device''s writes go to its own partition). Time-ordering within partitions supports efficient time-range scans. For extremely high-volume devices, sub-partition bucketing (splitting by time bucket within the partition) prevents oversized partitions. Option A causes hot spots on a single partition. Option C is operationally unmanageable at scale. Option D creates data silos and synchronization complexity.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the fundamental difference between a message queue and a publish-subscribe (pub/sub) system?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A message queue and pub/sub are identical — the terms are interchangeable in modern distributed systems"},{"id":"b","text":"A message queue delivers each message to exactly one consumer (point-to-point); a pub/sub delivers each message to all subscribed consumers (fan-out) — the key distinction is the delivery semantics"},{"id":"c","text":"A pub/sub system stores messages permanently; a message queue deletes messages after delivery"},{"id":"d","text":"A message queue requires producers and consumers to be online simultaneously; pub/sub does not"}]','b','Message queues (SQS, RabbitMQ classic queue mode) implement point-to-point: each message is consumed by exactly one consumer — once consumed, it is removed or marked consumed. Pub/sub (Kafka topics, RabbitMQ fanout/exchange, Google Pub/Sub) implements fan-out: each message is delivered to all active subscribers. A payment processing system uses a queue (one processor handles each payment). A notification system uses pub/sub (email, SMS, push all get the same event). Option A is false. Option C conflates delivery with persistence. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','An order service publishes an OrderCreated event to a message broker. A payment service and an inventory service both need to process this event independently. Which messaging pattern best supports this requirement?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A message queue — the broker delivers the event to one consumer; that consumer then forwards the event to both services sequentially"},{"id":"b","text":"A fan-out exchange or pub/sub topic — each subscriber (payment service, inventory service) receives its own independent copy of the OrderCreated event to process independently"},{"id":"c","text":"A direct point-to-point channel between the order service and each consumer — the order service must maintain separate connections to each consumer"},{"id":"d","text":"A message queue with competing consumers — both services compete to consume the same event, and the first one to grab it wins"}]','b','Fan-out pub/sub: the OrderCreated event is published once to a topic/exchange, and each subscriber gets its own independent subscription and copy. The payment service and inventory service each process their own copy — no competition, no coordination needed. This is the core pattern for event-driven architectures where multiple independent services need to react to the same business event. Option A (queue) delivers to one consumer — the other service would never see the event. Option C is not a messaging pattern — it describes direct coupling. Option D (competing consumers) is the queue model — only one wins.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is a dead-letter queue (DLQ) in a message queue system, and when is it used?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A dead-letter queue is the main queue where unprocessed messages accumulate — it is used to track messages that need manual review"},{"id":"b","text":"A dead-letter queue captures messages that fail processing repeatedly (exceed max delivery attempts) so they don''t block the main queue; failed messages are inspected, retried with backoff, or routed to an alerting system for manual resolution"},{"id":"c","text":"A dead-letter queue is used to store messages before they are published — acting as a staging area to control message throughput"},{"id":"d","text":"Dead-letter queues are only needed for batch processing systems, not real-time event streaming"}]','b','A dead-letter queue (DLQ) is a designated queue that receives messages that fail processing after a configurable number of retry attempts (maxDeliveries). Without a DLQ, failed messages would be re-queued infinitely (poison message) or silently dropped. DLQ enables: (1) isolating toxic messages that can''t be processed (malformed payload, business rule change), (2) alerting and manual inspection, (3) manual replay after fixing downstream issues. Best practice: set max attempts (e.g., 3), use exponential backoff between retries, and always DLQ. Option A misdescribes the main queue. Option C describes a staging queue, not DLQ. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Your system needs at-least-once delivery semantics — every message must be processed at least once, but duplicates are acceptable. What techniques does a consumer use to achieve this safely?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"At-least-once requires synchronous acknowledgment of each message before the next message is consumed — this guarantees each message is processed exactly once"},{"id":"b","text":"A consumer uses idempotency keys (message ID + deduplication check in DB) to safely process the same message multiple times — the downstream operation is idempotent so duplicates are harmless"},{"id":"c","text":"At-least-once delivery is impossible to implement reliably in asynchronous systems — you can only guarantee at-most-once"},{"id":"d","text":"Use a consumer-side TTL that discards messages after 1 second — if not processed in time, the message is considered lost"}]','b','At-least-once delivery means the broker redelivers messages if the consumer fails before acknowledging. This can cause duplicates. The consumer''s job is to make operations idempotent: (1) check if a message ID was already processed (deduplication table in DB), (2) use database unique constraints on message_id to reject duplicates, (3) design the downstream operation to be naturally idempotent (e.g., ''set value to X'' is idempotent, ''increment by 1'' is not). Exactly-once semantics (across producer → broker → consumer) requires distributed transactions or a two-phase commit — expensive. Option A describes synchronous processing, not at-least-once. Option C is false. Option D is at-most-once behavior.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Apache Kafka uses a log-based storage model. What happens when a consumer group processes messages, and how does Kafka''s offset management support this?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Kafka stores messages in a queue and deletes them after acknowledgment — consumers compete for messages like in traditional message queues"},{"id":"b","text":"Kafka retains messages in a persistent append-only log partitioned by topic; consumers track their own offset (position in the log) and can replay messages from any offset — enabling replay of historical events, backfilling, and flexible consumer group scaling without message loss"},{"id":"c","text":"Kafka delivers each message to all consumers simultaneously — there is no consumer group concept"},{"id":"d","text":"Consumer offsets are stored in the database by the application — Kafka itself does not track consumer position"}]','b','Kafka''s log-based model is fundamentally different from queue-based systems. Messages are stored partitioned and committed to an append-only log (persisted to disk, configurable retention). Consumers in a consumer group share partitions: each partition is assigned to one consumer in the group. Each consumer tracks its own offset (committing after successful processing). Because offsets are tracked separately, consumers can: replay from any offset, consume at their own pace, and re-read old messages for debugging or new services. Kafka''s consumer offset storage (in __consumer_offsets topic or __consumer_offsets in KRaft mode) is separate from the main log. Option A describes queue semantics (not Kafka). Option C is false. Option D is only partially true.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between Amazon SQS Standard Queue and SQS FIFO Queue in terms of delivery guarantees and ordering semantics?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Both SQS Standard and FIFO provide exactly-once delivery with strict ordering — the difference is only throughput capacity"},{"id":"b","text":"SQS Standard Queue provides at-least-once delivery with best-effort ordering (messages may be delivered out of order); SQS FIFO Queue provides exactly-once processing with strict FIFO ordering of messages within a message group ID"},{"id":"c","text":"SQS FIFO Queue provides at-least-once delivery; SQS Standard Queue provides at-most-once delivery"},{"id":"d","text":"SQS Standard Queue has higher throughput but no ordering guarantee; SQS FIFO has lower throughput and guarantees messages are delivered in the order they were published across ALL messages in the queue globally"}]','b','SQS Standard: at-least-once delivery (duplicates possible), best-effort ordering (occasional out-of-order delivery). SQS FIFO: exactly-once processing (deduplication via message deduplication ID or content-based hash), strict FIFO ordering within a message group ID. FIFO queues limit throughput to ~300 messages/second per API call (or ~3,000 with batching) vs. near-unlimited for Standard. FIFO ordering is per message group ID — multiple groups can be processed concurrently while maintaining FIFO within each group. Option A is false (Standard does not provide exactly-once). Option C reverses the guarantees. Option D overstates FIFO global ordering.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Event-driven architecture (EDA) decouples producers from consumers. What is the key advantage of loose coupling in EDA, and what new challenges does it introduce?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"EDA eliminates the need for any monitoring or observability because events are self-describing and always processed correctly"},{"id":"b","text":"EDA decouples producers and consumers in time (async) and space (different deployment units) — allowing independent scaling, fault isolation, and enabling new consumers to react to existing events without modifying the producer; challenges include debugging distributed event flows, handling out-of-order events, and managing event schema evolution"},{"id":"c","text":"Event-driven architecture is fundamentally simpler than synchronous request-response because it removes the need for error handling and retry logic"},{"id":"d","text":"Loose coupling in EDA means producers and consumers share the same data schema to avoid translation overhead"}]','b','EDA''s temporal and spatial decoupling enables: independent service evolution, addition of new consumers without touching producers, different teams working autonomously, resilience (producer doesn''t need to know if consumers are up). The challenges: (1) debugging is harder — no single call stack, (2) ordering is not guaranteed unless explicitly designed for, (3) schema changes (adding fields) must be backward-compatible, (4) eventual consistency means consumers may see a different state at any moment, (5) observability requires distributed tracing across event boundaries. Option A is false. Option C is false. Option D describes tight coupling.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the ''at-most-once'' delivery semantics problem, and why is it generally undesirable for business-critical operations?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"At-most-once means messages are guaranteed to arrive within 1 millisecond of being sent — it is the fastest delivery mode"},{"id":"b","text":"At-most-once delivery means a message may be lost entirely if the consumer fails before processing — the system never re-delivers; for business operations (payment, order), losing a message causes real-world consequences (money uncharged, order unfulfilled) — making at-most-once unacceptable"},{"id":"c","text":"At-most-once is the default and preferred mode in Kafka and SQS; it is safer than at-least-once because duplicates are never sent"},{"id":"d","text":"At-most-once only applies to batch processing systems, not real-time event streams"}]','b','At-most-once: message is delivered once OR not at all — if the consumer fails after delivery but before processing, the message is lost and not retried. For business-critical operations (charging a card, sending an email, reserving inventory), losing the message is unacceptable. At-least-once (retry until acknowledged) + idempotency handling (deduplication) is the standard for business events. Exactly-once (across producer → broker → consumer) is the gold standard but expensive (distributed transactions). Option A mischaracterizes it. Option C is false (at-most-once is not the default in Kafka/SQS). Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A consumer processes a message and then crashes before acknowledging it. With SQS, what happens to this message?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"SQS deletes the message immediately upon delivery — it is lost and cannot be recovered"},{"id":"b","text":"SQS holds the message invisibly for the visibility timeout window (30 seconds default); if no acknowledgment is received, the message becomes visible again in the queue and is delivered to another consumer (or retried by the same consumer after the timeout)"},{"id":"c","text":"SQS moves the message to the dead-letter queue automatically after the first failure"},{"id":"d","text":"SQS immediately redelivers the message to the same consumer every 5 seconds until acknowledged"}]','b','SQS uses a visibility timeout mechanism: when a consumer receives a message, it is invisible to other consumers for the visibility timeout period (default 30s, configurable 0s–12h). If the consumer doesn''t delete the message within this window, SQS makes it visible again for another delivery attempt. The consumer can call ChangeMessageVisibility to extend the window if processing takes longer. DLQ movement requires explicit configuration of maxReceiveCount on the queue''s redrive policy. Option A is false. Option C requires explicit DLQ configuration. Option D is not how SQS works.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: In an event-driven architecture, the event bus (or message broker) is a trusted component — events published to the bus are always processed correctly by all consumers.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','The event bus is not a trusted trust boundary in the sense that it provides no application-level guarantees about consumer behavior. Consumers can crash, throw exceptions, process events out of order, or misinterpret event schemas. The bus only guarantees delivery semantics (at-least-once, at-most-once, etc.) — not application correctness. Producers must design for consumer failures: use idempotency keys, version events, and handle poison messages via DLQs. Additionally, a consumer can be down for an extended period and miss events entirely (backfill requires explicit replay support, e.g., Kafka log retention). Trust must be earned by the consumer with proper error handling, not assumed from the bus.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: Apache Kafka guarantees that messages are always delivered to consumers in the exact order they were produced.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','Kafka guarantees ordering within a single partition. Because messages within a partition are stored in a committed append-only log, they are delivered to any consumer in offset order. However, if a topic has multiple partitions (which is the normal case for parallelism), different partitions receive messages in parallel and there is no global ordering across partitions. Only messages with the same partition key are guaranteed to be in order (because they go to the same partition). If global event ordering is required, use a single-partition topic (at the cost of throughput). This is a common misconception from Kafka''s default multi-partition configuration.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: A message queue and a database table can be used interchangeably for storing work that needs to be processed asynchronously — both are valid patterns for implementing a task queue.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','Databases can implement simple work queues (polling a jobs table, SELECT FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED) but are not a substitute for purpose-built message brokers. Databases are not designed for high-throughput message consumption patterns, lack native push notifications to consumers, require polling or scheduled jobs to check for new work, and create contention on the same tables used for application data. Purpose-built brokers (Kafka, SQS, RabbitMQ) provide delivery guarantees, DLQs, routing, fan-out, observability, and consumption models designed for message processing. Using a DB as a queue is a temporary shortcut that creates polling overhead, scalability bottlenecks, and operational complexity at scale.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','You are designing an event-driven order processing system with multiple microservices: OrderService, PaymentService, InventoryService, and ShippingService. Each service must process events in the correct order (e.g., payment must complete before shipping). How do you design for distributed saga orchestration with message queues?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Use a central orchestrator (saga orchestrator) that sends sequential commands to each service via dedicated queues; each service publishes a reply event to the orchestrator; on failure, the orchestrator sends compensating transactions (e.g., refund) in reverse order"},{"id":"b","text":"Let all services subscribe to the same topic and process events as they arrive — each service is responsible for detecting out-of-order events and waiting for the correct sequence"},{"id":"c","text":"Use a global database transaction that spans all services — message queues cannot participate in distributed transactions"},{"id":"d","text":"Serialize all events through a single Kafka partition with a fixed ordering key to guarantee cross-service ordering — this is the standard approach for saga patterns"}]','a','The saga pattern manages distributed transactions without distributed locks (no 2PC). Two approaches: (1) Choreography — services publish events that trigger other services; events chain; compensating transactions are triggered by failure events. (2) Orchestration — a central saga orchestrator sends commands to each service, waits for reply events, and coordinates the sequence; on failure, it sends compensating transactions (refund, inventory restore) in reverse order. For a multi-step order flow with strict ordering requirements, orchestration provides better visibility and control. Option B is unreliable — distributed ordering without explicit coordination is not guaranteed. Option C (global DB transaction) doesn''t work across service boundaries. Option D (single partition) doesn''t solve the saga ordering problem.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Kafka can handle millions of messages per second, but a consumer is experiencing significant lag — the consumer is processing slower than messages are arriving. What are the most effective ways to reduce consumer lag?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Increase the Kafka broker''s disk I/O capacity — consumer lag is always caused by the broker, not the consumer"},{"id":"b","text":"Consumer lag is reduced by: (1) scaling the consumer group horizontally (add more consumer instances, each assigned additional partitions), (2) increasing consumer parallelism (more partitions), (3) optimizing consumer processing logic (batch processing, async I/O, connection pooling), (4) partitioning strategy — ensure the partition key distributes load evenly and doesn''t create hot partitions"},{"id":"c","text":"Restart the Kafka consumer — lag is caused by in-memory state corruption and restarting clears it"},{"id":"d","text":"Consumer lag is a normal and acceptable state — it indicates the system is buffering messages for later processing and poses no risk"}]','b','Consumer lag (difference between latest offset and consumer''s committed offset) indicates the consumer can''t keep up with producers. Solutions: (1) horizontal scaling — add more consumer instances; Kafka partitions are the unit of parallelism, so more partitions enable more consumers. (2) Optimize consumer code: use batch consume (poll N messages, process in parallel), async I/O for downstream calls, connection pooling, efficient deserialization. (3) Partitioning strategy: if one partition is hot (e.g., celebrity user), it creates a bottleneck — split or add a bucket dimension to the key. (4) For very slow consumers, consider offloading to a pre-processing pipeline. Option A is wrong (lag is a consumer-side problem). Option C is not a general solution. Option D is false for real-time systems.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','You need to implement a pattern where a message should be processed exactly once, even if the message broker, consumer, and downstream database all have independent failure modes. What is the minimal architecture needed for exactly-once processing?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Exactly-once is impossible in distributed systems without a central coordinator — use at-least-once with client-side idempotency as the practical equivalent"},{"id":"b","text":"Exactly-once requires coordinating producer, broker, and consumer: producer uses idempotency keys, broker deduplicates (Kafka idempotent producer + transactions), and consumer deduplicates in a database using the message ID as a unique constraint — the combination of these three layers achieves exactly-once semantics"},{"id":"c","text":"Use a two-phase commit (2PC) protocol across the message broker and consumer database — this guarantees exactly-once by atomically committing both the message acknowledgment and the database write"},{"id":"d","text":"Exactly-once can be achieved by setting the message TTL to 0 and using synchronous acknowledgment — the broker will automatically retry until exactly-once is achieved"}]','b','Exactly-once delivery across all three layers: (1) Kafka''s idempotent producer + transactional production ensures a message is written to the log exactly once. (2) Kafka''s transactional consume + commit (using the consumer offset in the same transaction as the DB write) ensures the offset and the database change are committed atomically. (3) Consumer deduplication: the DB write uses message_id as a unique constraint — if a duplicate message is consumed (broker redelivery), the DB insert/update is a no-op. This is the Kafka transactional API + outbox pattern. Option A dismisses it as impossible — it''s achievable but complex. Option C (2PC) doesn''t apply to Kafka consumer commits. Option D is nonsense.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','A system processes 10,000 events per second. Each event triggers a downstream HTTP API call. Under peak load, downstream API timeouts are causing message processing failures and retry storms. What is the most effective mitigation?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Remove retries entirely — failed messages should go directly to the DLQ to prevent retry storms"},{"id":"b","text":"Implement a retry queue with exponential backoff with jitter: on first failure, re-queue with a 1-second delay; on second failure, 2 seconds; on third, 4 seconds; cap at a maximum; use jitter (randomized delay) to prevent thundering herd when the downstream recovers"},{"id":"c","text":"Reduce the number of concurrent consumers to 1 — sequential processing prevents API overload and ensures all retries are processed in order"},{"id":"d","text":"Increase the downstream API''s timeout from 1 second to 30 seconds — this gives the downstream more time to respond under load"}]','b','Exponential backoff with jitter is the standard mitigation for retry storms: each retry waits longer before retrying, preventing a flood of simultaneous retries from overwhelming a recovering downstream service. Jitter (randomization added to each delay) prevents synchronized retry storms where all consumers retry at exactly the same moment (e.g., all retry after 1s, all fail, all retry after 2s — thundering herd). Best practice: exponential backoff with full jitter (random value between 0 and min(cap, base * 2^attempt)) — this is the AWS architecture blog recommended approach. Option A (no retries) loses messages. Option C (sequential) kills throughput. Option D (longer timeout) increases resource contention.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Your event-driven system requires events to be consumed in order within a partition, but a downstream service (e.g., an email service) cannot handle concurrent processing — it requires sequential processing. How do you design for both ordering and sequential consumption?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Use a single-partition topic for all events — this guarantees ordering but limits throughput to one consumer and is the only way to ensure sequential processing"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a partition key that colocates events requiring sequential processing on the same partition — all events for a given entity (e.g., user_id) go to the same partition and are processed in order by a single-threaded consumer; other entities can be processed concurrently in parallel partitions"},{"id":"c","text":"Sequential processing and ordering are incompatible in distributed systems — you must choose one"},{"id":"d","text":"Implement a distributed lock at the consumer level — each consumer acquires a lock for the entity before processing, ensuring only one consumer processes events for that entity at a time"}]','b','Kafka partitions are the unit of ordering and parallelism. All events with the same partition key land in the same partition and are delivered in order to the consumer assigned to that partition. A single-threaded consumer (or single-threaded processing loop per partition) guarantees sequential processing for that entity. Multiple entities (different user_ids) go to different partitions and are processed in parallel. This is the standard pattern: partition by business key (user_id, order_id) to ensure causal ordering for related events. Option A (single partition) is too limiting — throughput is limited to one consumer. Option C is false. Option D (distributed lock) is expensive and unnecessary when partition-based colocation achieves the same goal more efficiently.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','True or False: In Kafka, a consumer group with 10 consumers can process a topic with only 3 partitions efficiently — adding more consumers than partitions provides no throughput benefit.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','Kafka partitions are the unit of parallelism. Each partition can only be assigned to one consumer in a group at a time. With 3 partitions, at most 3 consumers are actively processing messages simultaneously — the remaining 7 consumers sit idle. This is a common Kafka misconfiguration: oversizing consumer groups beyond partition count wastes resources. Solution: scale consumers to match partition count (or slightly fewer for fault tolerance), and scale partitions when scaling consumers. The partition count is the upper bound on consumer parallelism for that topic.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','An e-commerce platform uses Kafka to publish OrderPlaced events. A new NotificationService is being added to send confirmation emails. You need to ensure that when the NotificationService is deployed, it can backfill and process historical events from the past 7 days. What Kafka configuration supports this?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Kafka topics have a fixed retention of 7 days; configure the retention.ms parameter to 7 days and ensure the consumer group offset is reset to ''earliest'' when the new consumer first subscribes"},{"id":"b","text":"Create a new Kafka topic specifically for the NotificationService with a 7-day retention period; replay historical events from the OrderPlaced topic into the new topic using Kafka Streams or a Kafka Connect connector"},{"id":"c","text":"Kafka automatically retains all messages indefinitely; any new consumer can always read from the beginning regardless of when it was deployed"},{"id":"d","text":"Configure the consumer group''s offset reset policy to ''latest'' so the new service only processes new events as they arrive"}]','b','Kafka log retention is configurable (default: 7 days for log.retention.ms; varies by broker/tier). However, a topic configured for 7-day retention will have events older than 7 days deleted — you cannot backfill beyond the retention window. To backfill historical events for a new consumer: (1) create a dedicated topic or use an existing one with sufficient retention, (2) replay historical events from the source of truth (database CDC, event store, or original topic) using Kafka Connect Debezium CDC, Kafka Streams, or a custom replay job. Option A works only if the topic was already configured for 7-day retention when events were produced — if events are older, they''re gone. Option C is false. Option D (latest) is for new production consumers, not backfill.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the primary purpose of an API Gateway in a microservices architecture, and what problems does it solve?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"An API Gateway replaces the service mesh by providing distributed tracing and metrics collection for all services"},{"id":"b","text":"An API Gateway acts as a single entry point for all client requests, handling cross-cutting concerns like authentication, rate limiting, protocol translation (HTTP → gRPC), request routing, and aggregation — so individual services don''t need to implement these concerns"},{"id":"c","text":"An API Gateway is a database proxy that routes database queries to the appropriate microservice based on the query type"},{"id":"d","text":"An API Gateway is only needed for legacy monolithic applications migrating to microservices"}]','b','The API Gateway is the single entry point for all external (and sometimes internal) client traffic. It handles cross-cutting concerns (auth, TLS termination, rate limiting, load balancing, request routing, protocol translation) so microservices remain focused on business logic. It can also aggregate multiple backend calls into a single client response (GraphQL Federation, BFF pattern). Without a gateway, each service must implement auth/rate-limiting separately, creating duplication and inconsistency. Popular gateways: Kong, AWS API Gateway, Envoy (as gateway), Nginx. Option A confuses gateway with service mesh. Option C is false. Option D is false — gateways are standard in greenfield microservices too.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Service A needs to call Service B in a microservices system. Service B occasionally becomes slow or unavailable. What pattern prevents Service A from also becoming unresponsive when Service B degrades?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Circuit breaker — if the failure rate to Service B exceeds a threshold, the circuit ''opens'' and immediately returns a fallback response without calling Service B, preventing resource exhaustion and cascading failure"},{"id":"b","text":"Retry with exponential backoff — Service A retries Service B indefinitely until it succeeds; this is the standard circuit breaker behavior"},{"id":"c","text":"Load balancer — the load balancer automatically routes traffic away from failing instances of Service B"},{"id":"d","text":"Service registry — Service B registers its availability in a service registry, allowing Service A to discover healthy instances"}]','a','Circuit breaker (Michael Nygard, Release It!): a state machine (Closed → Open → Half-Open) monitors call failures. When failures exceed a threshold (e.g., >50% in 10 seconds), the breaker ''opens'' — subsequent calls fail immediately (fallback) without making the network call. After a timeout, it moves to ''half-open'' (allow one test call). If it succeeds, it closes; if it fails, it reopens. This prevents resource exhaustion (pool threads waiting on dead services) and cascading failures. Retry (B) without circuit breaker makes things worse under load. Load balancer (C) handles node-level failure, not service-level degradation. Service registry (D) handles discovery, not resilience.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is service discovery in microservices, and what is the difference between client-side and server-side discovery?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Service discovery is the process of routing API requests to the correct version of a service using semantic versioning"},{"id":"b","text":"Client-side discovery: the client queries a service registry (e.g., Eureka, Consul) to find service endpoints and load balances among them; server-side discovery: a router or load balancer (e.g., AWS ALB, Envoy) queries the registry and routes requests on behalf of the client — the client is unaware of the discovery process"},{"id":"c","text":"Server-side discovery requires each microservice to implement its own load balancing logic; client-side discovery uses a centralized load balancer"},{"id":"d","text":"Service discovery is only needed when using Docker containers; VMs do not require it"}]','b','Client-side discovery (Eureka, Consul + client SDK): the service consumer queries the registry directly, picks an instance, and handles load balancing — lightweight but couples clients to the registry API. Server-side discovery (AWS ALB, NGINX, service mesh sidecar like Envoy): the client sends requests to a well-known router, which queries the registry and routes — clients are simpler but the router is another component to manage. Kubernetes uses server-side discovery via kube-proxy + DNS (CoreDNS) — pods discover services via environment variables and DNS. Option A misdefines discovery. Option C reverses the definitions. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What are the two main approaches to implementing the saga pattern in microservices, and when would you choose orchestration over choreography?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Orchestration: a central coordinator sends commands to each service and waits for replies; Choreography: services publish and subscribe to events and react autonomously — use orchestration when you need explicit visibility, complex ordering, and clear failure handling; use choreography for simpler, loosely coupled flows"},{"id":"b","text":"Choreography is when a central database coordinates transactions across services; orchestration is when each service manages its own transaction independently"},{"id":"c","text":"Saga pattern uses distributed locks (2PC) for coordination; orchestration is the name for implementing saga without 2PC"},{"id":"d","text":"Orchestration and choreography are identical — both involve a central coordinator sending messages to services"}]','a','Saga Choreography: services publish domain events (e.g., OrderService publishes OrderPlaced → triggers PaymentService which publishes PaymentSucceeded → triggers InventoryService). No central coordinator — services react to events autonomously. Simple flows work well; complex flows create tangled event chains. Saga Orchestration: a saga orchestrator (a separate service or state machine) sends commands (ProcessPayment) to services, receives events, and decides next steps. Better for complex multi-step flows, gives clear visibility, and centralizes compensating transaction logic. Use orchestration for: complex ordering dependencies, multiple participants, and when you need a clear audit trail. Use choreography for: simple 2-3 step flows.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What are the three states of a circuit breaker, and what is the purpose of the half-open state?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Closed, Open, and Half-Open: Closed = circuit breaker is disabled; Open = circuit breaker is overloaded and logging all requests; Half-Open = circuit breaker is resetting after a timeout"},{"id":"b","text":"Closed (normal operation, failures counted), Open (failures exceeded threshold — calls fail immediately with fallback), and Half-Open (timeout elapsed — one test call allowed to check if the downstream service has recovered; if success → Closed, if failure → Open)"},{"id":"c","text":"Closed, Open, and Retrying: Closed = all requests pass; Open = all requests fail and are retried with backoff; Retrying = requests are queued for later processing"},{"id":"d","text":"Half-Open only exists in software circuit breakers, not hardware; hardware circuit breakers have only Closed and Open states"}]','b','Circuit breaker states: (1) Closed: normal operation, failures counted; if failures exceed threshold (e.g., 5 failures in 10s), transition to Open. (2) Open: all calls fail immediately with fallback, no calls reach the downstream — protecting it from being overwhelmed. (3) Half-Open: after a reset timeout, allow a limited number of test calls through; if they succeed, transition to Closed (recovered); if they fail, transition back to Open. The half-open state prevents a permanently broken downstream from staying open forever and allows recovery detection. Libraries: Resilience4j (Java), Hystrix (Netflix, in maintenance), Polly (.NET), circuit_breaker (Elixir).')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the 12-factor app methodology, and which factors are most relevant to microservices deployment and operation?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"The 12-factor app is a set of 12 coding guidelines focused on improving test coverage in microservices — factors 1-6 cover unit testing"},{"id":"b","text":"The 12-factor app (Heroku, 2011) defines 12 best practices for cloud-native applications: factor IV (config store), VI (process stateless), XI (logs as event stream), XII (admin processes) are especially relevant to microservices — enabling independent deployability, horizontal scaling, and observability"},{"id":"c","text":"The 12-factor app mandates that all microservices must be written in the same programming language to ensure consistency"},{"id":"d","text":"The 12-factor app is primarily a database design methodology — factors 7-12 cover data management best practices"}]','b','The 12-factor app (heroku.com/blog/12factor) defines 12 principles for software-as-a-service: I. Codebase (one repo per service), II. Dependencies (explicitly declared), III. Config (store config in environment), IV. Backing services (DBs, caches as attached resources), V. Build/release-run (strict separation), VI. Processes (stateless, no local state), VII. Port binding (export services via port), VIII. Concurrency (scale via process model), IX. Disposability (graceful shutdown), X. Dev/prod parity, XI. Logs (treat as event streams), XII. Admin processes (run admin tasks same as app). For microservices: Factor III (config) enables per-environment config without code changes; Factor VI (stateless) enables horizontal scaling; Factor XI (logs) enables centralized observability.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is observability in the context of microservices, and why is it more challenging than in a monolithic application?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Observability means collecting logs only — metrics and traces are optional add-ons for microservices"},{"id":"b","text":"Observability means the ability to understand a system''s internal state from its external outputs; in microservices it requires three pillars — metrics (Prometheus), distributed traces (Jaeger/Zipkin), and structured logs — to correlate events across service boundaries and diagnose failures in a distributed call chain"},{"id":"c","text":"Observability is less challenging in microservices because each service is small and easier to debug in isolation"},{"id":"d","text":"Observability is only needed in production environments, not during development or testing"}]','b','Observability (observability.io definition): the property of being able to infer internal state from external outputs. The three pillars: (1) Metrics — numerical measurements (latency, error rate, throughput) over time; (2) Distributed traces — a single request''s path through multiple services (trace ID propagates via headers, e.g., W3C TraceContext); (3) Structured logs — machine-readable logs with correlation IDs. In microservices, a single user request may touch 10+ services — without distributed tracing, finding which service caused a latency spike is nearly impossible. The monolith has a single call stack; microservices have a distributed call graph. Option A is false (logs alone are insufficient). Option C is false (distributed = more complex). Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','In microservices, why is it critical that services share nothing (are stateless) and that configuration is externalized from the application code?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Statelessness is optional — services can store local session state as long as they use sticky sessions for routing"},{"id":"b","text":"Stateless services + externalized config are required for independent deployability, horizontal scaling, and fault tolerance — any service instance can handle any request; configuration changes (environment, database URL, feature flags) take effect by restarting the service without rebuilding or redeploying the artifact"},{"id":"c","text":"Externalized configuration is only needed for production environments; development and staging can use hardcoded values"},{"id":"d","text":"Hardcoded configuration is actually better for microservices because it prevents configuration drift between environments"}]','b','Microservices must be independently deployable — if a service needs a configuration change (new feature flag, changed DB URL) and that requires rebuilding the container image, you lose the ability to deploy independently. Configuration must live outside the artifact (environment variables, config maps, Consul, Spring Cloud Config, Vault). Stateless services (no in-memory session, no local filesystem writes as primary state) enable horizontal scaling — any instance handles any request, and instances can be killed/restarted at any time without user impact. Sticky sessions + local state are anti-patterns in microservices. Option A is false. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A microservice needs to notify another microservice when an order is created. The sender does not need to wait for the receiver to process the event. Which communication style is most appropriate?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Synchronous REST/gRPC call — the order service calls the notification service directly and waits for a response"},{"id":"b","text":"Asynchronous messaging (event or message queue) — the order service publishes an OrderCreated event to a message broker; the notification service subscribes and processes it independently; the order service does not wait for the notification to complete"},{"id":"c","text":"WebSocket — the order service opens a persistent connection to the notification service for push-based delivery"},{"id":"d","text":"Database polling — the notification service periodically queries the order database for new orders"}]','b','Asynchronous messaging decouples the producer (OrderService) from the consumer (NotificationService) in both time and space. OrderService publishes once; NotificationService processes at its own pace. Benefits: OrderService is not blocked, NotificationService can be scaled independently, events are durable (queue), and consumers can be added without modifying OrderService. Synchronous REST (A) creates coupling — if NotificationService is down, OrderService fails. WebSocket (C) is connection-oriented and not appropriate for this use case. Database polling (D) is an anti-pattern: creates coupling to schema, wastes resources polling, and introduces delay. Asynchronous messaging is the right pattern for fire-and-forget notifications.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: In microservices, a service should always expose a REST API over HTTP for synchronous calls because it is the most language-agnostic and interoperable protocol.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','REST over HTTP/1.1 is widely supported but has significant overhead for internal microservice-to-microservice calls: JSON serialization/deserialization is slow, HTTP/1.1 connections are blocking (head-of-line blocking), no native streaming, limited schema evolution support. Modern microservices use: gRPC (HTTP/2, binary Protobuf, strongly typed contracts, streaming) for internal synchronous calls where performance matters; REST/HTTP for external-facing APIs where simplicity and browser compatibility matter; GraphQL for client-facing data aggregation APIs. The choice depends on the use case — there is no universal ''most interoperable'' winner. HTTP/2 + gRPC is actually more efficient for high-volume internal traffic.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: In a well-designed microservices architecture, each microservice should own its own database (or schema) and never share database tables or schemas with other services.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','Database per service is a core principle of microservices: each service manages its own data store, and other services access it only through the service''s API — never directly touching another service''s database. This enforces encapsulation and loose coupling: if Service A''s DB schema changes, Service B is unaffected as long as Service A''s API contract is maintained. Shared databases (shared tables, shared schemas across services) create tight coupling — schema changes in one service break other services, making independent deployability impossible. This is the database-per-service pattern, and it prevents the ''distributed monolith'' anti-pattern where services are deployed separately but coupled via a shared database.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: The strangler fig pattern is used to gradually migrate a legacy monolith to microservices by incrementally routing traffic from the monolith to new microservices until the monolith is eventually ''strangled'' and can be decommissioned.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','The strangler fig pattern (Martin Fowler): instead of a risky big-bang rewrite, you incrementally replace monolith functionality with microservices. An API gateway or reverse proxy intercepts requests — new/migrated features route to the new microservice, remaining features continue routing to the monolith. Over time, more traffic migrates to the microservice until the monolith handles only a small stub (eventually zero). Benefits: low risk, incremental value delivery, ability to rollback, real traffic testing. This is the recommended approach for modernizing legacy systems — not rewriting from scratch, which famously fails (Google, Amazon, and others have documented this). The monolith becomes the ''strangler fig'' that is gradually replaced.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','You are designing a microservices architecture where the OrderService synchronously calls PaymentService, which synchronously calls FraudDetectionService, which calls AddressVerificationService. This chain creates a 4-second end-to-end latency. What is this problem called and how do you redesign to reduce latency?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"This is a distributed monolith anti-pattern — all services must be merged back into a single monolith to reduce latency"},{"id":"b","text":"This is the distributed monolith or chatty microservice anti-pattern; redesign by replacing synchronous chains with asynchronous event-driven choreography: OrderService publishes OrderPlaced event; PaymentService, FraudDetectionService, and AddressVerificationService subscribe independently and process in parallel; OrderService waits for a composite event or uses a saga orchestrator"},{"id":"c","text":"This is a cascading failure — the circuit breaker pattern will resolve it without changing the architecture"},{"id":"d","text":"The solution is to increase the timeout values in each service from 1 second to 5 seconds — this gives each service enough time to complete"}]','b','Synchronous chains create ''distributed monolith'' latency: end-to-end latency = sum of all service latencies. A 4-service chain with 1s per service = 4s total. This creates tight coupling (each service must be available for the chain to work) and cascades failures. Redesign: use async choreography or orchestration. OrderService publishes an event once; PaymentService, FraudDetectionService, and AddressVerificationService all process it in parallel (fan-out). Each returns results to the saga orchestrator or writes to a results store. The client polls or uses WebSocket for completion notification. This reduces end-to-end latency to the latency of the slowest step (not the sum). Option A is wrong (the solution is decoupling, not monolith). Option C (circuit breaker) handles failures, not latency. Option D masks the problem.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','In Kubernetes, a pod crashes and a new pod starts. During startup, it receives traffic before it is fully initialized — causing request failures. How does Kubernetes support graceful initialization before receiving production traffic?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Kubernetes automatically delays routing traffic to a new pod until it passes a readiness probe; configure readinessProbe (HTTP GET, TCP socket, or exec) to check if the application is ready to serve traffic — traffic is only routed to pods with a passing readiness probe"},{"id":"b","text":"Kubernetes sends 10% of traffic to all pods simultaneously during startup — this is the standard load balancing behavior and cannot be changed"},{"id":"c","text":"The pod must emit a SIGTERM signal to the ingress controller to signal readiness before accepting traffic"},{"id":"d","text":"Graceful initialization is handled automatically by the container runtime — no configuration needed"}]','a','Kubernetes distinguishes between livenessProbe (is the container alive? restart if not) and readinessProbe (is the container ready to receive traffic?). Only pods with a passing readinessProbe are added to the Service''s endpoint slice and receive traffic. The readiness probe should check: (1) the HTTP endpoint returns 200 (not just that the port is open), (2) database connections are established, (3) cache is warmed. This prevents traffic from being routed to a pod still initializing (JVM warm-up, connection pool creation). Combined with preStop lifecycle hooks (e.g., sleep 5s before SIGTERM), this enables zero-downtime deployments and rolling updates. Option B is false. Option C is unrelated. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','You need to ensure distributed tracing works across 15 microservices for every user request. What is required for traces to correctly link a single request across all 15 services, and what happens if one service fails to propagate the trace context?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Each service must use a shared relational database to store trace IDs and look them up on each call — this is the standard W3C TraceContext approach"},{"id":"b","text":"Each service must propagate a trace ID and span ID via standardized HTTP headers (W3C TraceContext: traceparent, tracestate) on every outgoing HTTP/gRPC call; if any service in the call chain fails to propagate headers, the trace breaks at that point — the portion after the break appears as an unrelated trace or is lost"},{"id":"c","text":"Distributed tracing requires a centralized trace collector that all services poll every 10 seconds — headers are not needed"},{"id":"d","text":"Traces are only maintained within a single Kubernetes cluster — cross-cluster traces are not possible without a shared service mesh"}]','b','Distributed tracing (Jaeger, Zipkin, AWS X-Ray, OpenTelemetry) links a single user request across all services using trace context propagation. The W3C TraceContext standard defines ''traceparent'' (trace-id, span-id, trace flags) and ''tracestate'' headers. The first service creates a root span; each subsequent service: (1) extracts headers from the incoming request, (2) creates a child span linked to the parent span-id, (3) injects headers into outgoing calls. If a service fails to inject headers (e.g., a legacy service or a non-instrumented library call), the trace breaks — the downstream appears as a separate trace. Auto-instrumentation libraries (OpenTelemetry agents) handle this automatically for common frameworks. Option A is false. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','A microservice uses a shared library for database access. When the library needs a critical security patch, all 40 microservices that depend on it must be updated and redeployed. What architectural approach prevents this tight coupling to shared libraries?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Remove all shared libraries and copy the database access code into each microservice individually — this eliminates the shared dependency"},{"id":"b","text":"Use the Sidecar pattern: deploy a sidecar container alongside each microservice in the same pod that handles shared concerns (database connection pooling, metrics, secret injection) — library updates require only sidecar image rebuild, not application rebuild and redeployment"},{"id":"c","text":"Use a monorepo with automatic versioning — when the shared library is updated, a semantic version bump automatically updates all consuming microservices in CI"},{"id":"d","text":"Compile the shared library as a static binary and link it at container build time — this makes library updates invisible to the application"}]','b','The Sidecar pattern (also called ambassador or adapter) deploys a sidecar container alongside each application container in the same pod. The sidecar handles cross-cutting concerns: (1) service mesh sidecar (Envoy) handles network routing, retries, circuit breaking; (2) metrics sidecar (Prometheus node exporter); (3) secret injection sidecar (Vault agent sidecar); (4) database proxy sidecar (PgBouncer). Benefits: the shared logic lives in the sidecar container image, not the application — updating shared logic (e.g., a security patch) requires rebuilding only the sidecar image, not the application. The application is decoupled from the shared concern via a well-defined interface (usually localhost HTTP). Option A (copy-paste) is the scatter pattern, not a solution. Option C (monorepo) doesn''t prevent redeployments. Option D still requires rebuilding.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','You are deploying a new version of a microservice. In-flight requests must complete gracefully, and no requests should be lost. How do you achieve zero-downtime deployment in Kubernetes?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Use a blue-green deployment: spin up the new version alongside the old version, wait for the new version to pass health checks, then switch all traffic at once via the load balancer — zero downtime if the switch is instantaneous"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a rolling update: configure maxUnavailable=0 and maxSurge=1 in the Deployment strategy; combine with preStop sleep (draining in-flight connections) and readinessProbe (ensuring new pods are ready before receiving traffic); this incrementally replaces old pods with new ones while keeping the service available"},{"id":"c","text":"Stop the old version, wait 30 seconds, then start the new version — Kubernetes will automatically route traffic to the new pod once it is running"},{"id":"d","text":"Zero-downtime deployment is not possible in Kubernetes — some requests will always be dropped during version changes"}]','b','Rolling update with proper configuration: maxUnavailable=0 (no old pods killed before new pods are ready), maxSurge=1 (one extra pod during update), readinessProbe checking actual readiness (not just port binding), preStop lifecycle hook with a sleep to allow the kube-proxy to update iptables before SIGKILL, and graceful shutdown handling in the application (catch SIGTERM, stop accepting new connections, finish in-flight requests, then exit). Blue-green (A) also works but requires double the resources and a routing switch. The rolling update is the standard Kubernetes approach. Option C doesn''t handle in-flight requests. Option D is false with proper configuration.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','True or False: In a service mesh architecture, the sidecar proxy (e.g., Envoy) handles all cross-cutting concerns — authentication, authorization, retries, circuit breaking, and telemetry — without any application code changes.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','In a service mesh (Istio, Linkerd, Consul Connect), a sidecar proxy (Envoy, Linkerd proxy) is injected alongside each application pod and intercepts all inbound and outbound network traffic. The mesh control plane (Istiod, Linkerd controller) configures the proxies with policies for: mutual TLS (mTLS) encryption, JWT authentication at the mesh level, rate limiting, retries (with backoff), circuit breaking, traffic splitting (canary deployments), and telemetry (metrics, traces). Application code is unmodified — it simply makes outbound calls to localhost, and the sidecar handles mTLS, routing, and retries transparently. This is the core value proposition of a service mesh: cross-cutting concerns handled at the infrastructure layer, not in application code. Without a mesh, each service must implement these in its own code (e.g., via libraries like Hystrix, Polly).')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','An e-commerce platform needs to support canary deployments: 5% of production traffic should route to the new version of the CheckoutService to validate performance and correctness before full rollout. How do you achieve canary routing in a Kubernetes + service mesh environment?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Use Kubernetes namespace isolation: deploy the new version in a separate namespace and manually configure the ingress controller to route 5% of traffic to the new namespace"},{"id":"b","text":"Use traffic splitting (weight-based routing) in the service mesh (Istio VirtualService, Linkerd) to split traffic: 95% to stable, 5% to canary; use metrics (error rate, latency) from Prometheus to determine if the canary is healthy; if metrics look good, incrementally increase canary weight to 10%, 50%, 100%"},{"id":"c","text":"Canary deployments require a separate Kubernetes cluster for the canary version — routing is done at the DNS level by splitting the domain"},{"id":"d","text":"Use a feature flag service (LaunchDarkly, Unleash) configured with 5% rollout percentage — the application code evaluates the flag and routes internally"}]','b','Service mesh traffic splitting (Istio VirtualService, Linkerd) allows weight-based routing at the mesh level without application changes. Example Istio VirtualService: 95% weight to subset ''stable'', 5% to subset ''canary''. The mesh routes accordingly on every request. This is combined with: Prometheus metrics to monitor error rate and latency during the canary window; automatic rollback (if error rate exceeds threshold, mesh can automatically shift traffic back). Feature flags (D) are complementary but require application code to evaluate the flag — mesh-based routing is infrastructure-level and application-agnostic. Option A (separate namespace) is complex and doesn''t integrate with metrics. Option C (separate cluster) is too heavy. Option D is code-based and less observable than mesh-level routing.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the fundamental difference between vertical scaling (scaling up) and horizontal scaling (scaling out)?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Vertical scaling adds more machines to your pool; horizontal scaling adds more CPU, RAM, and storage to a single machine"},{"id":"b","text":"Vertical scaling adds more CPU, RAM, and disk to an existing machine; horizontal scaling adds more machines to distribute load"},{"id":"c","text":"Both terms describe the same thing — just different terminology used by cloud vs. on-premise vendors"},{"id":"d","text":"Horizontal scaling is limited by the physical constraints of a single machine; vertical scaling has no theoretical upper bound"}]','b','Vertical scaling (scaling up) beefs up a single machine — more CPU cores, RAM, faster disks — improving capacity without changing the architecture. Horizontal scaling (scaling out) adds more machines to the pool, distributing work across nodes. Horizontal is generally preferred for resilience and near-unlimited scale, but requires stateless application design and data partitioning. Vertical scaling hits a hardware ceiling and creates a single point of failure. Option A reverses both terms. Option C is false. Option D reverses the constraints.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A load balancer routes traffic across a pool of application servers. Which algorithm avoids the problem of a single slow server receiving a disproportionate share of requests?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Round-robin — distributes requests equally in rotation regardless of server state"},{"id":"b","text":"Weighted round-robin — assigns a static weight to each server based on its capacity"},{"id":"c","text":"Least connections — routes a new request to the server that currently has the fewest active connections"},{"id":"d","text":"IP hash — maps client IP to a specific server using a hash function for session affinity"}]','c','Least connections routes to the server with the fewest active requests at the moment, naturally accounting for varying request durations. A server processing slow queries accumulates fewer connections than one processing fast queries, so slow servers naturally receive fewer new requests. Round-robin (A) ignores server load and connection count. Weighted round-robin (B) uses static capacity weights, not real-time load. IP hash (D) is a form of sticky session, not a load-based algorithm.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Your system experiences a sudden traffic spike and some servers are overwhelmed while others sit idle. Which load balancing algorithm would best handle heterogeneous server capacities in real time?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Random selection — statistically distributes load across all servers regardless of capacity"},{"id":"b","text":"Weighted least connections — assigns new requests based on both active connection count and a server''s configured capacity weight"},{"id":"c","text":"Sticky sessions — binds each user to one server so their session state is always available"},{"id":"d","text":"Source IP hash — uses the client IP to deterministically select a server for consistent routing"}]','b','Weighted least connections extends the least-connections algorithm by factoring in each server''s capacity weight (configured based on CPU/RAM). A server with weight=2 receives roughly twice as many connections as weight=1 only when its current active connections divided by weight is lower than competing servers. This dynamically adapts to heterogeneous hardware and varying request complexity. Random (A) ignores capacity. Sticky sessions (C) is about session affinity, not load distribution. IP hash (D) is also about affinity.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Under the CAP theorem, what does a CP (Consistent + Partition-tolerant) system sacrifice during a network partition?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Consistency — the system allows stale reads to remain available during a partition"},{"id":"b","text":"Availability — the system refuses requests or returns errors during a partition to maintain consistency"},{"id":"c","text":"Partition tolerance — the system halts completely when a partition is detected"},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing is sacrificed; CP systems handle partitions without any trade-off"}]','b','CP systems choose consistency over availability during network partitions. When a partition occurs, the system may shut down non-majority nodes or block writes to prevent diverged states — serving errors or unavailable responses rather than potentially stale data. Classic CP systems: HBase, MongoDB (with replica sets in certain configs), Zookeeper, etcd. AP systems (Cassandra, DynamoDB) choose availability — they serve reads from any node, potentially returning stale data during partitions. Option A describes AP behavior. Option C is misleading — partition tolerance is the property you must keep.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A user logs into a web app and the load balancer routes them to Server A, which stores their session in memory. On the next request, a different load balancing algorithm routes them to Server B — their session is lost. What is the best architectural fix?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Implement sticky sessions using a session cookie so the user always hits the same server"},{"id":"b","text":"Store session data in a shared distributed cache (e.g., Redis) and make the application stateless; remove server-side session storage entirely"},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the memory of each server so sessions have more space and are less likely to be evicted"},{"id":"d","text":"Use a hardware load balancer with built-in session replication across all backend servers"}]','b','Sticky sessions (A) are a band-aid — they create load imbalance, make server maintenance harder, and don''t survive server crashes. The correct fix is externalizing session state to a shared store (Redis, Memcached) so any server can handle any request. This is the foundation of stateless application architecture — the server doesn''t care which instance handles a request because all state is in the shared layer. Option C doesn''t fix cross-server routing. Option D is expensive and still a band-aid.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','PACELC extends the CAP theorem. In a system with no network partition, what trade-off does PACELC describe?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Even without partitions, you must choose between latency and consistency — stronger consistency means higher latency"},{"id":"b","text":"PACELC states that without partitions, all three properties (Consistency, Availability, Latency) can be maximized simultaneously"},{"id":"c","text":"PACELC is only relevant for single-node databases and has no bearing on distributed systems"},{"id":"d","text":"The trade-off in PACELC is between Partition tolerance and Eventual consistency — latency is not a factor"}]','a','PACELC (Brewer, 2012) adds Latency as a first-class dimension: even when there is no partition (P), you face a choice between Latency (L) and Consistency (C). A system that synchronously replicates writes to all replicas for strong consistency incurs higher write latency than one that asynchronously replicates. DynamoDB: PB (write latency vs. availability), PC/EC (consistency vs. latency). Cassandra: PA/E (availability vs. consistency) + EL (latency vs. consistency). CAP doesn''t capture latency; PACELC does.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A service needs to handle 100,000 concurrent WebSocket connections. Each connection consumes memory and holds a persistent channel to a backend. What architectural approach best addresses this scale?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy a single powerful server with 128+ CPU cores and 512 GB RAM to handle all connections on one machine"},{"id":"b","text":"Use connection pooling on a single database server to multiplex all 100k connections through a small pool of backend threads"},{"id":"c","text":"Horizontally scale WebSocket servers behind a load balancer, use a pub/sub message broker for fan-out, and ensure the application is stateless (no session state on WebSocket servers)"},{"id":"d","text":"Limit the number of concurrent connections per user and reject requests above the threshold"}]','c','WebSocket long-lived connections are memory-intensive and stateful by nature. Horizontal scaling requires stateless application logic (all shared state in Redis/database), a pub/sub broker (Redis pub/sub, NATS, Kafka) to broadcast messages across nodes, and a load balancer with connection draining or WebSocket-aware routing. Single-server approaches (A, B) hit resource limits and create single points of failure. Rejecting connections (D) is not scaling — it''s throttling. Modern solutions use edge-based WebSocket gateways (e.g., Cloudflare Durable Objects, AWS API Gateway WebSocket).')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Your e-commerce site gets heavy traffic only on the homepage and product listing pages, but backend order-processing services sit idle most of the time. What architectural pattern solves this mismatch?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Microservices — split every service into a separate deployment unit so they scale independently"},{"id":"b","text":"Queue-based load leveling — place an asynchronous message queue (e.g., SQS) between the web tier and order-processing tier so each scales to its own pace"},{"id":"c","text":"Database sharding — partition the database by order date to speed up writes for peak traffic"},{"id":"d","text":"Horizontal scaling — always deploy 10x more backend servers than web servers to handle peak loads"}]','b','Queue-based load leveling decouples producers from consumers. The web tier drops orders into a queue as fast as they arrive; the processing tier pulls from the queue at its own pace — naturally absorbing spikes. This is the core of the producer-consumer pattern and is fundamental to event-driven architecture. It also provides back-pressure handling and message durability. Microservices (A) enable independent scaling but don''t alone solve producer-consumer mismatch. Sharding (C) is a database strategy. 10x overprovisioning (D) is wasteful and still doesn''t handle variance.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What does it mean for a service to be ''stateless,'' and why does it matter for horizontal scalability?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A stateless service does not use HTTP cookies; all client data is passed in request headers"},{"id":"b","text":"A stateless service does not store any per-request or per-session data between requests; all state is stored externally in shared storage — enabling any request to be handled by any server instance"},{"id":"c","text":"A stateless service is one that does not write to disk; it only processes data in memory"},{"id":"d","text":"Stateless services are faster because they do not maintain any database connections"}]','b','A stateless service treats each request as independent — no session state, no in-memory per-user data stored between requests. All state lives in external stores (Redis, database, shared storage). This enables horizontal scaling: any instance can handle any request, load balancers can distribute freely, and instances can be added or removed without breaking user sessions. Statelessness is a prerequisite for cloud-native, auto-scaling architectures. Option A confuses cookies with session state. Option C is about in-memory vs. disk. Option D is a mischaracterization.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Which consistency model allows stale reads in exchange for lower latency and higher availability?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Linearizability — all nodes agree on the order of operations, requiring synchronous coordination"},{"id":"b","text":"Causal consistency — operations that are causally related are seen by all nodes in order; unrelated operations may be seen in different orders"},{"id":"c","text":"Eventual consistency — updates propagate asynchronously; reads may return stale data, but all replicas eventually converge to the same value"},{"id":"d","text":"Strict consistency — every read sees the most recent write, with no exceptions"}]','c','Eventual consistency (EC) is an异步 replication model where writes are propagated to replicas in the background. Reads can return stale (out-of-date) results, but the system guarantees convergence once all writes have propagated. This enables low-latency local reads (especially in geo-distributed systems) and high availability during network partitions. DynamoDB, Cassandra, DNS, and many CDN caches use eventual consistency. Linearizability (A) and strict consistency (D) require synchronous coordination and sacrifice latency/availability. Causal consistency (B) is a middle ground between the two.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A global SaaS application stores user profile data in a database in us-east-1. Users in Asia experience 300ms+ latency for profile reads. What is the most effective way to reduce latency for global reads while keeping data reasonably consistent?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Compress all API responses with gzip to reduce transfer time over the transatlantic link"},{"id":"b","text":"Add read replicas in each geographic region and route read queries to the nearest replica; writes go to the primary — accepting eventual consistency for read replicas"},{"id":"c","text":"Upgrade the database server''s CPU and add SSDs to reduce query execution time locally"},{"id":"d","text":"Use a content delivery network (CDN) to cache user profile responses at the edge"}]','b','Geo-distributed read replicas are the standard solution for read-heavy, latency-sensitive workloads. The primary handles writes (single-master replication), while read replicas in each region serve low-latency reads. This sacrifices strong consistency for reads — cross-region reads may be slightly stale (eventual consistency) — which is acceptable for user profiles, dashboards, and most read-heavy use cases. Option A only reduces transfer time, not network latency. Option C doesn''t help remote users. Option D works for static assets, not dynamic personalized data.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: In the CAP theorem, a system can simultaneously guarantee all three properties — Consistency, Availability, and Partition Tolerance — when there is no network partition.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','The CAP theorem''s strict formulation says you can have at most two of three at any given time. In practice, the ''choice'' only matters during a partition. Without a partition, a system can be both consistent and available. However, some strict CAP formulations treat it as a property the system always exhibits — CP systems are always consistent and partition-tolerant but sacrifice availability during partitions, while AP systems are always available and partition-tolerant but sacrifice consistency during partitions. The nuance is that the impossibility result (choosing CA) applies only to the theoretical model, not to partition-free operation in practice.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: A system that uses synchronous (blocking) replication to all replicas will always be more consistent than one that uses asynchronous replication.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','true','Synchronous replication requires all replicas to confirm a write before acknowledging it to the client — guaranteeing that a successful write is visible to subsequent readers from any replica. Asynchronous replication acknowledges the write after it is accepted by the primary only, propagating to replicas in the background — meaning a reader on a replica might not yet see a recently acknowledged write. However, synchronous replication introduces latency (waiting for remote confirmations) and reduces availability if a replica is slow or unreachable. There is a real trade-off: stronger consistency comes at the cost of latency and fault tolerance.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: Sticky sessions (session affinity) are generally considered a best practice for scaling stateful web applications horizontally.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','Sticky sessions work around the symptom (lost in-memory session) rather than fixing the root cause (server-side session state). They create uneven load distribution (some servers accumulate more sessions), make it impossible to gracefully take a server offline, and do not survive server crashes. The industry best practice is to externalize session state to a shared distributed store (Redis, Memcached) and build stateless services. Sticky sessions are a legacy workaround, not a design goal.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Your team uses a health-check endpoint on each application server for load balancer routing decisions. Under high load, the health check passes but the server is so overloaded it takes 10+ seconds to respond to real requests. What happens and how do you fix it?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"The load balancer routes more traffic to the struggling server because its health check is still passing — causing a thundering herd. Fix: implement a passive health check that also monitors error rates or latency from the load balancer''s perspective"},{"id":"b","text":"The load balancer correctly routes traffic away from the slow server because the 10-second response triggers a timeout. No fix needed."},{"id":"c","text":"The load balancer automatically isolates the server after 3 consecutive slow health-check responses. Fix: reduce the health-check timeout threshold."},{"id":"d","text":"Active health checks cannot distinguish between a healthy slow server and a failing server. Fix: remove health checks entirely and use round-robin."}]','a','Active health checks (ping /health endpoint) only verify that the server is reachable and responding — they don''t measure actual request capacity. A server can pass a health check while being queued behind hundreds of slow requests. This causes the load balancer to continue sending traffic to an already overwhelmed server (thundering herd or ''misdirected trivia'' problem). Fixes: add a /ready endpoint that checks internal load (queue depth, thread pool, memory), configure the load balancer to also do passive health checks (track real request error rates/latency), and set circuit breakers at the load balancer. Option B is wrong (health checks often pass before timeout threshold). Option C requires specific LB config. Option D is dangerous.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Consistent hashing is used to distribute keys across nodes. What problem does it solve compared to naive modulo hashing, and why does adding virtual nodes (vnodes) improve distribution?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Consistent hashing solves the thundering herd problem during traffic spikes; virtual nodes randomize request routing to prevent hotspots"},{"id":"b","text":"Consistent hashing minimizes key remapping when nodes are added or removed; virtual nodes spread the keyspace owned by each physical node across multiple points on the hash ring, producing a more even load distribution"},{"id":"c","text":"Virtual nodes solve the CAP theorem trade-off by making every physical node appear as both CP and AP simultaneously"},{"id":"d","text":"Consistent hashing eliminates the need for a load balancer entirely; virtual nodes act as distributed health-check agents"}]','b','Naive modulo hashing (hash(key) % N) remaps virtually all keys when a node is added or removed, triggering a cache-miss or shard-remap storm. Consistent hashing maps keys and nodes onto a circular ring — only keys between the failed/added node and its neighbors are remapped. Virtual nodes assign multiple hash positions per physical node, smoothing out load imbalances caused by heterogeneous hardware or non-uniform key distributions. Used in: DynamoDB, Cassandra, Memcached, Redis Cluster. Option A misdescribes consistent hashing. Option C is false. Option D is unrelated.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','A system requires read-after-write consistency for user profile updates — a user who updates their profile should always see the new value immediately on the next page load. Which strategy best achieves this for a globally distributed read-heavy system?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Use eventual consistency with a 5-second propagation delay; most users won''t notice the delay"},{"id":"b","text":"After a write, route the same user''s subsequent reads to the primary (writer) region for a configurable time window; reads from other regions use replicas (session-level consistency)"},{"id":"c","text":"Disable read replicas globally and direct all traffic through the primary region — consistency is guaranteed by single-region routing"},{"id":"d","text":"Implement read-your-writes at the database level using synchronous multi-region replication with automatic failover"}]','b','Read-after-write consistency (also called read-your-writes) ensures a user immediately sees their own writes. The pragmatic global approach is to read from the primary (writer) region for a time window after a write (e.g., 30 seconds or until a sync marker), then fall back to replica reads elsewhere. This is session-level consistency — a middle ground between strong consistency (synchronous global replication, high latency) and eventual consistency (stale reads). Option A fails the read-after-write requirement. Option C sacrifices the performance benefit of geo-distributed replicas. Option D (synchronous multi-region) has extremely high write latency (satellite link delays). The pragmatic correct answer is B.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','True or False: Adding a load balancer in front of a microservice cluster always improves both performance and availability compared to not having one.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','A load balancer adds a single point of failure if not configured redundantly (active-passive HA pair). It also introduces a network hop (adding milliseconds of latency) and can become a bottleneck if undersized. For purely in-process communication within a Kubernetes cluster, a service mesh (e.g., Envoy sidecar) or client-side load balancing (Ribbon, Finagle) may be more appropriate than a centralized LB. The load balancer improves availability only when deployed in an HA configuration; it can degrade performance when used unnecessarily for internal service-to-service communication at high request rates.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','An auto-scaling policy triggers when average CPU across instances exceeds 80%. Under a sustained load increase, new instances spin up but the target group reports them unhealthy and they are terminated before taking traffic. What is the root cause likely to be?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"The health check endpoint is responding with HTTP 200 but the app is actually crashed — the LB is marking healthy instances as unhealthy"},{"id":"b","text":"The application requires a JVM warm-up period or dependency initialization (DB connections, caches) that happens after the process starts; the health check passes before the app is truly ready to serve traffic"},{"id":"c","text":"CPU usage spiked above 80% immediately, causing the auto-scaler to launch too many instances simultaneously, overwhelming the health check system"},{"id":"d","text":"The load balancer health check timeout is too short and is killing legitimate slow responses; fix: increase the timeout to 60 seconds"}]','b','This is the ''cold start'' or ''warm-up'' problem common with JVM-based, Spring Boot, and Node.js applications. The process starts, the HTTP server binds a port (health check passes), but the application is still initializing: establishing DB connection pools, warming caches, loading configuration. If the health check is /health instead of /ready, it passes before the app is truly capable of handling requests — causing the LB to route traffic to an unready instance, which fails, is marked unhealthy, and terminated. Fix: implement a /ready endpoint that checks internal readiness (DB connection, cache connectivity, thread pool state), configure the LB to use /ready as the health check, and add a startup delay or pre-warming strategy.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the fundamental difference between authentication and authorization in the context of API security?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Authentication and authorization are the same thing — both verify the user''s identity before granting access"},{"id":"b","text":"Authentication verifies WHO you are (identity proofing — username/password, OAuth token, SAML assertion); authorization verifies WHAT you are allowed to do (access control — permissions, roles, policies attached to your identity)"},{"id":"c","text":"Authorization verifies who you are; authentication determines what you can access"},{"id":"d","text":"Authentication is only relevant for human users; authorization is only relevant for machine-to-machine API calls"}]','b','Authentication (AuthN) answers: ''Are you who you claim to be?'' — proving identity via credentials, tokens, or certificates. Authorization (AuthZ) answers: ''What are you allowed to do?'' — enforcing access control rules (RBAC roles, ABAC policies, OAuth scopes). These are distinct concerns that are often confused. A user can be authenticated (logged in) but only authorized to read their own data, not delete other users'' data. Option A reverses both definitions. Option C reverses the order. Option D is false — both apply to all principals (human and machine).')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is a JWT (JSON Web Token), and what are its three main components?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"A JWT is an opaque token issued by OAuth2 servers; it contains only a session ID that references server-side session state"},{"id":"b","text":"A JWT is a self-contained, URL-safe token with three Base64URL-encoded parts separated by dots: Header (algorithm + token type), Payload (claims — user ID, roles, expiry), and Signature (HMAC or RSA signature verifying the payload integrity)"},{"id":"c","text":"A JWT is encrypted by default — anyone with the token can read the payload but cannot forge a valid token without the secret key"},{"id":"d","text":"A JWT''s payload is stored on the authorization server and only the session ID is transmitted to the client"}]','b','JWT (RFC 7519) is a compact, URL-safe token format: Header (alg, typ) → Base64URL(Payload) → Base64URL(Signature). The Payload contains claims: registered (iss, sub, aud, exp, nbf, iat, jti), public (defined by app), and private (agreed-upon custom claims). JWTs can be signed (JWS — HMAC or RSA/ECDSA) or encrypted (JWE). Unsigned/plaintext JWTs (alg=none) are a known exploit — always validate the algorithm and reject ''none''. JWTs are stateless (self-contained claims) but revocation requires a blocklist or short expiry. Option A describes an opaque session token. Option C overstates encryption — only JWE is encrypted; JWS is signed but payload is readable.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A JWT token is signed with HS256 (HMAC-SHA256) using a shared secret key. The server stores this secret key in the source code. What security vulnerability does this create, and what is the correct approach?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Storing the secret in source code is secure as long as the repository is private — no vulnerability exists"},{"id":"b","text":"Storing the secret in source code exposes it in version control history, CI/CD logs, and build artifacts even after removal; anyone with repo access can forge valid tokens — correct approach: use environment variables or a secrets manager (Vault, AWS Secrets Manager) injected at runtime, and rotate keys regularly"},{"id":"c","text":"HS256 is vulnerable to brute force attacks on the shared secret; use RS256 (asymmetric RSA) which cannot be brute forced"},{"id":"d","text":"The vulnerability is that JWTs are too small and can be easily intercepted — use larger tokens or encrypt the entire token body"}]','b','Embedding secrets in source code is a serious security anti-pattern: secrets in git history are there forever (even after removal), CI/CD logs expose them, Docker images contain them, and any developer or contractor with repo access can forge tokens. Best practices: (1) inject secrets at runtime via environment variables or secret injection sidecar (Vault Agent), (2) use asymmetric keys (RS256/ES256) where the server''s private key signs tokens and the public key is distributed to validators — the private key never needs to be on every service. Option A is false. Option C (RS256) is a good practice but not the primary fix for embedded secrets. Option D is unrelated.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the OAuth 2.0 Authorization Code flow, and why is it preferred over the Implicit flow for browser-based applications?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"The Authorization Code flow uses a 6-digit OTP code sent via SMS; the Implicit flow uses a hardware token — Authorization Code is preferred because OTPs are more secure than hardware tokens"},{"id":"b","text":"The Authorization Code flow exchanges an authorization code (obtained via browser redirect) for tokens at the backend — tokens never pass through the browser; the Implicit flow passes tokens directly through the URL fragment (visible in browser history, logs, referrer headers) — Authorization Code with PKCE is the secure choice for SPAs and mobile apps"},{"id":"c","text":"The Implicit flow is more secure than Authorization Code because it avoids an extra network round trip"},{"id":"d","text":"OAuth 2.0 Authorization Code and Implicit flows are equivalent — the only difference is the token format"}]','b','The Authorization Code flow: browser → authorization server → redirects back with authorization code → backend exchanges code + client_secret for tokens. Tokens never touch the browser URL or history. The Implicit flow (deprecated by OAuth 2.1): access token returned directly via URL fragment — visible in browser history, referrer headers, server logs, and browser extensions. This makes tokens highly susceptible to theft. Authorization Code + PKCE (Proof Key for Code Exchange) is the modern standard for SPAs (no client_secret needed since PKCE replaces it) and native apps. Option A is false. Option C reverses security. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is PKCE (Proof Key for Code Exchange) and why is it required for public clients (SPAs, mobile apps) in OAuth 2.0?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"PKCE is a 6-digit TOTP code that replaces the password during OAuth authentication for public clients"},{"id":"b","text":"PKCE is a cryptographically random code_verifier (created by the client) and its SHA256 hash (code_challenge) sent during authorization; when the authorization code is exchanged, the client must present the original code_verifier — preventing authorization code interception attacks where an attacker substitutes their own code"},{"id":"c","text":"PKCE is a fallback mechanism that allows OAuth clients to skip the client_secret verification step when the authorization server is unavailable"},{"id":"d","text":"PKCE is only needed for confidential clients (backend services); public clients do not need it"}]','b','PKCE (RFC 7636) addresses authorization code interception attacks (RFC 8252 for OAuth 2.0 for native apps). The attack: an attacker on the same network intercepts the authorization code from the redirect URL and exchanges it for tokens. PKCE prevention: client generates a random code_verifier, hashes it (SHA256) to create code_challenge, sends code_challenge with authorization request. When exchanging the code, the client must present the original code_verifier — an attacker with only the code cannot exchange it without knowing the verifier. PKCE is now required (OAuth 2.1) for ALL OAuth clients, not just public ones. Option A is false. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','Your public API is being abused by automated scripts sending thousands of requests per minute. What API security mechanism most directly addresses this abuse?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Rate limiting — limits the number of requests a client can make within a time window (e.g., 100 requests/minute per API key); exceeding clients receive 429 Too Many Requests — this protects against both accidental and malicious abuse"},{"id":"b","text":"Throttling — the API slows down responses to abusive clients rather than rejecting them"},{"id":"c","text":"IP allowlisting — block all traffic except from known IP addresses"},{"id":"d","text":"OAuth 2.0 authentication — requires all API clients to authenticate via OAuth, which inherently prevents abuse"}]','a','Rate limiting (also called quota management) is the direct mechanism for preventing API abuse. Implemented via: API gateway (Kong, AWS API Gateway), token bucket algorithm (refill rate + burst capacity), sliding window or fixed window counters per API key/client IP. HTTP 429 Too Many Requests is the standard response with Retry-After header. Rate limiting is distinct from: throttling (B) which degrades quality rather than blocking; IP allowlisting (C) which doesn''t scale; OAuth (D) which authenticates but doesn''t limit request volume. Option A is correct. Rate limiting should be combined with authentication for accountability.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the difference between encryption at rest and encryption in transit?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Encryption at rest protects data stored on disk (databases, files, backups) — using AES-256 at the storage or database layer; encryption in transit protects data moving over the network (TLS) — using TLS 1.2/1.3 to prevent eavesdropping and man-in-the-middle attacks"},{"id":"b","text":"Encryption at rest and encryption in transit are the same thing — both use TLS to protect data"},{"id":"c","text":"Encryption in transit is only needed for cross-datacenter replication; data within a single data center does not need encryption in transit"},{"id":"d","text":"Encryption at rest is sufficient for all security requirements — encryption in transit adds unnecessary latency with no security benefit"}]','a','Encryption at rest: protects stored data (AES-256 at file system level, volume encryption — AWS EBS, Azure Disk; database transparent data encryption — TDE; application-level field encryption). Required for: compliance (PCI-DSS, HIPAA, GDPR), protection against physical theft of storage, insider threats. Encryption in transit: protects data on the wire (TLS 1.3 preferred; avoid SSLv3/TLS 1.0/1.1). Required for: preventing eavesdropping, man-in-the-middle attacks, data in motion between services (internal mTLS). Both are required for defense-in-depth — encryption at rest protects stored data, encryption in transit protects data being used/processed. Option B is false. Option C is false. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the principle of least privilege in the context of API and microservice security, and why is it important?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Least privilege means giving every user an admin account so they can access everything they might need"},{"id":"b","text":"Least privilege means every principal (user, service, process) should have only the minimum permissions necessary to perform its task — no more; it limits blast radius when credentials are compromised and reduces the attack surface of the entire system"},{"id":"c","text":"Least privilege applies only to human users, not to machine-to-machine API calls or service accounts"},{"id":"d","text":"Least privilege is a compliance requirement for financial services only — it is optional for other industries"}]','b','Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP): grant minimum necessary permissions. For users: give only the permissions needed for their role (not admin by default). For services: use dedicated service accounts with scoped IAM roles (not root/admin credentials). For APIs: require scopes that match what the client actually needs — not full read/write access. If a microservice''s credentials are leaked, least privilege limits what an attacker can do with them. Example: a notification service should only have ''send message'' permission, not ''delete all users'' permission. Option A is the opposite. Option C is false. Option D is false — PoLP is a universal security principle.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','A web application stores user passwords. What is the correct approach to password storage, and why are plain-text or reversible encryption approaches wrong?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Store passwords encrypted with AES-256 — when a user logs in, decrypt the password and compare it to the login attempt"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a slow, salted key derivation function (Argon2id preferred, bcrypt, scrypt, or PBKDF2 with high work factor) to hash passwords; store only the hash; during login, hash the provided password and compare hashes — this makes brute-force attacks computationally expensive and useless if the database is leaked because the original password cannot be recovered from the hash"},{"id":"c","text":"Store passwords using MD5 hashing without salt — MD5 is fast and sufficient for password storage"},{"id":"d","text":"Store passwords in plain text and rely on HTTPS to protect them in transit — the database is trusted"}]','b','Password hashing: use a dedicated password hashing function (Argon2id > bcrypt > scrypt > PBKDF2) with a unique random salt per user and a high work factor (iterations/cost). Hashing (one-way) means the original cannot be recovered — critical for breach scenarios. Encryption (AES) is reversible — if the key is stolen or the DB is compromised, all passwords are recovered. MD5/SHA1 without salt are fast and vulnerable to rainbow tables and GPU brute force. The salt prevents precomputed rainbow table attacks. The work factor (cost/difficulty) makes brute-force attacks slow — Argon2id specifically resists GPU/ASIC attacks. Option A (encryption) is wrong. Option C (MD5) is wrong. Option D (plaintext) is dangerous.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is mutual TLS (mTLS) and when would you use it for service-to-service communication in a microservices architecture?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"mTLS is TLS where only the server presents a certificate — used for all public HTTPS endpoints"},{"id":"b","text":"mTLS is bidirectional TLS: both the client and the server present and validate each other''s X.509 certificates — used in microservices for service mesh mTLS (Istio, Linkerd) to encrypt and authenticate all service-to-service traffic within the cluster"},{"id":"c","text":"mTLS requires a centralized PKI (Certificate Authority) infrastructure to issue and rotate certificates; without a CA, mTLS cannot function"},{"id":"d","text":"mTLS and OAuth 2.0 are interchangeable — either can be used for service-to-service authentication and you should choose one"}]','b','Mutual TLS (mTLS): both client and server authenticate each other via X.509 certificates. In a service mesh (Istio, Linkerd), mTLS is enforced transparently via sidecar proxies — certificates are provisioned and rotated automatically by the mesh control plane (SPIFFE/SPIRE). mTLS provides: (1) encryption in transit, (2) service identity verification (no unauthorized services can call a service), (3) audit trail of which services communicated. Unlike OAuth (D) which is identity-based (user/service principal), mTLS is transport-layer authentication — it verifies the cryptographic identity of the process/container, not the principal''s access rights. Option A describes standard TLS (server-only). Option C is correct (requires CA) but Option B is the best answer. Option D is false — they serve different purposes.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','What is the purpose of an API key in API security, and what are its limitations compared to OAuth 2.0 tokens?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"API keys provide the same security as OAuth tokens and are preferred for all API authentication scenarios"},{"id":"b","text":"API keys identify the calling application (which client is making the request) and can enforce rate limits per client; they do not inherently identify the user, carry authorization scopes, or expire automatically — OAuth tokens carry identity, scopes, and are time-limited; use API keys for server-to-server authentication where the client is a known application; use OAuth for user-delegated access"},{"id":"c","text":"API keys are encrypted JWTs with built-in expiration; they are more secure than OAuth tokens"},{"id":"d","text":"API keys should be stored in source code alongside the application logic for easy access"}]','b','API keys identify the project/application (not the user) and are useful for: rate limiting, analytics, and blocking abused keys. Limitations: they don''t carry user context (a key represents a project, not a person), they don''t encode scopes or permissions, they don''t expire automatically (unless you implement rotation), and revoking a key requires regenerating it and updating all clients. OAuth tokens (access tokens, JWTs) carry identity (sub claim), scopes (what the token allows), and have short expiry. API keys are appropriate for server-to-server (M2M) API access where the client is a known application. Option A is false. Option C is false. Option D is a security anti-pattern.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: A JWT with a valid signature from a trusted issuer (iss claim) is sufficient to trust the claims in the payload without additional validation.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','Validating only the signature is insufficient. A JWT with a valid signature from a trusted key can still be invalid because: (1) expiry (exp claim) may have passed — always check exp against current time; (2) not-before (nbf) may not yet be valid; (3) audience (aud) may not match your service; (4) issuer (iss) may be trusted but the token was issued for a different client (scope/audience mismatch). Always validate: signature, algorithm (reject alg=none), expiry, not-before, audience, and issuer. A token from a trusted issuer but with wrong audience or expired timestamp can grant unintended access. This is a common JWT security mistake.')
,(NULL,'MIDDLE','True or False: HTTPS (TLS) automatically encrypts all data stored in cookies — if an attacker gains access to the cookie file on the user''s device, the cookie data remains protected.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','HTTPS/TLS only encrypts data in transit — data stored in cookies on the filesystem/disk is NOT encrypted by TLS. If an attacker gains access to the device (malware, stolen device, physical access), they can read all cookies from the cookie file. To protect cookies at rest: use the Secure flag (cookie only sent over HTTPS), HttpOnly flag (prevents JavaScript access — mitigates XSS), SameSite=Strict/Lax (CSRF protection), and for highly sensitive data (tokens), encrypt the cookie value at the application layer (encrypt-then-MAC) or store in a server-side session with an opaque session ID in the cookie.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','You are designing an API access control system for a SaaS application with multiple tenants. A tenant''s admin should only be able to manage users within their own organization. How do you implement fine-grained access control that scales across many tenants and roles?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Use a static admin password for each tenant — admins use the same password as their organization''s shared credentials"},{"id":"b","text":"Use RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) with tenant-scoped roles: the user''s JWT contains their tenant_id claim and role; the authorization layer checks both that the requested resource''s tenant_id matches the user''s tenant_id AND that their role grants the required permission — preventing cross-tenant access even if a user has an admin role"},{"id":"c","text":"Store all tenant data in the same database table without tenant isolation and rely on application-level filtering — this is simpler and equally secure"},{"id":"d","text":"Use IP-based access control: only allow access from IPs within each tenant''s corporate network"}]','b','Multi-tenant RBAC with tenant scoping: user''s JWT carries tenant_id + role claims. On every request, the authorization layer must: (1) verify the resource''s tenant_id matches the user''s tenant_id (not just their role), (2) verify the role grants the requested permission. Without tenant_id checks, a ''super-admin'' role from one tenant could access another tenant''s resources — a classic multi-tenant authorization bypass vulnerability. ABAC (Attribute-Based Access Control) extends this with resource attributes (owner, sensitivity level) for more fine-grained policies. Option A (shared password) is insecure and unaccountable. Option C creates cross-tenant data leakage risk. Option D (IP-based) is brittle and spoofable.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','An attacker exploits an SQL injection vulnerability in a user input field to extract the entire user database including password hashes. What security controls would have prevented this, and what post-breach actions are necessary?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"SQL injection is prevented by using Web Application Firewall (WAF) rules — no code changes are necessary"},{"id":"b","text":"Prevention: parameterized queries / prepared statements (never concatenate user input into SQL); input validation (allowlists); least privilege DB user (app can''t DROP tables); output encoding for reflected XSS. Post-breach: incident response plan, breach notification (GDPR 72h), password reset force, audit logs, rotate all credentials that may have been exposed, assume passwords are compromised even if hashed — force reset and notify affected users"},{"id":"c","text":"If passwords are hashed with bcrypt/Argon2id, no further action is needed — hashed passwords cannot be reversed"},{"id":"d","text":"SQL injection can only be prevented by migrating from SQL databases to NoSQL databases"}]','b','SQL injection prevention: parameterized queries (the #1 defense — user input is treated as data, not SQL), input validation (whitelisting over blacklisting), least privilege DB accounts (app shouldn''t have DDL rights), ORM usage with proper configuration. WAF (A) is a defense layer but not a substitute for secure coding. Post-breach: (1) incident response (contain, eradicate, recover), (2) GDPR breach notification within 72 hours if EU residents affected, (3) force password reset for affected users, (4) rotate all credentials that could have been exposed, (5) notify affected users, (6) perform root cause analysis. Option C is false — even strong hashes can be brute-forced for weak passwords. Option D is false.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','Your microservices use OAuth 2.0 Access Tokens to authenticate and authorize requests. The access token has a 1-hour expiry. How do you handle token refresh without disrupting users, and what are the security trade-offs?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Issue a new access token with a 24-hour expiry every time the old token expires — the client must re-authenticate to get the new token"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a Refresh Token: the authorization server issues a short-lived access token (1 hour) and a long-lived refresh token (e.g., 7 days); when the access token expires, the client silently exchanges the refresh token for a new access token — no user interaction needed; trade-offs: refresh tokens must be stored securely (HttpOnly cookie or secure storage), must be revocable, and a stolen refresh token enables long-term unauthorized access if not detected"},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the access token expiry to 365 days — this eliminates the need for refresh tokens and is equally secure"},{"id":"d","text":"Use the same access token indefinitely without expiry — expiry only creates unnecessary complexity"}]','b','Refresh token flow: client stores a long-lived refresh token (in HttpOnly cookie or secure storage), uses it to silently obtain new access tokens before or after expiry. Benefits: good UX (no re-login), short-lived access tokens limit exposure (stolen token only valid for its lifetime). Security trade-offs: (1) refresh tokens are high-value targets — store in HttpOnly cookies to prevent XSS theft; (2) must be revocable (server maintains a token registry or blocklist); (3) stolen refresh token = long-term access — implement anomaly detection (new device/location = revoke and alert); (4) rotation: rotate refresh token on each use (refresh token rotation) — if an old token is used twice, it indicates theft and all tokens are revoked. Option C (365-day tokens) are dangerous — long-lived tokens are high-value theft targets. Option D is catastrophic.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','You need to implement API security for a financial transaction API where sensitive data (account numbers, transaction amounts) must be protected even from internal employees who have database access. What additional security layer is required?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Encryption at rest on the database is sufficient — internal employees can be trusted not to abuse their database access"},{"id":"b","text":"Use field-level encryption (FLE) or tokenization: sensitive fields are encrypted at the application layer before being sent to the database — the database stores ciphertext only; decryption keys are stored in a separate key management service (KMS) — even DBAs with full table access cannot read sensitive fields without the key"},{"id":"c","text":"Use RBAC to restrict which employees can access the financial tables — this is sufficient to protect sensitive data"},{"id":"d","text":"Store all financial data in a separate database that is only accessible via stored procedures — this eliminates the need for application-layer encryption"}]','b','Defense-in-depth for sensitive data: field-level encryption (FLE) or tokenization. FLE: encrypt sensitive fields (credit card numbers, SSN, account numbers) in the application layer before sending to the database — the database stores ciphertext that is meaningless without the key. The KMS (AWS KMS, HashiCorp Vault) manages keys separately from data. Tokenization: replace sensitive values with non-sensitive tokens (PCI-DSS tokenization model). This protects against: insider threat (DBAs, cloud operators), SQL injection (attacker reads ciphertext, not plaintext), and database backups theft. RBAC (C) helps but doesn''t prevent authorized DBAs from reading data. Stored procedures (D) still allow SELECT access to data. Option B is the correct answer.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','An API gateway sits in front of your microservices. A client''s API key is compromised (leaked in a public repository). What happens when you revoke the key, and how quickly can you mitigate the risk?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Revoking the key takes effect immediately — all subsequent requests using the revoked key are rejected within seconds by the API gateway"},{"id":"b","text":"Revocation timing depends on caching: if the gateway caches key validation results, a revoked key may remain valid until the cache expires (minutes to hours); to achieve fast revocation: cache revocation events in Redis/blocklist with short TTL, use a live validation endpoint (not cached), or use short-lived JWTs (minutes) instead of long-lived API keys"},{"id":"c","text":"API keys cannot be revoked — once issued, they remain valid until their natural expiry date"},{"id":"d","text":"Revoking the key requires regenerating the entire API gateway configuration and redeploying — this takes hours"}]','b','API key revocation is not instantaneous by default: if the gateway caches the result of ''is this key valid?'' lookups, a revoked key may continue to work until the cache TTL expires. Mitigation strategies: (1) maintain a revocation blocklist (Redis set) checked on every request, with the blocklist updated immediately on revocation; (2) use short TTL for key validation cache (e.g., 60 seconds); (3) for high-security scenarios, validate keys against the authorization server on every request (no cache) or use short-lived JWTs instead of long-lived API keys. Option A overstates immediacy. Option C is false for most implementations. Option D is unnecessarily slow with proper architecture.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','True or False: Using HTTPS for all API calls is sufficient to protect against all common API security threats including injection attacks, unauthorized access, and data exposure.','TRUE_FALSE','[]','false','HTTPS (TLS) only encrypts data in transit — it protects against eavesdropping and man-in-the-middle attacks on the network. It does NOT protect against: SQL injection (malicious input reaches the application), broken authentication (stolen credentials or tokens), broken authorization (IDOR — accessing other users'' resources), excessive data exposure (API returns too much data including sensitive fields), rate limiting abuse, XSS (stored scripts served over HTTPS), or insider threats. HTTPS is a necessary but not sufficient security control — it is the transport layer, not the application security layer. Defense-in-depth requires: authentication, authorization, input validation, output encoding, rate limiting, field-level encryption, and security monitoring.')
,(NULL,'SENIOR','A microservices system uses service account credentials (long-lived API keys) stored as Kubernetes Secrets to authenticate service-to-service calls. These secrets are base64-encoded in etcd. What is the security risk, and what is the correct mitigation?','MULTIPLE_CHOICE','[{"id":"a","text":"Base64 encoding is encryption — Kubernetes Secrets stored in etcd are secure and no further action is needed"},{"id":"b","text":"Base64 encoding is not encryption — it provides zero confidentiality. Anyone with access to etcd (cluster admin, cloud provider) can read the secrets. Mitigations: enable Kubernetes encryption at rest (AES-CBC or AES-GCM secret encryption config), use an external secrets manager (HashiCorp Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, Azure Key Vault) with the Kubernetes External Secrets Operator, or use Istio SPIFFE/SPIRE to issue short-lived X.509 certificates instead of long-lived API keys"},{"id":"c","text":"Store secrets in Kubernetes ConfigMaps instead of Secrets — ConfigMaps are encrypted by default"},{"id":"d","text":"The risk is minimal — Kubernetes cluster access is already restricted to authorized administrators"}]','b','Kubernetes Secrets are base64-encoded (not encrypted) by default — they are stored in plaintext in etcd and visible in pod environment variables and logs. Anyone with etcd read access, or who can exec into a pod, can read secret values. Mitigations: (1) enable Kubernetes Secret Encryption at Rest (encrypting etcd data with a KMS-encrypted key — not default), (2) use an External Secrets Operator to sync secrets from Vault/AWS Secrets Manager into Kubernetes Secrets at runtime — the secret value never lives in etcd, (3) use SPIFFE/SPIRE to issue short-lived X.509 certificates for service-to-service mTLS instead of long-lived API keys — certificates are automatically rotated, limiting exposure window. Option A is false. Option C is false (ConfigMaps are not encrypted by default). Option D underestimates the insider threat.');
